K \\l "toc45"}}{\fldrslt{\fs20\cf2\par\bullet\tab \uc2  EXPLOITATION OF AREA'S IMMIGRANTS IS SHAMEFUL}}}\page {\par\fs20\uc2 THE CAP TIMES\par {\*\bkmkstart toc0}{\*\bkmkend toc0}\b \uc2 SANFELIPPO IS THE WISCONSIN LEGISLATURE'S HUMAN WRECKING BALL\b0\par\par\uc2 Dave Zweifel \par \uc2 658 \uc2 words\par \uc2 25 March 2020\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par 30\par \uc2 ISSN:07494068\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2020 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Now that the Wisconsin Legislature appears to have gone home for the year, I want to bestow an award to the legislator who went beyond the call of duty this past session to gum up the works - state Rep. Joe Sanfelippo, the Republican from West Allis.\par \par \uc2 It wouldn't surprise any observer of state politics if Sanfelippo set some modern-day record for being a human wrecking ball, sabotaging public interest legislation by inserting his own biases and skewed political agenda at just the right moment.\par \par \uc2 A skilled bomb thrower is he.\par \par \uc2 The prime example is what he did to the bipartisan bill aimed at preventing future backlogs of sexual assault kit testing. The measure had been authored by a bipartisan health care coalition to create the first statutory guidelines on how to process sexual assault kits, which can contain evidence that is crucial to finding sexual predators or freeing the wrongly convicted.\par \par \uc2 It was aimed a preventing another backlog like the one just a few years ago that saw the kits go untested for months and even years, a situation that denied justice for survivors of sexual assault by letting the attackers go free. Under the bill, hospitals and others collecting evidence for the kits would be required to immediately send them to the State Crime Lab for testing.\par \par \uc2 It was passed by the state Senate with ease, but when it came over to the Assembly, Sanfelippo didn't care about justice delayed or even denied. As chair of the Assembly's Committee on Health, he refused to call a public hearing on a bill that most regarded as good legislation. And then as the session neared its end, he found all sorts of problems with the bill and decided to insert an amendment to pander to his conservative constituency.\par \par \uc2 He decided that the bill should include a requirement that student rape victims be immediately eligible to attend a voucher school and one to require law enforcement to notify ICE if the test results point to an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 . When Assembly Speaker \uc2 Robin Vos\uc2  decided to go along with Sanfelippo, which he regularly does, it effectively killed the bill for this session.\par \par \uc2 Not only did it now contain provisions that many Democrats didn't like, it would have to be sent back to the Senate for another vote. The result in the end was nothing passed. Rape kit procedures will have to wait another year. Thanks a lot, Joe.\par \par \uc2 But, this is modus operandi for Sanfelippo.\par \par \uc2 Last month, the West Allis Republican succeeded in scuttling a common-sense bill that he had, in fact, originally backed, to allow direct primary care clinics to operate more freely in Wisconsin. The bill included a strict anti-discrimination clause. But, at the last minute, Sanfelippo introduced an amendment that removed sexual orientation, national origin and ancestry from the language, once again thwarting any bipartisan agreement.\par \par \uc2 Sanfelippo's action sparked charges by state Sen. Tim Carpenter, an openly gay legislator from Milwaukee, that the new language amounted to bigotry. It passed the GOP-controlled Assembly and Senate anyhow, but not without rancor sparked by our favorite guy from West Allis.\par \par \uc2 But Joe's handiwork pops up all over the place, whether it's to ridicule gun safety efforts, fight criminal reform legislation to help reduce the prison population and, hence, taxpayers' costs, or push efforts to take local control away from Milwaukee, his favorite punching bag.\par \par \uc2 And to show you how much of a nice guy and team player he is, Sanfelippo didn't have a nice thing to say about fellow Republican, state Sen. Luther Olsen, who announced he's retiring after 25 years in the Legislature.\par \par \uc2 He was "one of the biggest roadblocks to school reform and accountability in the Legislature," snarled Joe. Apparently, Olsen didn't believe in throwing bombs.\par \par \uc2 CREDIT: By Dave Zweifel\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020200326eg3p00004\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 LOCAL\par {\*\bkmkstart toc1}{\*\bkmkend toc1}\b \uc2 VICTIM ADVOCATES SAY GOP STALLING; LEGISLATURE | SEXUAL-ASSAULT KITS\b0\par\par\uc2 RILEY VETTERKIND \par \uc2 739 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 February 2020\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par A.3\par \uc2 ISSN:0749405X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2020 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Democrats made a last-minute push on Wednesday for a bill that would seek to prevent backlogs of sexual-assault kits as sexual-assault victims and prosecutors blasted Republican lawmakers for putting up roadblocks to the bill's passage.\par \par \uc2 Democratic Attorney General \uc2 Josh Kaul\uc2  and a coalition of sexual-assault victim advocates called on Assembly Republicans to take up and pass a bill introduced more than eight months ago that would create the first statutory guidelines for how to process sexual-assault kits, which could help preserve physical evidence to aid in prosecution. The Senate passed the bill, but the effort has stalled in the Assembly.\par \par \uc2 Assembly Republicans have declined to advance the bill supported by criminal justice professionals and instead have moved in a different direction, opting to introduce legislation that includes many of the same measures Kaul and Democrats want, but with added controversial provisions related to private-school vouchers and immigration that Democrats reject, putting the entire effort in peril.\par \par \uc2 A spokeswoman for Democratic \uc2 Gov. Tony Evers\uc2  said Republicans "are now putting on a pretty gross and disappointing political display."\par \par \uc2 Advocates accused Republicans of playing politics with people's lives.\par \par \uc2 "This is how you kill a bill," said Ilse Knecht, director of policy and advocacy for the New York-based Joyful Heart Foundation, a sexual-assault victim advocacy group. "We've been involved in reform laws across the country, and I will tell you I have never experienced party politics being injected into this issue in this way."\par \par \uc2 Steffen's revision\par \par \uc2 Last Thursday, Rep. David Steffen, R-Green Bay, who introduced bipartisan sexual-assault kit legislation alongside Democratic Attorney General \uc2 Josh Kaul\uc2  last year, came out with the new bill to give his fellow Republicans another option to consider as the end of the legislative session nears. During a hearing on the bill Wednesday, Steffen explained he introduced the new bill to ensure more GOP support. He said the change was meant to secure at least 50 votes within the Republican caucus before moving a bill to the floor.\par \par \uc2 The bill's introduction came after Rep. Joe Sanfelippo, chairman of the committee tasked with advancing the bipartisan legislation, expressed opposition to Steffen's first bill and wouldn't commit to a public hearing. That bill, which has widespread bipartisan support, would create statutory requirements for who should collect and store sexual-assault kits, and when.\par \par \uc2 Sanfelippo, R-New Berlin, provided a number of objections to the bill, chiefly that it adds more regulation without doing enough to prevent future backlogs. Kaul said such criticisms were unfounded and that the bill makes great strides in mandating law-enforcement agencies comply with new requirements.\par \par \uc2 Sanfelippo said he supports the new bill, which also would create timelines for collecting and storing sexual-assault kits but creates more compressed requirements in some areas.\par \par \uc2 Kaul said he had several issues with the bill.\par \par \uc2 "This bill is a mess and the Legislature should vote it down," Kaul said.\par \par \uc2 Republicans said the private-school voucher provision aims to allow children who are sexually assaulted to leave the school where they may have been victimized. Steffen said a provision requiring authorities to report immigrants in the country illegally was meant to protect \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  women by creating a new deterrent for sexual predators. Kaul also took issue with the bill for mandating a sexual-assault kit tracking program without providing funding for it.\par \par \uc2 'Do your job'\par \par \uc2 Veronica Figueroa, executive director of Unidos, a group combating domestic violence and sexual assault, said the immigration and voucher provisions don't belong in the bill. She said the immigration measures do little to prevent sexual assault because perpetrators who are deported can find their way back to the United States.\par \par \uc2 "We put you in that seat," Figueroa told committee lawmakers. "Do your job and support your communities and stop playing with the lives of survivors."\par \par \uc2 Jacqueline Jaske, an advocate and survivor of sexual assault, criticized Republicans for employing what she called stall tactics to prevent a bill from moving forward.\par \par \uc2 "All of these messages tell victims that they don't matter," Jaske said. "This isn't a political issue for me. I considered myself a Republican and I cannot support this solely Republican bill or the politics replacing victims' rights for justice with a win for their team."\par \par \uc2 CREDIT: RILEY VETTERKIND rvetterkind@madison.com\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020200207eg260000a\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 OPINION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc2}{\*\bkmkend toc2}\b \uc2 YOUR VIEWS\b0\par\par\uc2 986 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 April 2019\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par A.9\par \uc2 ISSN:0749405X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2019 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Sales tax could pay to fix roads\par \par \uc2 Regarding Wednesday's State Journal editorial, "Don't stall fix to crumbling state roads": It's too bad the people who are suppose to be running the show down in Madison don't use a little common sense to fix our roads. The politicians talk about it a lot and come back with the same old answers that have not worked.\par \par \uc2 A possible solution I have presented to a couple of my representatives from the Portage area is to raise the state sales tax by 1%. This would be used solely for the repair and maintenance of our state roads. This 1% could not be used for any other purpose.\par \par \uc2 Why should the drivers be the only ones to pay for maintenance? Shouldn't everyone pay to repair our roads? Some people may not have a driver's license, but they use the roads. I don't think a 1% increase is going to break anyone. Do you? I myself would rather pay 1% more in sales tax than 8 cents in gas taxes.\par \par \uc2 Robert G. "Bob" Beahm, Portage\par \par \uc2 Medical marijuana can save lives\par \par \uc2 Forty years ago, I was a newly hired employee of a manufacturer in the Detroit area.\par \par \uc2 On one occasion, I was meeting with the company warehouse manager. While talking with him, I could see he was not feeling well. He told me he was taking chemotherapy for a treatable cancer, but the treatment was making him nauseous. The doctor prescribed anti-nausea, narcotic medication, but it was making him tired and confused.\par \par \uc2 I quietly asked him if he had tried smoking some marijuana to relieve the nausea. He had never tried marijuana, but his situation made him desperate. I told him I might know someone who could help. A few phone calls later, I got him a small bag of pot. I got him a small pipe and explained the process.\par \par \uc2 Several weeks later, I was walking through the warehouse. I saw the manager running toward me. I thought I was in trouble. He ran up to me with tears in his eyes and hugged me. He said I had saved him. He told me he had contemplated suicide.\par \par \uc2 The marijuana had eased the nausea, allowing him to eat normally. It was a good day.\par \par \uc2 Bruce Longfield, Middleton\par \par \uc2 Don't fall for toll road scam\par \par \uc2 Some of our politicians are pushing for toll roads in Wisconsin.\par \par \uc2 Our roads need repairs, but the last thing we need is toll roads. They are just another scam to get your money. The toll roads will be under construction constantly (as a way to convince you to pay more), so you won't be flying from point A to point B.\par \par \uc2 They will probably be sold and resold to private corporations, and the tolls will always be rising. For example, Indiana's tollway belongs to an Australian corporation. Then you'll be forced to buy a toll pass. If you don't, you'll be waiting to pay at the one open "cash" booth for 5 minutes. They'll punish you.\par \par \uc2 Take a trip from the Wisconsin border to Chicago on I-90 and you'll see how much in tolls it will cost you just to drive on the road. You'll be in shock. Only a few cents from each dollar with actually go to the roads.\par \par \uc2 Don't fall for it.\par \par \uc2 Jerzy Matian, Mauston\par \par \uc2 Trump shouldn't get another term\par \par \uc2 Why should we give \uc2 Donald Trump\uc2  four more years as president? All he does is think about his wall and watch television for hours at a time when he is supposed to be working. And some people want to have him as president four more years?\par \par \uc2 In any business, if an employee did that he would be fired and not rewarded as President Trump wants voters to do. It is time for his base to put their thinking caps on. What if North Korea threatened us with nuclear war? Would you trust President Trump to handle such a situation? Does he know what to do?\par \par \uc2 A man who watches television most of his day and doesn't read books does not have the intelligence and work ethic needed to be president.\par \par \uc2 He even was a poor businessman. He went bankrupt six times, and most banks refused to lend him anymore money. And we should give him four more years as president? That is a ridiculous idea.\par \par \uc2 Diana Vance, Monroe\par \par \uc2 Critics can focus on their districts\par \par \uc2 On April 7, the State Journal the published the letter "All-female School Board isn't diverse," bad-mouthing Madison public schools. On April 8, it published another letter, "Teachers need to be respected," doing the same.\par \par \uc2 Interestingly, the author of the first letter is from Oshkosh and the author of the second letter is from Windsor - neither of which are within the bounds of the Madison School District. On Election Day, several thousand people who really do live in the Madison School District and have financial and personal stakes in the district went to the polls and made their wishes quite clear.\par \par \uc2 Backseat driving can be a lot of fun if you have no stake in the results. Maybe it's time these letters writers offer their educational expertise to the school districts where they actually live.\par \par \uc2 Michael Reichert, Madison\par \par \uc2 Only legal residents deserve licenses\par \par \uc2 If you hold the coat of someone who is committing a crime, wouldn't you be considered aiding and abetting that crime?\par \par \uc2 How can you justify giving an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  a legal Wisconsin driver's license. It makes absolutely no sense to me. Don't tell me the streets will be safer.\par \par \uc2 So in their infinite wisdom, our lawmakers are considering giving illegal immigrants the coveted driver's license? To paraphrase Dilbert, "We allow the idiots to make decisions."\par \par \uc2 Ralph Trentadue, Madison\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020190416ef4f00009\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc3}{\*\bkmkend toc3}\b \uc2 YOUR VIEWS\b0\par\par\uc2 909 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 March 2019\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par A.11\par \uc2 ISSN:0749405X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2019 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Nonresidents need tuition freeze, too\par \par \uc2 I agree with some of the arguments in the recent Wisconsin State Journal editorial "Keep tuition freeze, boost funding for \uc2 UW System\uc2 ." Yet I would like to see some changes made to the tuition freeze.\par \par \uc2 I support \uc2 Gov. Tony Evers\uc2 ' proposal to continue the in-state tuition freeze for UW students. Being a resident of Wisconsin attending UW, I am grateful that I can afford my tuition without going into debt.\par \par \uc2 But nonresident students don't have it as nice as I do. Most of my friends live out of state and are struggling with the amount of loans needed to achieve a degree.\par \par \uc2 It was recently announced that their tuition - which is already $36,805 without housing, meals, and books included - is increasing next year. Giving out-of-state students a tuition freeze or reduction would potentially lead to a more inviting university and could bring in more diversity to a predominantly white campus.\par \par \uc2 Gov. Evers should fight aggressively for his proposal to freeze tuition for in-state students but amend it to include out-of-state students to create a more inviting and diverse university.\par \par \uc2 Karissa Niederkorn, Madison\par \par \uc2 Trump is acting more like a dictator\par \par \uc2 In 1943, when I became 18, I Joined the Army and was trained as an infantryman. After training, I was sent to Burma in a ranger regiment. I spent nearly a year fighting the Japanese through the jungles and mountains of Burma.\par \par \uc2 We fought to save our democratic way of life. That way of life includes a democratically elected government and Congress, which passes laws, and an executive who carries out those laws.\par \par \uc2 In less than two years as president, \uc2 Donald Trump\uc2  has become a dictator. He ignores the Constitution. He lacks political knowledge, so he makes poor decisions. He ignores advice from his government experts, but naively believes foreign officials and enemies. He is ignorant, incompetent, moody and cannot stand anyone who disagrees with him.\par \par \uc2 If he is not impeached by 2020, his supporters must join those of us who voted against him to remove him from office. At age 94, I cannot march or protest, but I am working on living long enough to vote against him in 2020.\par \par \uc2 Richard Bates, Baraboo\par \par \uc2 Stop the wildlife killing contests\par \par \uc2 For over 30 years I was a high school biology teacher, after which I retired to northern Wisconsin.\par \par \uc2 Recently, I became aware of people who try to kill as many animals as they can in the name of entertainment for prizes. One such event targeting coyotes was held near Tomahawk in January.\par \par \uc2 In my younger years, I did my share of hunting, but this practice goes against what my father taught me and what I taught my kids. It gives hunters a bad name and shows a lack of respect for the animals killed.\par \par \uc2 My grandkids come to visit me often, but I know neither they nor I will forget the time we saw a bobcat in the yard, or the summer the fox had a den near our house. We feel privileged to be able to see these animals. To think of someone viewing them only as a number makes me very sad for the state of affairs for wildlife here in Wisconsin.\par \par \uc2 I encourage everyone that feels the same way to contact their state legislators (I've already called mine, Sen. Tom Tiffany, R-Minocqua) and urge them to support Senate Bill 30, which would ban these contests.\par \par \uc2 Ronald Youngbauer, Boulder Junction\par \par \uc2 National Guard is needed at border\par \par \uc2 I disagree with \uc2 Gov. Tony Evers\uc2 ' decision to remove the 112 Wisconsin National Guard members who were protecting the U.S. border.\par \par \uc2 Legal immigrants are allowed to seek American citizenship. My wife applied for a green card to become an American. This is a slow and expensive process, but good for the country. It took us two years.\par \par \uc2 She underwent medical exams to prove she was free of communicable diseases. She suffered through numerous immunization injections.\par \par \uc2 How many Wisconsinites will be infected with diseases carried by illegal immigrants? Does Gov. Evers care?\par \par \uc2 My wife, her mother, father, sister and son were investigated. She answered questions about jobs, memberships and political affiliation. We endured four Homeland Security interviews.\par \par \uc2 How many drug dealers, gang members and criminals will sneak into America without being investigated?\par \par \uc2 Most drugs come in at points of entry, but some people also carry drugs across the border. Guard members stopped one \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  with 70 pounds of methamphetamine. How many Americans will be injured by the drugs they bring? Does Gov. Evers care?\par \par \uc2 It is unconscionable to remove Wisconsin troops from the border. If Gov. Evers cared about the health, safety or welfare of Wisconsin voters, he would let our troops continue to protect the border.\par \par \uc2 Jim Meitner, Neshkoro\par \par \uc2 Make daylight saving the rule\par \par \uc2 This is in response to a recent letter to the editor "Daylight saving time should end." It called for an end to daylight saving time and to make standard time permanent.\par \par \uc2 What needs to be done is an end to standard time and make daylight saving time permanent. I agree changing the time twice per year is a hassle.\par \par \uc2 We need the extra hour of daylight in the late afternoon in the winter when virtually everyone is up and about rather than in the early morning, when at least half are not up and about yet.\par \par \uc2 Dave Searles, Brodhead\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020190305ef3400036\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 OPINION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc4}{\*\bkmkend toc4}\b \uc2 YOUR VIEWS\b0\par\par\uc2 855 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 August 2018\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par A.11\par \uc2 ISSN:0749405X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2018 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Goldberg doesn't understand racism\par \par \uc2 Regarding Jonah Goldberg's Wednesday column, "The left shouldn't attempt to redefine what racism is," racism can have two definitions Goldberg's and the left's.\par \par \uc2 Goldberg's definition of racism is there isn't any logical and apparent difference between haters. There is only one definition of hate. He mocks the left's definition of racism as it relates to power. But what power means is that white haters have power to implement their hatred.\par \par \uc2 They can systematically inflict harm such as deprivation, discrimination and unfair treatment on minority populations. Minorities who hate have no such power to inflict harm on white people.\par \par \uc2 Myrna Sokolinsky, Madison\par \par \uc2 Man can't stop the forces of nature\par \par \uc2 In the last week or so have you noticed the beautiful red sunsets, haze in the atmosphere and the smell of smoke in the air?\par \par \uc2 This is the result of man-made pollution. It is the result the western forest fires.\par \par \uc2 A fire in Colorado was set on purpose and the suspect is an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  from Denmark. Homes have been destroyed, millions of dollars have been spent and lives have been lost.\par \par \uc2 The pollution factor over the northern states, and damage to the environment is significant.\par \par \uc2 Let's see what the climate change supporters are going to do about this. Here is your chance to control a pollution event. Are you going to protest?\par \par \uc2 Help fight the forest fires? March on Washington? Tax the man who started it? What?\par \par \uc2 This is currently impacting air quality, forest ecology, private and government property and endangering the lives of wildlife, pets and humans and you can do nothing. These tragic events are much too big for we humans to really stop.\par \par \uc2 Just like tornadoes, hurricanes, earthquakes and volcanic eruptions, wild stuff happens.\par \par \uc2 We try to survive.\par \par \uc2 John H. Pickle Jr., Lodi\par \par \uc2 GOP made failed policies of the past\par \par \uc2 With predictability, Republican congressional candidate Bryan Steil said that if Democrat Randy Bryce is elected in the 1st Congressional District we would return to the failed policies of the past.\par \par \uc2 Which failed policies are those? For much of the last 50 years we have had Republican administrations cutting taxes and regulations. Each time that has set the stage for a recession.\par \par \uc2 These administrations all increased the debt. Or maybe Steil is referring to the Great Society programs that allowed his former boss, House Speaker \uc2 Paul Ryan\uc2 , R-Janesville, to attend college on expanded Social Security benefits. Or maybe the failed policies of the clean air and water act that eliminated the fires on the rivers and smog-filled air. Or maybe the failed policies of the 1950s that led to growth in education and other infrastructure.\par \par \uc2 Or maybe those failed policies of the late 1930s that helped stabilize a country in free fall.\par \par \uc2 One thing that all those failed policies have in common is that they helped the working people and created a stable society.\par \par \uc2 Derek Popp, Mount Horeb\par \par \uc2 Leaders must protest Harley boycott\par \par \uc2 President \uc2 Donald Trump\uc2 , America's bully in chief, has returned to his \uc2 Twitter\uc2  hammer to urge a boycott of \uc2 Harley-Davidson\uc2 . It appears the orange one is still miffed that Harley executives said Trump's tariff war would cost the company about $100 million a year and force it to move some production overseas. Apparently, in Trump's world successful American companies are supposed to suck it up and take one for the team. That's not the way free enterprise is supposed to work in America.\par \par \uc2 It's long past time for the Republican Party to return to its historic core principles of free markets, lowering deficits and debt and supporting American businesses. And it's time for GOP stalwarts such as Gov. Scott Walker and House Speaker \uc2 Paul Ryan\uc2 , R-Janesville, to speak up to support those core principles.\par \par \uc2 These leaders should stand up and defend this iconic Wisconsin business, possibly the best known Wisconsin brand in the world.\par \par \uc2 Richard Berg, Middleton\par \par \uc2 Take concerns about police seriously\par \par \uc2 As a cisgender gay white male who just turned 30, my experiences with Pride events have been built on the ideal that Pride is about inclusion and acceptance.\par \par \uc2 LGBTQ history was not something I learned growing up. So it wasn't until I read about the Stonewall riots, which occurred after police raided a gay bar in New York City, and activists such as Marsha P. Johnson that I began to consider the historical context. The harassment and violence endured by transgender and queer people, and especially LGBTQ people of color, ignited the fight against inequality in society an inequality perpetuated by police.\par \par \uc2 If members in our community are concerned about including police organizations in the march, we would be wise to listen. Feelings of pain caused by excluding law enforcement participating in the parade pales in comparison to the years of injustice police, as an institution, have inflicted on LGBTQ people of color.\par \par \uc2 We would also be wise to remember why Pride started in 1969, and it certainly was not to stand in "solidarity" with the police force.\par \par \uc2 Andrew Kohrs, Fitchburg\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020180821ee8h0008l\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 OPINION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc5}{\*\bkmkend toc5}\b \uc2 TAKING KIDS AT BORDER IS A NEW LOW\b0\par\par\uc2 Dave Zweifel \par \uc2 591 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 June 2018\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par D.2\par \uc2 ISSN:0749405X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2018 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 VIEWS OF THE CAPITAL TIMES\par \par \uc2 U.S. Sen. Jeff Merkley, an Oregon Democrat who has been particularly vocal about the Trump administration's cruel, if not evil, policy of separating young children from their asylum-seeking parents, was reluctantly allowed to visit an immigrant detention center the other day.\par \par \uc2 After seeing the conditions and how children were kept apart from their parents, he asked U.S. immigration workers if they were concerned about the impact family separation could have on children, some of whom are removed to facilities hundreds of miles away. "We simply follow the orders from above," he was told.\par \par \uc2 When I read that line last week in a Michelle Goldberg column in The \uc2 New York Times\uc2 , I couldn't help but think back to that awful time in history when German soldiers and officials excused their atrocities by explaining they were only following orders.\par \par \uc2 Today, as the rest of us celebrate Father's Day, isn't a good day for hundreds of \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  dads, many of whom came here to try to escape murderous gangs and persecution. Their kids are no longer with them and many have no idea where they are.\par \par \uc2 We're reading some of the awful stories now. Goldberg recounted an earlier Times' story that described a 5-year-old boy from Honduras who had been separated from his father and cried himself to sleep at night with a stickfi gure drawing of his family under his pillow.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, The \uc2 Washington Post\uc2  ran a story about a 39-year-old \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  from Honduras who killed himself in his cell after his 3-year-old was taken.\par \par \uc2 "This is as bad as I've ever seen in 25 years of doing this work," Goldberg quoted the deputy director of the ACLU's Immigrants Rights Project. "The little kids are literally being terrorized."\par \par \uc2 Columnist Nicholas Kristof, noting that we as a nation have crossed so many ugly lines lately, says he's haunted by the Trump administration's tactic of seizing children at the border.\par \par \uc2 A Salvadoran woman described how her 4- and 10-year-old sons were taken from her and she was given but five minutes to say goodbye. "Is this really who we are'" Kristof asked. "As a parent, as the son of a refugee myself, I find that in this case Trump's policy has veered from merely abhorrent to truly evil."\par \par \uc2 Yet Trump's secretary of Homeland Security, \uc2 Kirstjen Nielsen\uc2 , defends the policy, saying it's nothing more than what we do every day in the United States when an adult in a family commits a crime.\par \par \uc2 "If you as a parent break into a house, you will be incarcerated by police and thereby separated from your family," she told a congressional committee, attempting to equate situations where children may lose a miscreant parent to jail, but they still can live in their homes, not in some strange land, and, even more importantly, know where everyone is. The foster family who took in the 5-year-old Honduran boy says not a day goes by when the boy fails to ask in Spanish, "When will I see my papa'"\par \par \uc2 According to The Times, they tell him the truth. They do not know. No one knows.\par \par \uc2 As I asked in a column weeks ago, what will future generations say of us?\par \par \uc2 Credit: By Dave Zweifel; Zweifel is editor emeritus of The Cap Times: dzweifel@madison.com and @DaveZweifel.\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020180618ee6h0002q\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 OPINION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc6}{\*\bkmkend toc6}\b \uc2 YOUR VIEWS\b0\par\par\uc2 1,005 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 December 2017\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par D.3\par \uc2 ISSN:0749405X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2017 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 President Trump favors the fat cats\par \par \uc2 Our president has announced plans to drastically reduce the size of two national monuments in Utah. To cheering Republican leaders in Salt Lake City, Trump declared "public lands will once again be for public use."\par \par \uc2 Really? I wonder if our president has ever stepped foot in a national park or monument? If he had, he might realize the primary reason we have them is to preserve public lands for public use. These parks and monuments are there for all, and they enrich our lives.\par \par \uc2 As it is, President \uc2 Donald Trump\uc2  apparently thinks "public use" involves turning these lands over to private entities - developers (like himself), mining companies, logging companies and others. Of course, this is the very opposite of "public use."\par \par \uc2 It is obviously more important to Trump that he serve the interests of fat cats while spewing platitudes about returning parks and monuments to the "public."\par \par \uc2 What a travesty.\par \par \uc2 John Pray, Verona\par \par \uc2 Immigrant deserved harsher sentence\par \par \uc2 O.J. Simpson never confessed to killing his wife and a young man on that fateful evening in Brentwood, Calif. Most of us thought he was guilty, but his lawyers skillfully maneuvered the trial on racial smears. A jury of easily swayed people were gullible and returned a not guilty verdict. Most of America exclaimed, "What'"\par \par \uc2 An \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 , Jose Zarate, confessed he shot \uc2 Kate Steinle\uc2  in San Francisco. He claimed it was an accident. So what? She is still dead.\par \par \uc2 What should have been at least manslaughter is now possession of a stolen gun. Egads! That's like stabbing someone to death and only being charged with possession of a stolen knife.\par \par \uc2 Zarate had been jailed and deported multiple times before he shot Steinle. Because we don't have a secure border, he easily crossed the border and headed for San Francisco, Calif., a sanctuary city that would deal with him leniently. San Francisco came through in spades for Zarate. Not so much for Steinle.\par \par \uc2 I suspect more like Zarate are roaming around illegally in the United States.\par \par \uc2 Joyce McRoberts, New Glarus\par \par \uc2 Deficits don't matter to today's GOP\par \par \uc2 For decades, Republicans have lived by a few core principles: anti-abortion, Second Amendment rights, strong military and small government. Related to small government is the notion that the budget should be balanced. In fact, many Republicans are urging a Constitutional Convention to mandate balanced budgets.\par \par \uc2 So it's surprising Republicans have now become the party of massive deficit spending. Both House and Senate versions of the new tax bill would add more than $1 trillion to the debt. With the exception of \uc2 Sen. Bob Corker\uc2 , R-Tenn., all GOP senators voted for a deficit increase. In the House, Speaker \uc2 Paul Ryan\uc2 , R-Janesville, a noted deficit hawk, led the charge for "tax reform." Have all of the deficit hawks during the Obama admin-istration become chickadees?\par \par \uc2 History has not been kind to debtor nations. Consider the fate of Greece, a country with such massive debt that it is prey to creditor nations. Right now China owns over a trillion dollars of our debt. This will surely rise with this tax bill. As Republicans used to argue, debt is both an economic and a national security issue. I could not agree more.\par \par \uc2 George Savage, Madison\par \par \uc2 Government doesn't own tax money\par \par \uc2 U.S. Sen. Tammy Baldwin, D-Madison, has called the Republican tax cuts a "giveaway to the wealthiest few." U.S. Rep. Mark Pocan, D-Black Earth, also has called them a "giveaway to the wealthiest." House Minority Leader \uc2 Nancy Pelosi\uc2 , D-Calif., said the tax rate cuts are a "gift to corporate America."\par \par \uc2 I believe they are each in need of an attitude adjustment.\par \par \uc2 If I choose to not steal your car, it is not a gift to you. You can only give away something you own in the first place. You can argue the cuts are not necessary. You can argue they are unwise. But you can't declare it's all yours to begin with. It is not the government's money. They don't get to decide what you keep.\par \par \uc2 Governments only acquire wealth by confiscating it. Please keep that in mind when you decide how much to confiscate from taxpayers.\par \par \uc2 Patrick O'Loughlin, Madison\par \par \uc2 GOP is dishonest about its principles\par \par \uc2 As saddened as I am by the resignation of U.S. Sen. Al Frankin, D-Minn., I have to respect his decision that realizes how the allegations are taking away from important Senate business.\par \par \uc2 But I have to question the Republican senators and representatives who are still publicly supporting a president who openly brags on tape about molesting women, and a Senate candidate in Alabama who was allegedly banned from a public mall for trolling for young girls. What does this say about those elected officials who are either silent or - even worse - openly voicing support for these men?\par \par \uc2 At least U.S. Sen. Tammy Baldwin, D-Madison, has spoken out to support her convictions, though it may cost her party a vote in the Senate. \uc2 U.S. Sen. Ron Johnson\uc2 , R-Oshkosh, seems to feel his party is more important than his convictions - or else he's not the man he represents himself to be.\par \par \uc2 Patricia M. Giesfeldt, Cottage Grove\par \par \uc2 Don't forget Hill's harassment claims\par \par \uc2 In this time of widespread sexual harassment allegations, we should remember \uc2 Anita Hill\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Twenty-six years ago, long before it was safe, Hill made allegations of sexual harassment against a Supreme Court candidate. Today, these allegations would be considered credible by all but the most partisan observers. At that time, Hill was branded a liar and accused of slanderous claims.\par \par \uc2 As a result, we have a sitting Supreme Court justice today who routinely rules on a wide variety of cases which involve abuses of power and which determine if the rights of women should remain the same as those of men. Maybe it is finally time to do something about this.\par \par \uc2 Jim Miller, Madison\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020171211edca0002m\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 THE CAP TIMES\par {\*\bkmkstart toc7}{\*\bkmkend toc7}\b \uc2 NEW WOMEN'S LEGAL NETWORK IS A STEP IN RIGHT DIRECTION\b0\par\par\uc2 Margaret Krome \par \uc2 571 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 November 2017\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par 43\par \uc2 ISSN:07494068\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2017 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 None but the most obdurate could ignore the recent stories tumbling on top of each other of abuse against women, in this country and globally.\par \par \uc2 From the "#MeToo" social media campaign, to a new California law protecting the privacy of job applicants' salary history, to an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  teen's successful legal fight against federal government efforts to deny her legal right to an abortion, all have brought up what I already knew: that women's rights are as precarious today as at any time in my lifetime. Some people are taking productive steps.\par \par \uc2 Months ago, revelations about ways that high-profile and powerful men have coerced women colleagues to provide sexual favors seemed like business as usual. Then the stunning and now months-long Bill Cosby/ Roger Ailes/ Bill O'Reilly/ Harvey Weinstein stories of aggressive abuse began to form an endless torrent of male culprits. And the #MeToo social media campaign that followed demonstrated that sexual coercion is, indeed, business as usual, with a poll finding that 54 percent of American women have experienced "unwanted and inappropriate sexual advances" during their lifetimes. If public exposure and private lawsuits prove insufficiently corrective, we must identify other remedies.\par \par \uc2 During my career, I've mostly set my own salary, but I've been told twice that I shouldn't expect parity with male colleagues because my husband makes a good salary. So I'm not surprised that women earn on average 80 percent what men earn for the same work, and I've witnessed how one's past salary tends to perpetuate inequity. Unfortunately, in April, a federal appeals court ruled that employers can legally pay women less than men for the same work based on previous salary differences. Pushing back recently, California changed its law to prohibit employers from asking about previous salaries and benefits, a step that should open up public discussion about pay inequity.\par \par \uc2 The young immigrant woman whom the Trump administration tried to prevent from receiving an abortion demonstrated both her tenacity in insisting on her legally protected rights and also the power of having legal representation.\par \par \uc2 Unfortunately, current prospects regarding federal protection of women's rights aren't bright. In September, \uc2 CNN\uc2  reported that of the 42 attorneys that President Trump had nominated for U.S. attorneys, only one was a woman. While my own family demonstrates that men can be strong feminists and advocates for women's rights, this appalling record's clear bias augurs ill for meaningful gender protection.\par \par \uc2 So it's exciting that the National Women's Law Center recently launched a national legal network to combat sex discrimination faced by women and girls in jobs, school, and health care. What a travesty that our national leadership should be so unreliable that a private Legal Network for Gender Equity is needed, but it's reassuring to see an actionable strategy to push back - against discriminatory hiring and pay inequality. Against sexual abuse and forcing women to accept health outcomes and reproductive outcomes that aren't of their choosing. Against sexist custom that prevents women the full range of education, self-determination and choice in their lives.\par \par \uc2 Gender discrimination is now evident to all. Certainly, cultural change takes time, but investments in legal remedies right now can help shift that culture toward justice and civility.\par \par \uc2 Credit: By Margaret Krome\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020171103edb100130\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 LOCAL\par {\*\bkmkstart toc8}{\*\bkmkend toc8}\b \uc2 IMMIGRANT RIGHTS GROUPS CRITICIZE MILWAUKEE\b0\par\par\uc2 379 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 July 2017\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ISSN:0749405X\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2017 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved. \par \par \uc2 Immigrant rights groups are accusing Milwaukee leaders of caving in to pressure from the Trump admin-istration and quietly expanding cooperation with immigration officials.\par \par \uc2 One group, Voces de la Frontera, says Milwaukee officials are weakening safeguards for immigrants by making it easier for the Milwaukee Police Department to work with federal immigration agents. The group also warns the changes could lead to racial profiling, the Milwaukee Journal Sentinel reported.\par \par \uc2 Jeff Fleming, spokesman for Mayor Tom Barrett, said the mayor remains committed to immigrants.\par \par \uc2 "The mayor is not wavering at all in his support of immigrants in Milwaukee. For reasons of technical compliance, some changes were required in official policy," Fleming said. "But again the mayor stands with immigrants, the immigrant community and the entire city on respecting the value of immigrants."\par \par \uc2 But Voces' executive director, Christine Neumann-Ortiz, criticized changes in standard operating procedures that were approved last month by Police Chief Edward Flynn and are set to take effect Thursday.\par \par \uc2 One eliminates a directive that officers were not to question people about their immigration status unless they met a narrow list of criteria. Another change states that officers "shall inform" federal immigration officials of the whereabouts or behaviors of any "suspected \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 " when that person is arrested for a felony or other serious crimes, such as those involving terrorism or street gangs.\par \par \uc2 "It literally mandates that the Police Department turn over the information," said \uc2 Darryl Morin\uc2  of the \uc2 League of United Latin American Citizens\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The Milwaukee Police Department did not respond to requests for comment.\par \par \uc2 Morin and Neumann-Ortiz said the policy changes occurred largely out of view of the public.\par \par \uc2 "We completely condemn the undemocratic process by which this decision was made," Neumann-Ortiz said. "Basically the community was kept in the dark that the city, under Barrett's leadership, was caving into pressure from the Trump administration."\par \par \uc2 The Trump administration threatened in April to cut grant money for Milwaukee County, but not the city, over so-called sanctuary policies for immigrants.\par \par \uc2 Barrett has been a vocal critic of efforts by President \uc2 Donald Trump\uc2  and his administration to clamp down on "sanctuary cities," repeatedly saying they were trying to force local governments to act as "border guards."\par \par \uc2 Credit: Associated Press\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020170706ed7500035\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 FRONT\par {\*\bkmkstart toc9}{\*\bkmkend toc9}\b \uc2 THOUSANDS GATHER AT CAPITOL ; WORKERS, STUDENTS, SUPPORTERS JOIN TO DEFEAT WHAT SOME CONSIDER TO BE ANTI-IMMIGRANT LEGISLATION A DAY WITHOUT LATINOS | DEMONSTRATORS, BUSINESSES STAND IN SOLIDARITY\b0\par\par\uc2 DOUG ERICKSON   \par \uc2 DOUG ERICKSON derickson@madison.com, 608-252-6149; State Journal reporters Matthew DeFour and Amanda Finn contributed to this report.\par \uc2 1,204 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 February 2016\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2016 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Angered by bills in the state Legislature they consider anti- immigrant, thousands of Latinos and their allies descended Thursday on the state Capitol in what they hoped would be a persuasive show of unity and opposition.\par \par \uc2 The rally, called "A Day Without Latinos and Immigrants in Wisconsin," also sought to convey the economic power of the Latino community by illustrating what would happen if thousands of Latino employees and business owners didn't show up for work.\par \par \uc2 Numerous local businesses, including a \uc2 McDonald's\uc2  in Middleton and the popular restaurant Quivey's Grove in Madison, closed Thursday, either in solidarity with their Latino employees or because they did not have enough staff to open.\par \par \uc2 The Capitol Police\uc2  Department estimated the crowd size inside the Capitol and on the grounds at 14,000. The Madison Police Department estimated there were 20,000 people on the streets around the Capitol at the peak of the day's march.\par \par \uc2 No arrests or incidents related to the rally were reported by either department.\par \par \uc2 Many protesters were Madison students, some of whom marched in throngs from West and East high schools. Early estimates showed about 4,500 students, or 16 percent of the district's total enrollment, were absent Thursday, compared with 1,500 students and 5.5 percent on a typical day, said district spokeswoman Rachel Strauch-Nelson.\par \par \uc2 The primary goal of the day was to defeat two "antiimmigrant laws" moving through the Legislature, said Christine Neumann-Ortiz, executive director of Voces de la Frontera, the rally's main sponsor.\par \par \uc2 One bill, SB 533, would place restrictions on a local government's ability to issue identification cards to people such as immigrants who are in the country illegally. It has passed the Assembly and the Senate and is awaiting action by Gov. Scott Walker.\par \par \uc2 The other bill, AB 450, would withhold state funding from so- called "sanctuary cities." These are cities where public employees are prohibited from inquiring about someone's citizenship status. The bill has passed the Assembly and is awaiting action in the Senate.\par \par \uc2 Jennifer Mancera, 30, of Madison, who attended the rally, said she takes the legislation personally "because, at one point, I was an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 ."\par \par \uc2 "At the end of the day, these bills push away people who are only trying to make this a better country," she said.\par \par \uc2 Assembly Speaker Robin Vos, R-Rochester, told reporters Thursday that protesters misunderstood the impact of the sanctuary cities bill.\par \par \uc2 "The goal of the legislation is to make sure that people who commit crimes are punished," Vos said. "The basic idea that fear is being instilled is not coming from the Wisconsin Legislature. It's coming from the activists who want to try to pursue a political agenda."\par \par \uc2 Dave Gorak of La Valle, executive director of the Midwest Coalition to Reduce Immigration, also took issue with the rally, calling it "outrageous."\par \par \uc2 "These people have no respect for our laws or our sovereignty, yet they want us to respect them for attempting to cut the legs off our enforcement policies," he said.\par \par \uc2 However, Middleton dairy farmer Thomas Wagner, 62, said he doesn't think legislators understand the consequences of what they're doing. He came to the rally to support the 13 Latinos who work for him, more than half of his farm's workforce, he said. He and his brothers would not be able to continue operating their 1,700- head dairy operation without them, he said.\par \par \uc2 "We need these people in our state," he said. "They are good, honest, hard workers."\par \par \uc2 East High sophomore Alexandra Miranda, 15, came to the rally with her parents and two younger brothers. She said most of her friends also chose the rally over classes.\par \par \uc2 "This means a lot to me because I don't want my family to be torn apart," she said. Her brothers' stroller was festooned with white balloons saying, "Wisconsin is not Arizona."\par \par \uc2 Javier Hernandez, 39, of Madison, waved a huge homemade white flag with red letters reading, "The Land is to Who Works It." Each young person in a large group of students from the Watertown area held a placard with an individual letter that together spelled out, "One nation under God, indivisible, with liberty and justice for all."\par \par \uc2 Neumann-Ortiz said her organization was keeping a list of businesses that had closed and said she was confident the number would end up being in the hundreds across the state.\par \par \uc2 "If you have a climate that is so un-welcoming that people leave your state, industries are going to die," she said.\par \par \uc2 La Brioche, a bakery and restaurant in Madison that employs about 40, was among those that closed Thursday.\par \par \uc2 "We have a fair number of Latino employees, so it will be obvious to them where we stand on these issues, and I hope for some sort of ripple effect if enough people understand the negative aspects of this legislation," said owner David Yankovich.\par \par \uc2 La Brioche and another Madison bakery, Le Petit Croissant, planned to make sandwiches to pass out at the rally so that people would not spend money at restaurants that remained open.\par \par \uc2 Carrie Barndt, who owns six area \uc2 McDonald's\uc2  restaurants, said she closed the one on Allen Boulevard in Middleton Thursday because so many employees, both Latino and non-Latino, asked for the day off. She consolidated the remaining employees at the other five locations.\par \par \uc2 At least half a dozen businesses on \uc2 State Street\uc2  in Downtown Madison were closed either part or all of the day on Thursday in solidarity with the rally. Tutto Pasta, Casa de Lara and Endless Knot closed for the day, while Hawk's Bar and Grill, Roast Public House, and Himal Chuli were planning to reopen for dinner.\par \par \uc2 Amy Moore, owner of Little Luxuries on \uc2 State Street\uc2 , said she did not close for the event because she wanted to "be open for people who are Downtown for the event or not." She noticed an up-tick in shoppers because of the rally - specifically those in need of gloves and socks.\par \par \uc2 Caption: Photos by JOHN HART - State Journal    Demonstrators said recent legislation - such as banning local identification cards and punishing cities that prohibit employees from asking about one's immigration status - was a personal affront to them and their families, many of whom skipped work and school Thursday to drive the point home.  Police estimated that as many as 20,000 people marched around the streets of the Capitol at the peak of Thursday's rally, called "A Day Without Latinos and Immigrants in Wisconsin."  Thousands of protesters moved into the Capitol rotunda Thursday to demonstrate against legislation that would prohibit the creation of local identification cards and punish cities whose officials don't actively work with federal authorities to enforce immigration laws.  Many students walked out of school to attend Thursday's protest, and businesses shut down to accommodate their employees who wanted to participate.   \par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020160222ec2j0000x\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 FRONT\par {\*\bkmkstart toc10}{\*\bkmkend toc10}\b \uc2 WALKER STRUGGLES TO FIND HIS STANCE ON IMMIGRATION ; HIS POSITION ON BIRTHRIGHT CITIZENSHIP UNCLEAR AFTER ZIGZAGGING COMMENTS, VIEWS\b0\par\par\uc2 MARK SOMMERHAUSER   \par \uc2 MARK SOMMERHAUSER msommerhauser@madison.com, 608-252-6122\par \uc2 1,336 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 August 2015\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2015 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Gov. Scott Walker has struggled in recent days to say where he stands on immigration, even after Republican rivals usurped him in presidential polls with forceful appeals to voter anger on the issue.\par \par \uc2 Walker appeared to complete a swift, sweeping transformation from immigration pragmatist to hard-liner last week at the Iowa State Fair. There, he endorsed key provisions of the immigration plan put forth by GOP frontrunner \uc2 Donald Trump\uc2  hours earlier.\par \par \uc2 But in the face of mounting questions about his immigration position, Walker backpedaled on his support for one of those provisions - ending birthright citizenship - in interviews over the weekend.\par \par \uc2 Trump is leading the GOP pack, in part, on the basis of his sharp opposition to illegal immigration. Experts say that suggests a strident stance by other Republican candidates on the issue would find favor with many GOP caucus-goers and primary voters.\par \par \uc2 But Walker's wobbling on immigration could dog him, especially since he has been accused of flip-flopping on other topics. Should he commit to a hard-line immigration position, experts say it also might dampen his appeal in a general election.\par \par \uc2 Lara Brown, a professor of political management at \uc2 George Washington University\uc2 , said it's clear Trump is driving the GOP conversation on immigration. For now, it may be politically appealing for other Republicans to mimic Trump's positions, but Brown said trouble may await those who do.\par \par \uc2 "Any Republican that chases Trump too far down this rabbit hole will make themselves un-electable next fall," Brown said.\par \par \uc2 At the state fair last week, Walker appeared to express support for building a wall on the U.S. border with Mexico.\par \par \uc2 Birthright citizenship divides GOP field\par \par \uc2 For the first time, Walker also indicated support for ending birthright citizenship - the right to citizenship for those born in the U.S., which is guaranteed by the U.S. Constitution.\par \par \uc2 Both building the wall and ending birthright citizenship are in Trump's immigration plan, which was released a day before Walker's state fair remarks.\par \par \uc2 Both measures also would face practical hurdles to implement. Ending birthright citizenship would be extraordinarily difficult, since it likely would require amending the Constitution, experts say. Building a wall would cost tens of billions of dollars, experts say - and they disagree on how effectively it would deter illegal immigration.\par \par \uc2 Walker backtracked on birthright citizenship a few days later, telling CNBC's John Harwood that he neither supports nor opposes ending the practice.\par \par \uc2 As recently as 2013, Walker said he supported creating a path to citizenship for those living in the U.S. illegally. It was a long- held position for Walker, who in 2002, as Milwaukee County executive, signed a resolution expressing support for comprehensive immigration reform.\par \par \uc2 Walker's abrupt evolution on the issue began in March, as he began preparing a presidential run. He said he no longer supports a path to citizenship, telling Fox News host Chris Wallace that his reversal came after he talked to governors of U.S. border states.\par \par \uc2 Walker weighed in again in April, saying he favors lower levels of legal immigration to protect the jobs and wages of workers already in the U.S.\par \par \uc2 Then came his comments in Iowa last week, which followed polls the previous week that showed him tumbling in Iowa and in the national race, while Trump soared.\par \par \uc2 Asked if his repeated calls to secure the border would entail building a wall on the U.S. border with Mexico, Walker said: "It's a combination of infrastructure - the wall itself - but you also have to have technology and personnel in support of that."\par \par \uc2 NBC News on Monday, Aug. 17, asked Walker if he supports ending birthright citizenship.\par \par \uc2 "Yeah, absolutely, going forward," Walker responded.\par \par \uc2 Hunt asked again to confirm Walker's response.\par \par \uc2 "Yeah, to me it's about enforcing the laws in this country," Walker said, nodding.\par \par \uc2 Soon after that, Walker began backtracking. A Tuesday statement to the State Journal from Walker's spokeswoman, AshLee Strong, appeared to distance Walker from his remarks a day earlier.\par \par \uc2 In the interview with Harwood Friday, Walker said he neither supports nor opposes ending birthright citizenship.\par \par \uc2 "I'm saying that until you secure the border and enforce the laws, any discussion about anything else is really looking past the very things we have to do," Walker said.\par \par \uc2 Then Sunday, Walker told ABC's George Stephanopoulos that he doesn't support changing the 14th Amendment to the U.S. Constitution, which likely would be necessary to end birthright citizenship.\par \par \uc2 Birthright citizenship has emerged as a surprising point of divergence for the Republican presidential field. U.S. Sen. Ted Cruz of Texas and U.S. Sen. \uc2 Lindsey Graham\uc2  of South Carolina are among those joining the call to end it. Others, such as U.S. Sen. \uc2 Marco Rubio\uc2  and former Gov. Jeb Bush, both of Florida, have said it should remain in place.\par \par \uc2 A few lawmakers, such as former U.S. Sen. \uc2 Jim DeMint\uc2  of South Carolina and Rep. Steve King of Iowa, proposed ending birthright citizenship in years past.\par \par \uc2 Not Walker's first shift on immigration\par \par \uc2 But Marc Rosenblum, an immigration expert at the nonpartisan \uc2 Migration Policy Institute\uc2  in Washington, D.C., said until recently, it "never really had much leverage as a serious proposal."\par \par \uc2 That's because the 14th Amendment to the U.S. Constitution guarantees citizenship to anyone born in the U.S. Some conservatives, however, have argued the right doesn't extend to those born to parents living in the U.S. illegally.\par \par \uc2 Amending the Constitution is a monumental task. The only method by which it has been done requires two-thirds approval of the amendment in the U.S. House and Senate, then ratification by three- fourths of the states.\par \par \uc2 Rosenblum said the constitutional amendment hurdle has been the main impediment to a broader discussion of ending birthright citizenship. But now that Trump has proposed it, others are following suit, he said.\par \par \uc2 "It has some sort of intuitive appeal" for opponents of illegal immigration, Rosenblum said. "It really resonates with the idea that immigrants are somehow gaming the system."\par \par \uc2 Arizona law\par \par \uc2 This isn't the first time Walker publicly zigzagged on immigration.\par \par \uc2 As a gubernatorial candidate in 2010, Walker spoke out against Arizona's 2010 immigration law, which, among other provisions, requires state law enforcement officers to check a person's immigration status during routine stops if there is reasonable suspicion that person is an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "In America, we don't want our citizens getting pulled over because of how they look," Walker said at the time.\par \par \uc2 Walker changed course days later, saying he would be comfortable signing a similar law in Wisconsin.\par \par \uc2 Walker changed his stance once more in 2012, saying he didn't want the Wisconsin Legislature to pass such a bill because it would become a "huge distraction" from more pressing issues.\par \par \uc2 Immigration also isn't the only major issue on which Walker has shifted this year. He changed his stance on the federal renewable fuel standard - a key issue in the early presidential state of Iowa - and on whether a right-to-work measure would become law in Wisconsin, and was widely perceived as changing his tone on abortion.\par \par \uc2 Brown said virtually every presidential candidate changes their stance on some issue. Where they find trouble, Brown added, is when they shift too far, too fast, or both.\par \par \uc2 "Unsuccessful candidates often make these shifts too quickly," Brown said. "That's how they get branded 'flip-floppers.'"\par \par \uc2 Web Extra\par \par \uc2 Keep up-to-date with the latest news as Scott Walker pursues the 2016 Republican presidential nomination with our Tracking Scott Walker page\par \par \uc2 go.madison.com/walker\par \par \uc2 Caption: BUTCH DILL - Associated Press  Wisconsin Gov. Scott Walker, a Republican presidential candidate, gets a high-five from Finley Bell during a campaign stop on Saturday at Dreamland BBQ in Birmingham, Ala.   \par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020150825eb8o0000c\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Front\par {\*\bkmkstart toc11}{\*\bkmkend toc11}\b \uc2 CONGRESSIONAL ROLL CALL\b0\par\par\uc2 823 \uc2 words\par \uc2 25 July 2015\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2015 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Here's how members of Wisconsin's congressional delegation voted on major issues this week.\par \par \uc2 SANCTUARY CITIES, IMMIGRATION ENFORCEMENT: The House on Thursday voted, 241 for and 179 against, to deny certain law-enforcement grants to so-called "sanctuary cities" that decline to act as an arm of federal immigration enforcement. The GOP-drafted bill (HR 3009) is a response to a recent murder in San Francisco, a sanctuary city, in which an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  with felony convictions allegedly gunned down Kathryn Steinle after city authorities released him from custody.\par \par \uc2 A yes vote was to send the bill to the Senate.\par \par \uc2 Voting yes: Paul Ryan, R-1st, James Sensenbrenner, R-5th, Glenn Grothman, R-6th, \uc2 Sean Duffy\uc2 , R-7th, Reid Ribble, R-8th\par \par \uc2 Voting no: Mark Pocan, D-2nd, Ronald Kind, D-3rd, Gwen Moore, D- 4\par \par \uc2 CRIME RATES IN SANCTUARY CITIES: Voting 181 for and 239 against, the House on Thursday defeated a bid by Democrats to block any funding cuts under HR 3009 (above) that would reduce a city's deployment of police on the beat or raise its crime rate with respect to domestic violence, sex crimes or crimes against children.\par \par \uc2 A yes vote was to adopt the motion, which, had it prevailed, would have immediately amended the bill.\par \par \uc2 Voting yes: Pocan, Kind, Moore\par \par \uc2 Voting no: Ryan, Sensenbrenner, Grothman, Duffy, Ribble\par \par \uc2 STATE REGULATION OF COAL ASH: Voting 258 for and 166 against, the House on Wednesday passed a GOP-drafted bill (HR 1734) that would give states rather than the \uc2 Environmental Protection Agency\uc2  primary authority to regulate the coal ash discharged as waste by the nation's 500-plus coal-fired power plants. The bill would put states in charge of permitting and enforcement under a new \uc2 EPA\uc2  rule for regulating coal ash impounded in ponds or landfills near these plants. The federal rule takes effect Oct. 19.\par \par \uc2 A yes vote was to send the bill to the Senate.\par \par \uc2 Voting yes: Ryan, Moore, Sensenbrenner, Grothman, Duffy, Ribble\par \par \uc2 Voting no: Pocan, Kind\par \par \uc2 DRINKING WATER FROM NEARBY WELLS: Voting 192 for and 231 against, the House on Wednesday refused to require operators of coal-ash impoundment sites to provide notification and alternative sources of safe drinking water to properties within one-half mile whose wells show signs of coal-ash contamination. The Democratic- sponsored amendment was offered to HR 1734 (above).\par \par \uc2 A yes vote was to adopt the amendment.\par \par \uc2 Voting yes: Pocan, Kind, Moore\par \par \uc2 Voting no: Ryan, Sensenbrenner, Grothman, Duffy, Ribble\par \par \uc2 VOLUNTARY LABELING OF GMO FOODS: Voting 275 for and 150 against, the House on Thursday passed a bill (HR 1599) that would establish a system of voluntary, state-administered labeling requirements for foods that contain genetically modified organisms (GMOs). In addition, the bill pre-empts any existing or future state or local laws that establish mandatory labeling of genetically engineered foods. At present, there are no federal requirements for GMO labeling.\par \par \uc2 A yes vote favored a voluntary state-by-state approach to labeling GMO foods.\par \par \uc2 Voting yes: Ryan, Sensenbrenner, Grothman, Duffy, Ribble\par \par \uc2 Voting no: Pocan, Kind, Moore\par \par \uc2 MANDATORY GMO LABELING: Voting 123 for and 303 against, the House on Thursday defeated an amendment to HR 1599 (above) that sought to require mandatory, federally administered labeling of foods containing genetically modified organisms (GMOs). This would replace the underlying bill's voluntary state-level approach.\par \par \uc2 A yes vote was to establish federally mandated labeling of foods containing GMOs.\par \par \uc2 Voting yes: Pocan, Moore\par \par \uc2 Voting no: Ryan, Kind, Sensenbrenner, Grothman, Duffy, Ribble\par \par \uc2 GMO FOODS LABELED AS 'NATURAL': Voting 163 for and 262 against, the House on Thursday refused to prohibit food labeled as "natural" from containing genetically modified ingredients. The vote affirmed wording in HR 1599 (above) that allows \uc2 Food and Drug Administration\uc2  and \uc2 U.S. Department of Agriculture\uc2  definitions of "natural" to include GMO foods.\par \par \uc2 A yes vote was to prohibit foods containing GMOs from being labeled as "natural."\par \par \uc2 Voting yes: Pocan, Kind, Moore\par \par \uc2 Voting no: Ryan, Sensenbrenner, Grothman, Duffy, Ribble\par \par \uc2 SIX-YEAR TRANSPORTATION BILL: Voting 62 for and 36 against, the Senate on Wednesday agreed to start debate on a bill (HR 22) that would authorize $317 billion over six years for highway and mass- transit construction projects. Because the Highway Trust Fund is projected to raise only $240 billion over the next six years to finance these projects, the bill faces a shortfall of $77 billion that would be funded by revenue increases or spending cuts yet to be fully determined. If the bill clears the Senate, it would have to be reconciled with a House-passed measure to fund transportation programs only through Dec. 18.\par \par \uc2 A yes vote was to advance the transportation bill.\par \par \uc2 Voting yes: Ron Johnson, R\par \par \uc2 Voting no: Tammy Baldwin, D\par \par \uc2 Next week, the House will take up bills on federal regulations and veterans' programs, while the Senate will resume work on a six- year funding bill for highway and mass-transit construction projects.\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020160217eb7p0000u\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 WEEKEND\par {\*\bkmkstart toc12}{\*\bkmkend toc12}\b \uc2 PLATA'S 'ROAD' TELLS TALES OF HIS OWN LIFE'S JOURNEY\b0\par\par\uc2 JANE BURNS  \par \uc2 JANE BURNS jburns@madison.com, 608-252-6440\par \uc2 1,093 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 March 2015\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par D1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2015 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.  \par \par \uc2 There can be various ways to tell a life story, and Cris Plata knows that firsthand.\par \par \uc2 The Wisconsin singer-songwriter already has his story in book form, and now that book has a companion. "Migration Road," Plata's third release and first since 2003, takes its cues from the music he heard in his youth as his family traveled the U.S. as migrant farm workers.\par \par \uc2 "So I had to go back and think of the first music that I'd heard in these places, music I'd never been exposed to in Texas," said Plata, 60, who was born on a ranch near Poteet, Texas.\par \par \uc2 The CD serves as a companion piece to "Cris Plata: From Fields to Stage," a youth-targeted book in the Wisconsin Historical Press' Badger Biography Series. The book came out last year, and the CD is being released this week with a launch party Saturday at the High Noon Saloon.\par \par \uc2 "I think this is the best CD I've done, in terms of the material and the fidelity, and to have my wife at the helm producing it was a unique experience," Plata said.\par \par \uc2 His wife, Ann, a veterinarian, also plays bass in the band. It was her first time as producer and she also wrote the CD's opening song, "Goodbye Butterfly." Many of the songs benefited from his wife's tweaks, Plata said, in terms of instrumentation, content and tempo.\par \par \uc2 "I learned from Butch Vig because he had great ideas," Plata said of the Smart Studio producer who worked on Plata's first record, 1989's "Spreading the Rumor." "But Ann must have really been paying attention."\par \par \uc2 The suggestion to make it a collection of the sounds that influenced him came from Ann, Plata said, and the result is a variety of styles as he retraces the road that brought him to Wisconsin. It's where he remains, living with Ann on a farm near Columbus.\par \par \uc2 Plata's family worked the cotton fields of Texas, tomato fields of Indiana and Florida and a variety of vegetable operations in Wisconsin. Music was their entertainment, both back home in Texas and while in their temporary homes far away.\par \par \uc2 Plata learned the guitar at a young age, picking up the music that he heard around him as a child, what he describes as Mexican roots music.\par \par \uc2 But his travels opened his ears to different kinds of music, styles he'd never heard before. That's part of the music that makes up "Migration Road," and the stories those songs tell.\par \par \uc2 The record's second track, "House of the Master," is about the workers in Florida who had to go to the fields on Sunday, without pay, because the boss said so and the workers had to keep their jobs. Migrant workers came to Florida from Jamaica, too, and Plata was introduced to their music.\par \par \uc2 "They were singing stuff I'd never heard before," Plata said. "I wasn't a musician then but I loved music and thought, 'I really like what they're doing.'"\par \par \uc2 He asked them what it was, and they told him it was "rocksteady" - a precursor to reggae music.\par \par \uc2 The next track on the record, "Sitting in the Shade," takes its inspiration from another music that was unfamiliar to the young Plata - bluegrass. He first heard it when his family was in Indiana and again was intrigued.\par \par \uc2 "We'd turn on the radio and think, 'What's this strange sound"" Plata said. "It was banjos and high and lonesome singing, mandolins, guitars and a big doghouse bass. I really liked it."\par \par \uc2 The record also includes much of what has inspired Plata throughout his life - a love of animals and all of nature, as well as a sense of trying to do right in the world.\par \par \uc2 That comes through in one of the most beautiful songs on the record, "Moonlight Walkabout," inspired by the times that Plata would just sit in the fields on a moon-lit night, listen to the sounds of the animals and play his guitar.\par \par \uc2 His heritage comes through strong in a song that is a tribute to his oldest brother, Juan, who taught him traditional music and also gave him his introduction to rock 'n' roll.\par \par \uc2 "A couple years before he died, I went down to Texas and he introduced me to all his musical friends who were in a mariachi band, and that was a treat," Plata said.\par \par \uc2 "I learned quite a bit because I'd never played with a full mariachi band before."\par \par \uc2 Plata wanted to do a mariachi song, but he wanted to do it right and it was still unfamiliar territory to him. He used a combination of English and Spanish lyrics, and brought in Chris Wagoner of the Stellanovas on violin.\par \par \uc2 "I had to sweat it out. I wanted to do a tribute, but I wanted to do it justice," Plata said. "I didn't want it to be a hack job.\par \par \uc2 "I kind of had to study it a little bit."\par \par \uc2 His "Migration Road" ends with the first song he ever recorded in 1989. He was about to record his first album in Madison, but while visiting family in San Antonio was inspired to write the song "Little Eagle" after reading about the death of an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  in a locked truck.\par \par \uc2 Plata wanted the song to have the traditional sound of border music, and recorded it there to achieve that.\par \par \uc2 "My wife said, "Why don't you put on the first song that you ever recorded? Then it's like completing the journey," he said in choosing songs for "Migration Road."\par \par \uc2 The migration days are long over for Plata. He'll spend time playing around the Midwest again this year, but also taking time to ride horses with his wife.\par \par \uc2 It's a passion they both share, with a horse on the CD's cover and two songs evoking horses.\par \par \uc2 "She did so much for this record," Plata said. "We're going to spend some time doing what she wants to do."\par \par \uc2 IF YOU GO\par \par \uc2 What: Cris Plata with Extra Hot\par \par \uc2 When: 5:30 p.m. Saturday\par \par \uc2 Where: High Noon Saloon, 701A E. Washington Ave.\par \par \uc2 Tickets: $7\par \par \uc2 On the Web: crisplata.com\par \par \uc2 Caption: JOHN CONNELL  Cris Plata's new CD, "Migration Road," was inspired by the many places he and his family spent time as migrant workers throughout his early life.  \par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020150323eb3k00001\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 OPINION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc13}{\*\bkmkend toc13}\b \uc2 YOUR VIEWS\b0\par\par\uc2 873 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 August 2014\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2014 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.  \par \par \uc2 Treat texting at wheel like drunken driving\par \par \uc2 Last weekend I watched as a young driver slammed into the back of a stopped car while texting. Fortunately, no one was seriously hurt.\par \par \uc2 Since texting probably impairs driving as much as drinking does, the punishment should be the same. Whenever we see people texting behind the wheel, we should call the police and report them. The police can't be everywhere, but the public can.\par \par \uc2 If people want to kill themselves, that's one thing. But I don't want them to take me with them.\par \par \uc2 - Richard Nawratil, Monona\par \par \uc2 Hamas\uc2  exposes its civilians to risk\par \par \uc2 Though \uc2 Hamas\uc2  is the acknowledged terrorist aggressor to Israel, it is also the first to cry "cease-fire." Why? Because Israel fights