ted\par \par \uc2 A referendum on the primary election ballot calls for $4 million in additional property taxes for Blackhawk Technical College.\par \par \uc2 Most states used to have both a tech college system and a community or junior college system that merged to eliminate duplication of buildings, campuses, programs and services. I have long advocated the merger of the \uc2 Wisconsin Technical College System\uc2  and the \uc2 University of Wisconsin\uc2  System to create a Wisconsin State College System.\par \par \uc2 Some fear the loss of the "technology and industry" programs of tech colleges. But this can be addressed with a requirement that up to 40 percent of the budget goes to trade and industry programs.\par \par \uc2 Another concern I have is the lack of basic education requirements for tech college students that other colleges have, including course work in social studies, science and humanities.\par \par \uc2 The problem with tech colleges is that business and industry want to create worker drones rather than well-rounded, educated citizens.\par \par \uc2 - Dave Searles, Brodhead\par \par \uc2 US can't solve every problem, care for all\par \par \uc2 A letter last Thursday from the executive director of the Wisconsin Alliance for Women's Health claimed pro-lifers are hypocritical and hateful toward \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  children.\par \par \uc2 Pro-lifers (not necessarily political parties) care about all life, young and old, male and female, from conception to natural death.\par \par \uc2 Treating symptoms alone never eliminates causes. Too many people have forgotten or rejected our creator's perfect plan. Our country can't solve the causes of violence in other countries, nor support all its effects.\par \par \uc2 Legalized abortion in 1973 didn't eliminate the causes of immature or irresponsible sexual actions. Since then millions of such resultant lives have been conceived and then eliminated.\par \par \uc2 Compassion begins at home, and pro-lifers do their part to save as many of the least of these unwanted lives as they can. Adoption offers refuge from violence in the womb.\par \par \uc2 - Alice Mueller, Richland Center\par \par \uc2 Subeck stands for fairness in workplace\par \par \uc2 I support Lisa Subeck for Assembly because of her positions on raising the minimum wage, providing paid sick leave and equal pay.\par \par \uc2 These are issues that cut across partisan political lines. We need policies that recognize the reality of peoples' lives today and also support an economy that works for everyone.\par \par \uc2 Women are increasingly the breadwinners in their families. When employers don't pay people equally for doing the same job, or when there is no access to paid sick leave, it hurts children, families and our economy.\par \par \uc2 Subeck has shown, by her career and her stands on issues, that she understands the importance of making the workplace fair and how that helps us all. I'm voting for Subeck on Aug. 12.\par \par \uc2 - Barbara J. Wright, Madison\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020140808ea870000u\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc14}{\*\bkmkend toc14}\b \uc2 YOUR VIEWS\b0\par\par\uc2 878 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 August 2014\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A11\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2014 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.  \par \par \uc2 Unproductive Congress should adjourn forever\par \par \uc2 We have all heard the phrase "Nero fiddled while Rome burned."\par \par \uc2 This is very much like our \uc2 Congress\uc2 , particularly the Republicans, suing and threatening impeachment of the president while our country is in crisis.\par \par \uc2 Congress\uc2  just adjourned for a five-week vacation after doing virtually nothing all year while many issues are left unaddressed. All we need to do is listen to or read the daily news to understand what they are.\par \par \uc2 Everyone in \uc2 Congress\uc2  should be sent home permanently. How long would any of us hold a job if we were that unproductive?\par \par \uc2 - Kenneth Sedbrook, Juda\par \par \uc2 Allow no 'border kids' to come to Madison\par \par \uc2 This recent effort by our illustrious Mayor Paul Soglin and his cohorts to import \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  children to Madison, house them and integrate them into our liberal society is mind-boggling.\par \par \uc2 To warehouse them, provide medical and hygiene service with interpreters, security and administrative personnel is not the way for Madison to provide jobs.\par \par \uc2 We have enough migration of people who seek good benefits in Madison. We do not need to assist a dysfunctional federal government with this dilemma.We all feel the hurt for these children and will support charities at the site, but not on our doorsteps.\par \par \uc2 Let our mayor not make this a political issue. His energy can be better spent straightening out the municipal golf course mess.\par \par \uc2 Benevolence and socialism at taxpayer expense is not needed at this time.\par \par \uc2 - Donald Knapp, Madison\par \par \uc2 US policies provoked immigration mess\par \par \uc2 Tuesday's two editorials on the migration of children across our southern border fail to mention the policy reasons why this may be occurring.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 North American Free Trade Agreement\uc2  has allowed a huge influx of U.S. corn to Mexico, El Salvador, Guatemala and Honduras, which has caused the bankruptcy of small farmers in Central America.\par \par \uc2 Since they cannot successfully compete, some try to migrate to the United States to feed their families. Those left behind depend on their financial support. Parents may become separated from their children.\par \par \uc2 Deporting drug dealers back to their countries has caused an escalation of violence and death in those countries. Many children come to the United States because their only surviving parent is here, or because they are orphaned and homeless.\par \par \uc2 Our immigration policies and international trade agreements helped create the problems we now have. Before we once again jump to what looks like an "easy solution," a more thorough examination of the causes and long-term solutions is needed.\par \par \uc2 - Mary Trainor, Madison\par \par \uc2 US claim to help the weak is lip service\par \par \uc2 How unapologetically hypocritical the United States is. Now even U.S. citizens know our claim about being champions of human rights is mere lip service.\par \par \uc2 Our president and military leaders have seen fit to enter many theaters of battle in the name of human rights over the past five years. We tell the world we will always fight injustice against people with little means of adequately defending themselves.\par \par \uc2 Yet nowhere has the fighting and death toll been so lopsided as in Palestine. Instead of helping the victims, we send hundreds of millions of dollars in military aid to Israel, the aggressor. The Palestinians have nowhere to go to escape except the refugee camps that are still in Palestine.\par \par \uc2 We preach against the likes of \uc2 al-Qaida\uc2  and at the same time support the largest religious extremist organization on Earth.\par \par \uc2 - Derek Rideout, Madison\par \par \uc2 Keep seeking peace in our violent world\par \par \uc2 Our world has always had hot spots of violence. Just in the last century, we've had two world wars, the Cold War and conflicts in Korea, Vietnam and the Middle East. Conflict is nothing new.\par \par \uc2 But now we seem to be experiencing a continuous increase in hostility and violence. Israel vs. Palestine. Sunnis vs. Shiites. Syria. Libya. Iran. Iraq. Afghanistan. North Korea. Existing governments vs. rebels and insurgents. Russia vs. Ukraine.\par \par \uc2 Then there are American Republicans vs. Democrats. Kids in Gang A shooting kids in Gang B in too many American cities. Random gunmen shooting people in American schools, malls and even hospitals. Respect for human dignity and life is extremely low across the world.\par \par \uc2 The Bible tells us "Thou shalt not kill" and "Love your neighbor as yourself." The old John Lennon song says, "All we are saying, is give peace a chance."\par \par \uc2 Whether for religious or secular reasons, where has the attempt to adhere to those principles gone? More importantly, how do we get it back?\par \par \uc2 - Terry Schmeckpeper, Onalaska\par \par \uc2 Suing of Obama an affront to taxpayers\par \par \uc2 In an unprecedented move, the \uc2 U.S. House of Representatives\uc2  has voted to sue the president. This action isn't just an insult to President \uc2 Barack Obama\uc2 , it's an outrage and abuse of House Speak \uc2 John Boehner\uc2 's power.\par \par \uc2 If this is the best \uc2 Congress\uc2  has to offer, we're in trouble. With all the problems around the world, illegal immigrants crossing our border, getting our troops home and getting our veterans the care they need in a timely manner, \uc2 Congress\uc2  has better things to do than sue the president.\par \par \uc2 The taxpayers are getting the short end here, folks. Tell Boehner to get back to the jobs at hand. See the list above.\par \par \uc2 - Lynn Ketchum, Madison\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020140805ea840000e\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 SUNDAY OPINION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc15}{\*\bkmkend toc15}\b \uc2 SHOULD AMERICA ALLOW MORE LEGAL IMMIGRATION?\b0\par\par\uc2 2,101 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 July 2014\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par E2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2014 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.  \par \par \uc2 Millions of jobless Americans is also a crisis\par \par \uc2 Last Sunday's editorial stated our legal immigration level is a mere "trickle." An average of around one million legal immigrants have entered the United States annually since 1990. If \uc2 the Senate\uc2  amnesty bill passed last June becomes law, it would mean even more.\par \par \uc2 To be sure, the thousands of Central American children entering this country illegally is heart-breaking, but this crisis exists because of the federal government's decades-long message that we are not serious about enforcing immigration laws.\par \par \uc2 And the biggest losers are the 18 million jobless Americans who want full-time work but can't find it. Why isn't their struggle to compete with immigrants in a dismal job market also viewed as a "humanitarian crisis"?\par \par \uc2 The editorial correctly states "our capacity for newcomers is limited." According to the \uc2 Pew Research Center\uc2 , immigration currently is responsible for 82 percent of our population growth and at this rate, our numbers are projected to reach 438 million by 2050.\par \par \uc2 At what number do we finally heed Earth Day founder Gaylord Nelson's warning that we "can't take all the people who want to come here"?\par \par \uc2 - Dave Gorak, LaValle, executive director, Midwest Coalition to Reduce Immigration\par \par \uc2 U.S. not serious about controlling immigration\par \par \uc2 The current mass immigration of children to the United States is being used as a tool to sell big increases in legal immigration. Never mind that the "trickle" of legal immigrants into the U.S. has averaged a million per year for the last quarter-century.\par \par \uc2 Some think we must have many more immigrants to assure America's economic success a perpetual motion machine.\par \par \uc2 There is no serious fence along most of the border, no requirement that employers electronically verify the Social Security numbers of employees. Deportation beyond the border area is focused on criminals.\par \par \uc2 Without changing these incentives, you can set any higher level of legal immigration and still have high illegal immigration.\par \par \uc2 As John Kass wrote in his column last Sunday, "Democrats are encouraging waves of unskilled labor from south of the border to compete for what few lowskilled jobs still exist." The bulk of our leadership is doing likewise.\par \par \uc2 - Chuck Litweiler, Madison\par \par \uc2 Allow more guest workers to come to America\par \par \uc2 Dairy farmers in Wisconsin are in desperate need of employees, and immigrants seem to be the best choice to fill the need.\par \par \uc2 The federal government provides a small number of guest worker certificates, far below the number actually needed.\par \par \uc2 Why can't that number be raised to truly meet the need? Latino workers would not have to die in the desert to find work. While living in Wisconsin, they would not have to bring family here but could return home several times a year to visit. Farmers would not have to hire undocumented workers.\par \par \uc2 Why does it need to be so hard to solve this puzzle?\par \par \uc2 - Marlene Hardick, Madison\par \par \uc2 Immigration policies do more harm than good\par \par \uc2 The sad immigration story just keeps getting sadder.\par \par \uc2 As a North American I am ashamed that we are treating people the same way as we would treat a rodent problem. Fellow humans are coming here because they are desperate and cannot survive in their own country, not because they expect a warm welcome and all their needs met here.\par \par \uc2 For our country's future, and for that of the world, children need their parents, safety, access to food, health care and education. These people are courageous beyond belief to make the trip, and to be arrested and deliberately "displaced" is cruel.\par \par \uc2 A recent letter-writer mentioned the potential of the children who have come. I would add the example given in a recent article of a 30-year-old who had been here since age 7, who had a good job and a wife and two daughters here when he was deported in 2010.\par \par \uc2 More harm than good will come from "displacing" people. We are separating families, removing children from the parental love and support they need, removing adults with no criminal past who are contributing members of our communities.\par \par \uc2 It's cruel, makes no sense, is a waste of time and resources and will hurt us in the long run.\par \par \uc2 - Jan Tymorek, Madison\par \par \uc2 Obama is willing to give our country away\par \par \uc2 Our country has a commander in chief devoid of leadership ability, which runs through his whole administration. The flow of illegal immigrants is to his advantage, just to stick it to his political opponents. Polls prove his feeling for this country is very shallow.\par \par \uc2 The people coming across the border, whether young children or adults, are illegal immigrants and should be shipped back.\par \par \uc2 Many of our men and women have served and many have made the ultimate sacrifice to protect the sovereignty and the borders of other countries, but President \uc2 Barack Obama\uc2  does not see fit to protect our borders. Why?\par \par \uc2 The question for liberal Democrats is when you give our country away, what else are you willing to give?\par \par \uc2 - Robert E. Schultz, Darlington\par \par \uc2 Today's protesters forget their immigrant ancestors\par \par \uc2 America has always had hard work to do. Except for the Indians, we are all late comers.\par \par \uc2 Immigrants have always come to this country with hope in their hearts, looking for something better. They got the worst jobs, worked hard, endured prejudice, and saved their earnings. They made sure their kids worked hard in school and had manners and respect for teachers and others.\par \par \uc2 When immigrants came here, they were greeted with prejudice and disdain.\par \par \uc2 It's no different today except the time and fashion. We have protesters dressed up in red, white and blue carrying signs, and shouting hateful phrases.\par \par \uc2 These individuals think nothing about how their ancestors felt when they came to America.\par \par \uc2 As a mob, protesters shout hate at little children and young mothers who are escaping countries ruined by our drug addiction. These broken, desperate families are drug lord refugees.\par \par \uc2 These protesters are part of a misogynistic political party, which stands directly against our American president and the thoughtful Americans who care for people, no matter what their race, sex or age.\par \par \uc2 - Daniel Holzman, Baraboo\par \par \uc2 Address the needs of children in U.S. first\par \par \uc2 This is a humanitarian crisis. All of the children in the United States who go to bed hungry every night is also a humanitarian crisis.\par \par \uc2 We can help these children from other countries who have crossed the border only when all of the children in this country are fed, clothed and have a place to sleep at night.\par \par \uc2 Let us address the needs of our children first, and the needs of others requiring our assistance second.\par \par \uc2 - Joyce Fichtel, Hillpoint\par \par \uc2 United States often the cause of refugee problems\par \par \uc2 The United States has a long history of creating refugee problems in other countries.\par \par \uc2 The Bay of Pigs betrayal has left us with a steady stream of Cubans since the 1960s. The Vietnamese and Hmong who survived after our partial evacuation still trickle in.\par \par \uc2 Our illegal invasion of Iraq caused refugee problems for all the surrounding countries while we methodically destroyed their infrastructure.\par \par \uc2 Now we are complaining about the Central American families who are trying to escape the death and destruction of warring drug gangs, which are fighting each other to service the United States' insatiable desire for illegal drugs.\par \par \uc2 We should not only welcome these people with open arms, but we should beg their forgiveness as they walk by.\par \par \uc2 - Rex Tilley, Brooklyn\par \par \uc2 Would Vatican help with immigrant children problem?\par \par \uc2 I saw on the Internet that the pope has weighed in on our flood of \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  minors. He has suggested compassion and support. Frankly, I'm gratified, and I think this is a good idea for two reasons.\par \par \uc2 First, I've heard that a proper facility to house the minors would require 90,000 square feet of space. Those dimensions could easily be found inside the Vatican, a great place to protect the children.\par \par \uc2 And certainly the \uc2 Vatican Bank\uc2  has the necessary financial resources to provide years of medical care for a host of Third World infirmities, funded educations and cradle-to-grave housing.\par \par \uc2 It's very important work and it should be an answer to his prayers that we allow him to help.\par \par \uc2 Second, and perhaps most importantly, the Vatican's "put your money where your mouth is" support would be a clear message to the rest of the world. It's easy for a foreign sovereign to carp about what's wrong with America. It's time they put up or shut up.\par \par \uc2 - Chico Buller, Sun Prairie\par \par \uc2 Veterans denied care while invaders' receive it\par \par \uc2 Every year we send millions in aid to the South American countries, this along with thousands of good American jobs.\par \par \uc2 But apparently these governments are doing little to help stop the flow of illegal immigrants coming through their borders to invade the United States. This is especially true with the Mexican government. Of course they don't want to stop them. Then it would become their problem to resettle them.\par \par \uc2 What if we stop all aid to these countries until they step up and help with the problem. At least then the aid money could be used to help with our costs.\par \par \uc2 We are spending money feeding, housing and clothing these invaders. This, while we already have thousands of legal American citizens, including many veterans, who are walking the streets, homeless, hungry and without jobs.\par \par \uc2 I don't care what the reason is, it's not fair when legal citizens who have paid taxes for many years and fought for their country are denied the basics of life while we take care of invaders. We need to close the border with federal troops.\par \par \uc2 - George E. Sutton, Cottage Grove\par \par \uc2 Misinformation leads people to send children here\par \par \uc2 Throughout history, floods of refugees into neighboring countries have posed a threat to the stability of those countries.\par \par \uc2 Erroneous information has apparently been spread throughout Central America that children coming to America would be allowed to stay. This mass assault on our border presents both an economic and a political threat.\par \par \uc2 Our nation's budget will be strained as we struggle to house and feed them as they go through our justice system. No matter how our government handles the situation, it will be targeted by political opponents for failing to protect our nation and its people.\par \par \uc2 Foreign anti-American forces could be at fault for this misinformation. But there are also home-grown forces, who see themselves, but not President \uc2 Barack Obama\uc2 , as "true Americans." Could they be the source of this misinformation?\par \par \uc2 These immigration problems make the Obama administration an easy target for those determined to blame our president for anything that happens in the world and at home.\par \par \uc2 - Karen Wagner, Wautoma\par \par \uc2 Secure our borders and enforce existing laws\par \par \uc2 We do not need a "sweeping change" in our immigration laws. And I don't think it is wise to increase the number of legal immigrants allowed into the United States.\par \par \uc2 We are hard pressed to employ our own people now. Why do we need more?\par \par \uc2 The only change we need is to properly enforce our existing laws and to secure our borders.\par \par \uc2 - Gary W. Sutherland, Brodhead\par \par \uc2 How many illeal immigrants will come to Wisconsin?\par \par \uc2 The Christian Science Monitor, in a July 2006 issue, had an article about "Operation Wetback." It indicated that in 1954, President Dwight Eisenhower, over the course of two years, deported around 1.3 million illegal immigrants from Mexico to help provide jobs for Americans.\par \par \uc2 In 1986, President Ronald Reagan was set to deport illegal immigrants when the Democrats persuaded him to declare amnesty. In return they promised the border would be secured. Their promise to secure the border was never kept.\par \par \uc2 Now, in 2014, it's strange that President \uc2 Barack Obama\uc2  doesn't think American workers need help. He is more interested in hiding the illegal immigrants by transporting them, some of whom may carry disease, all over our nation.\par \par \uc2 Madison Mayor Paul Soglin said last week that Wisconsin was to get some illegal immigrants here. The fact that the federal government is handling this so secretively makes you figure they are up to something. This will affect Madison's medical services, education and housing.\par \par \uc2 Why won't our government provide complete information?\par \par \uc2 - Joyce McRoberts, New Glarus\par \par \uc2 Caption: MATT YORK Associated Press Protesters gather near the entrance to an Oracle, Ariz., juvenile facility Tuesday in an effort to stop a bus load of Central American immigrant children from being delivered to the facility.  \par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020140730ea7k0005y\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 SUNDAY OPINION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc16}{\*\bkmkend toc16}\b \uc2 MORE VIEWS\b0\par\par\uc2 1,693 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 June 2014\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par E2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2014 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.  \par \par \uc2 Illegal immigrant\uc2  ?crisis' seems to trump VA ?scandal'\par \par \uc2 The Obama-manufactured deluge of thousands of illegal immigrants from Central America, most of them children, now taking place along our border with Mexico is being called a "humanitarian crisis."\par \par \uc2 But the thousands of veterans who died waiting to be treated by the mismanaged Veterans Administration is merely a "scandal."\par \par \uc2 One wonders whether federal officials now furiously trying to find relocation centers across the nation for these illegal immigrants are addressing the VA's disgraceful conduct with the same intensity.\par \par \uc2 Not likely, because in the case of the former, what we're looking at is another generation of Democratic voters, right? ? Dave Gorak, La Valle, Midwest Coalition to Reduce Immigration\par \par \uc2 Make State Street vehicle-free to support cafes\par \par \uc2 A Wednesday front-page article, "City considers ordinance to shrink sidewalk cafes," discussed a way to give State Street pedestrians more walking room. Wow, what a regressive approach to this problem!\par \par \uc2 Why not consider what many European cities have done: take a signature street and turn it into a pedestrian- and bicycleonly thoroughfare.\par \par \uc2 I have experienced these areas and they are delightful, serving as a mecca to draw people into a friendly shopping and eating zone. Why not have something like this for Madison's signature street?\par \par \uc2 There is no reason to have buses going up and down this six- block stretch. The restaurants could expand their outdoor seating areas, there would be plenty of room for pedestrians and bikes, and this could become an amazing place to visit in Madison.\par \par \uc2 It sure would be better than having smaller restaurant seating areas with diesel-belching buses ruining the atmosphere.\par \par \uc2 Progressive Madison should try to be progressive in responding to this issue.\par \par \uc2 ? Joseph Tripalin, McFarland\par \par \uc2 Common-sense gun laws are sorely needed\par \par \uc2 Grown men showing off their guns at parks, stores and coffee shops in Wisconsin is dangerous and ludicrous.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 National Rifle Association\uc2  and its advocates want everyone to carry guns everywhere and use them to protect against criminals. This lacks common sense. How can we distinguish a law-abiding citizen from a citizen who's not in two seconds?\par \par \uc2 We've fallen down the slippery slope, pushed by those who love their guns so much they can't be reasonable or admit that others may not wish to carry guns. This could be simply for moral purposes ("Thou shalt not kill") or because they want to live in a civilized society where problems are not solved by shooting first and asking later.\par \par \uc2 We have rights as well, to life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness. Living in fear is not happiness. Trampling on others' rights does not constitute freedom.\par \par \uc2 Our legislators should stop listening to gun lobbyists and enact common-sense laws. Laws restricting the use of guns won't prevent all tragedies, but they will help establish acceptable behavior and influence the culture in our communities.\par \par \uc2 ? Brenda Thomas, Madison\par \par \uc2 Religion in government fraught with danger\par \par \uc2 In Iraq, the Sunnis and Shiites are killing each other again.\par \par \uc2 They were born in the same country and speak the same language. Both are believers in Islam, but differ in interpretations of their Koran.\par \par \uc2 The Sunnis say they are being mistreated by the Shiites, who are now in positions of power in the government, while the Shiites seem to be getting even for the many years they were mistreated while the Sunnis were in power.\par \par \uc2 It's crazy ? almost as if Catholics and Protestants were killing each other over some details in the Bible.\par \par \uc2 Wait a minute! I almost forgot Catholics and Protestants actually were killing each other for many years, in Europe, except when they weren't busy killing Jews.\par \par \uc2 Would somebody remind me, again, why it would be a good thing if we had more religion in government?\par \par \uc2 ? Art Naebig, La Valle\par \par \uc2 What would Jesus do about O'Connor Center?\par \par \uc2 In \uc2 Chris Rickert\uc2 's June 17 column, "Church exemption burdens taxpayers," he writes about the \uc2 Catholic Diocese\uc2  of Madison manipulating plans for the future of the Bishop O'Connor Center with the purpose of avoiding payment of property taxes.\par \par \uc2 It appears apartments planned for the building would be in competition with other businesses that pay property taxes. However, the church is calling them "benevolent apartments' because there will be amenities associated with them aimed at seniors looking for a religious living environment.\par \par \uc2 The Catholic Church uses its interpretation of Scripture to support its signature opposition to artificial birth control, abortion and gay marriage.\par \par \uc2 Apparently the church is unfamiliar with the Bible passages in Matthew 22:21, and Mark 12: 17, in which Jesus says "Therefore render to Caesar the things that are Caesar's, and to God the things that are God's."\par \par \uc2 In other words, Jesus said "Pay your taxes."\par \par \uc2 ? Philip M. Neis, Madison\par \par \uc2 We all deserve good government\par \par \uc2 The author of a recent letter titled "Use your vote wisely this fall" quotes the well-known epigram of philosopher Joseph de Maistre: "People get the government they deserve."\par \par \uc2 Actually, de Maistre was wrong about that. Germans did not deserve Hitler, Russians did not deserve Stalin, and China did not deserve Mao Zedong. Add your own to the list.\par \par \uc2 Everyone deserves good government, and they deserve to have the knowledge of how to peacefully rid themselves of bad government.\par \par \uc2 De Maistre had the bad luck to have his philosophy summarized for posterity by the most foolish thing he said.\par \par \uc2 ? John Morgan, Madison\par \par \uc2 Consider elk herd when setting wolf hunt quota\par \par \uc2 Regarding last Sunday's guest column by Ron Weber, "Bears vs. wolves in northern Wisconsin," I also hope the decision regarding the wolf hunting quota is based on science.\par \par \uc2 If it is, the quota will be doubled for the wolf hunt. The stated plan is to reduce the population to 350 wolves statewide, yet the quota is always set too low.\par \par \uc2 What about the Wisconsin elk herd, which is not increasing as it should be due to the increased predation from wolves?\par \par \uc2 Elk were also native animals wiped out many years ago, but the pro-wolf people care little about the progress of the elk herd.\par \par \uc2 There is room for both, but the wolf population must be reduced in number for the elk to make it and increase.\par \par \uc2 ? Gary W. Sutherland, Brodhead\par \par \uc2 Redskins\uc2  name is not respectful\par \par \uc2 I don't buy the argument that the \uc2 Redskins\uc2  name is a sign of respect.\par \par \uc2 A recent letter writer used the example of Vikings noting that they are often portrayed as "mean, grumpy and bloodthirsty men." Most people I know don't like, let alone respect, mean, grumpy and blood-thirsty men. Instead, we fear them, because they are intimidating and unpredictable.\par \par \uc2 That is the reason some schools choose powerful and destructive forces of nature, such as cyclones, avalanches, blizzards and lightning as their mascots. We don't revere and admire hurricanes and tornadoes. We are simply afraid of their power. Some schools even use devils and demons as their mascots. They don't choose those nicknames out of respect for Satan.\par \par \uc2 Finally, identifying a group of people by the color of their skin is not a show of respect. We no longer refer to Asians as yellow- skinned or Hispanics as brown-skinned for the same reasons we no longer refer to Native Americans as \uc2 Redskins\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 ? Dave Edgerton, Madison\par \par \uc2 Marriage makes parents responsible for children\par \par \uc2 In a Thursday letter, "Marriage and parenthood are distinct issues," the writer reminds us that people made babies for millennia before we had marriage.\par \par \uc2 However, as civilization advanced, we found that societies functioned much better when the mother and father were clearly identified as responsible for their children.\par \par \uc2 That was formalized as the institution of marriage. In fact, were it not for the prospect of natural children, we would not have the institution of marriage.\par \par \uc2 Obviously, gay couples cannot have natural children.\par \par \uc2 But I must admit that the biggest problem with marriage in our culture is not gay marriage but rather the flood of non-marital births.\par \par \uc2 These children seldom have a committed father, and the results are bad.\par \par \uc2 Data suggests they are more likely to not finish high school, to use drugs, to commit crimes, and to live in poverty.\par \par \uc2 This is because our society does not recognize that the purpose of marriage is to provide a stable, protecting home for children, not just to express love between the couple.\par \par \uc2 ? Wayne Shockley, Brooklyn\par \par \uc2 Marriage is more than a legal contract\par \par \uc2 Reducing marriage to only a legal contract as presented in Thursday's letter, "Marriage and parenthood are distinct issues," is necessary for the legitimization of same-sex marriage.\par \par \uc2 However, marriage is much more than a legal contract. It involves a deep personal unity that includes the union of one flesh; requiring indissolubility and faithfulness in mutual self-giving and is open to fertility.\par \par \uc2 Civil society requires a legal dimension to marriage due to its concern for permanent unions of mothers and fathers.\par \par \uc2 The common good is best served when children are raised by their biological parents together in one home.\par \par \uc2 Reductionism of the sacredness of marriage is all the rage at this time. What the consequences will be remains to be seen.\par \par \uc2 ? Monsignor Roger J. Scheckel, Richland Center\par \par \uc2 Procreation only possible with a male and female\par \par \uc2 A letter in Thursday's paper, "Marriage and parenthood are distinct issues," referenced a previous letter to the editor, "Existence is due to the mother and father."\par \par \uc2 The writer of Thursday's letter totally missed the point.\par \par \uc2 The facts of biology and procreation are very basic. In order to procreate it takes a male and a female. Males cannot procreate with males, and females cannot procreate with females.\par \par \uc2 The same-sex couples today who are demanding equal this and equal that are here in this world because of a male and a female, a sperm and an egg.\par \par \uc2 If the entire world were made up of only same-sex couples, and no surgical intervention existed to facilitate procreation, the human race would become extinct.\par \par \uc2 That is a biological fact. It has nothing to do with marriage or a marriage contract.\par \par \uc2 ? Amanda Kemnitz, Madison\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020140630ea6t0001l\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 SUNDAY BEST\par {\*\bkmkstart toc17}{\*\bkmkend toc17}\b \uc2 'ENRIQUE'S JOURNEY' CONTINUES TO UNFOLD ; UPDATE\b0\par\par\uc2 DOUG ERICKSON  Wisconsin   \par \uc2 DOUG ERICKSON , Wisconsin State Journal , derickson@madison.com , 608-252-6149\par \uc2 411 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 March 2014\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par G3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2014 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Three years ago, more than 1,000 people showed up at Union South to hear Pulitzer Prize-winner Sonia Nazario discuss "Enrique's Journey," her harrowing and true account of a 16-year-old Honduran boy's attempts to reach the U.S. as an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  in order to join his mother.\par \par \uc2 The book was \uc2 UW-Madison\uc2 's selection that year for its "Go Big Read" community-reading project. It has only grown in popularity since then.\par \par \uc2 Last month, \uc2 Random House\uc2  issued a revised and updated version that includes a new chapter on immigration, a Q&A with Nazario, and an epilogue on Enrique that is almost as gripping as the original story.\par \par \uc2 "What has happened to him is really a reflection of what has been happening to so many immigrant families here," said Nazario, who lives in the Los Angeles area but was born in Madison and visits here often. Her brother is a senior systems programmer at UW- Madison.\par \par \uc2 As for the update on Enrique, he was partying with friends at a motel in 2011 when police officers arrived, Nazario said. He had an outstanding arrest warrant for not paying a ticket for driving without a license, she said.\par \par \uc2 He was arrested and handed over to federal immigration authorities to be deported. "He spent the next 14 months locked up for that," she said.\par \par \uc2 During this time, Enrique was separated from his girlfriend and their two children. So again, a family was torn apart, Nazario said. "This is the real fallout from U.S. policies," she said. "Families are being separated in reverse now."\par \par \uc2 Ultimately, Enrique received a visa to stay in the U.S. legally due to the work of pro bono lawyers - "a miracle," Nazario said. Many are not so fortunate.\par \par \uc2 About 200,000 parents of children who are American citizens were deported between 2010 and 2012, and 5,000 parentless children are now in foster care because their mother or father was detained or deported, she said.\par \par \uc2 "The issues are more urgent than ever with the number of these kids surging," she said.\par \par \uc2 "Enrique's Journey" has now been selected as the common read by 66 universities, 12 cities and scores of high schools. Nazario said \uc2 UW-Madison\uc2  remains her largest common-read experience by sheer number of books distributed.\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020140317ea3g0002i\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 LOCAL\par {\*\bkmkstart toc18}{\*\bkmkend toc18}\b \uc2 DRIVER IN FATAL CRASH TO RETURN TO HONDURAS ; HE VOLUNTARILY WILL GO BACK AFTER THE U.S. CHOSE NOT TO DEPORT HIM\b0\par\par\uc2 DENNIS PUNZEL  Wisconsin   \par \uc2 DENNIS PUNZEL , Wisconsin State Journal , dpunzel@madison.com , 608- 252-6179\par \uc2 518 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 July 2013\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2013 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 A driver who caused a crash that killed a Prairie du Sac man in 2011 was released from jail Thursday and plans to return to his native Honduras as soon as possible.\par \par \uc2 Hugo A. Alfaro-Gomez, 25, pleaded no contest in April to charges of homicide by negligent driving and causing great bodily harm by reckless driving that resulted in the crash on Highway 12 and Highway K that killed Richard D. Lemoine, 65, and seriously injured his wife, Linda.\par \par \uc2 But Alfaro-Gomez was ruled to not be responsible for the crash because he was afflicted with psychosis at the time.\par \par \uc2 Originally, \uc2 U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement\uc2  had a hold on Alfaro-Gomez and his lawyer, Assistant Public Defender Luis Cuevas, anticipated that deportation proceedings would begin as soon as Alfaro-Gomez was released.\par \par \uc2 ICE, however, later dropped its hold, leaving open the possibility for Alfaro-Gomez to remain in the U.S. He then requested that he return to Honduras.\par \par \uc2 Dane County Circuit Judge William Hanrahan approved a plan in which Alfaro-Gomez will be monitored by the state Department of Health Services until the paperwork can be completed for him to return to Honduras. He'll live with relatives in the area until then.\par \par \uc2 "He's a fish out of water here," said Cuevas. "Mentally, it's more beneficial to him to go back to his home country. He will have the support of his mother and family members. He wants to go back. We discussed that and that's what he wants."\par \par \uc2 Cuevas said it could take several months to work out the details of that return.\par \par \uc2 "Given what happened here I think it's important that he's supervised," Cuevas said. "He has no objection. He certainly feels bad as to what happened. It's regrettable. He understands that he'll be protected and the public will be protected."\par \par \uc2 The Lemoines' son, Josh Lemoine, said he was disappointed that immigration officials released their hold on Alfaro-Gomez after the plea agreement.\par \par \uc2 "It's pretty clear that his mental health is unstable and he's a risk to public safety being here," Josh Lemoine said. "He's an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 , and it's just disappointing that ICE doesn't step up to the plate and do their part in the case."\par \par \uc2 Linda Lemoine was suffering from colon cancer at the time of the accident and was to have started chemotherapy. But that was delayed because of the injuries she suffered in the crash, which caused her to be hospitalized for more than three weeks. She died Oct. 28, 2012.\par \par \uc2 "Our family has been through so much with losing my dad and my mom," Lemoine said. "The accident shortened my mom's life and took what time we would've had with her away from us. It's always going to be a piece of our life."\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020130720e97j0000c\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 The Cap Times\par {\*\bkmkstart toc19}{\*\bkmkend toc19}\b \uc2 MEDIA BEGIN TO DROP THE I-WORD AS IMMIGRATION REFORM TAKES PLACE ; MADISON\b0\par\par\uc2 Pat Schneider   \par \uc2 Pat Schneider\par \uc2 606 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 April 2013\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 All\par 9\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2013 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 From April 4\par \par \uc2 Big news for the movement to drop the term "\uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 ."\par \par \uc2 The Associated Press, whose stylebook is a sort of bible of word usage for traditional media, on Tuesday dropped its endorsement of "\uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 ." "Illegal" from now on should be used only to describe actions, not people, say AP executives.\par \par \uc2 Major newspapers, including the New York Times and the Los Angeles Times, also are considering changing their style sheets to drop the term. Not only is it offensive to many, critics say, it is an oxymoron because someone who is an "immigrant" is by definition someone who has legal status to live permanently in the United States.\par \par \uc2 A change in newspaper style usually goes unnoticed by anyone outside a newsroom, but this one has people weighing in on \uc2 Twitter\uc2  and other online discussions. Fox News and other conservative news outlets have characterized the move as "cheerleading" in advance of expected immigration reform in Congress.\par \par \uc2 A campaign to Drop the I-Word, launched by the online news source Color-Lines, has been under way for a couple of years. But momentum is building as Democrats ? and most Republicans smarting from immigrant communities' firm embrace of President Obama in 2012 ? agree that this is the year to pass comprehensive immigration reform. The White House is pressing for fast action, including a vote in the Senate as early as this month.\par \par \uc2 What people are called is more than a matter of semantics, says Salvador Carranza, president of the Latino Education Council of Dane County. "It affects how the general public perceives people who are here to make a better life and contribute their best to the country," he told me. "It's very important."\par \par \uc2 People who stay in the country after a visa expires may have violated the civil regulations governing immigration, Carranza told me. Those who re-enter the United States after being deported may be guilty of a misdemeanor, he admitted, but many are trying to return to support their families. "How is that a crime?" he asked.\par \par \uc2 "No person is ?illegal.' It has always been offensive to many people, especially immigrants," Carranza argued.\par \par \uc2 Carranza, long active in the grass-roots Latinos United for Education and Advancement, said the group worked for years to get local newspapers and TV stations to drop the I-word. He even stopped returning calls for comment from Wisconsin State Journal reporters a couple of years ago when the paper decided to stick to AP style.\par \par \uc2 State Journal City Editor Phil Brinkman told me that the newspaper will continue to adhere to AP style as much as possible. In a newsroom memo, Brinkman said he characterized AP's move away from "\uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 " as a positive change overall.\par \par \uc2 "I've long had a problem with the ?nounification' of groups of people. I have always advised reporters to wherever possible not put labels on groups of people, but describe the situation," he said.\par \par \uc2 "Illegal immigration" is a term that will continue to be used in the paper, because without labeling anyone it conveys that people who stay in the country on an expired visa or sneak in without one are "willfully violating U.S. immigration law," Brinkman told me.\par \par \uc2 At The Capital Times, Managing Editor Chris Murphy said we have not had a formal policy on the use of "\uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 " but informally have avoided it in recent years and will continue to do so.\par \par \uc2 Caption: ISTOCK People march in downtown Los Angeles in 2010 to demand immigration reform.   \par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020130411e94a00015\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 OPINION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc20}{\*\bkmkend toc20}\b \uc2 YOUR VIEWS\b0\par\par\uc2 882 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 March 2013\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A11\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2013 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 You'd think liberals would support school vouchers\par \par \uc2 Lost in the partisan debate about the merits or demerits of school vouchers is the issue of individual choice and the ability of parents to measure educational quality.\par \par \uc2 If true liberals were consistent, they would rally for vouchers. After all, liberals are for the choice of terminating a fetus, the choice of spending government transfer payments (like food stamps or unemployment payments) on whatever the recipient wants, even the choice of an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  wanting to cross the border to the United States.\par \par \uc2 And probably the greatest educational voucher ever ? the G.I. Bill ? grants veterans the choice of where to go to college. Yet we can't allow parents to choose where they send their children to school?\par \par \uc2 Regarding educational standards, is that not also a choice? Charter schools are not exempt from the public's wrath if the school selected does not perform. The parents can simply leave and send their children to another school. But when it comes to K-12 education, the public is required to pay for public schools but has no choice if the schools don't perform.\par \par \uc2 School vouchers should be supported by liberals, not opposed. Give those who are not able to pay tuition an opportunity to choose the school of their choice.\par \par \uc2 ? Ray Unger, Madison\par \par \uc2 Stroebel should focus on jobs, not iffy 'problems'\par \par \uc2 Rep. Duey Stroebel, R-Saukville, should be working on jobs.\par \par \uc2 He doesn't seem to have much to do lately. Over the past few weeks he has been working on legislation geared to solve problems that don't exist. The first non-problem was early voting. Duey introduced legislation that specifically targeted Madison's and Milwaukee's\par \par \uc2 SEND YOUR VIEWS\par \par \uc2 Send your letter, 200 words or less, to wsjopine@madison.com or to Letters to the Editor, P.O. Box 8058, Madison, WI 53708. Please include your full name, address and phone number for verification.\par \par \uc2 early registration schedules. This is another piece of legislation designed to suppress Democratic votes. It should be thrown out in the courts or by the Government Accountability Board.\par \par \uc2 Duey's second effort is to raise the retirement age for public employees before they can collect pension benefits. The rationale for this legislation is flimsy, at best, and not based on reasonable research, as pointed out by Employee Trust Funds.\par \par \uc2 The intent seems to be to punish public employees for being public employees. Since he knows little about the pension system, he should leave it alone.\par \par \uc2 I would think Duey would be more concerned with the horrible jobs record the Republicans have, and would spend his time seeking industry that would flourish in this state.\par \par \uc2 ? John Wilson, Dane\par \par \uc2 Don't confuse Easter's God with Puritan God\par \par \uc2 In columnist Steve Chapman's Sunday piece on the "tyranny of the virtuous," he argues we must "let people make their own decisions even if they have some impact on others." This is probably necessary in a free country.\par \par \uc2 What bothers me about this column is that many readers will blame religion ? in particular Christianity ? for this "tyranny of the virtuous." This is justified because the loudest Christian voice in our country is that of the Puritan God who needs his people to enforce good behavior.\par \par \uc2 However, the God of this Easter season is not that God. As a father he has made all of his children, both good and bad. As the son, he has become a human being who has forgiven every human being's acts of misbehavior. Through the voice of the Holy Spirit, God tells us "Since you are God's loved children, free of all guilt, then behave like God's children and tell others about the father/ son/spirit God in words and actions."\par \par \uc2 The Puritan God is so much like us that if we are not looking for the father/son/spirit God in worship, in reading the Bible and in prayer, then the Puritan God will come through loud and clear.\par \par \uc2 ? John Torgerson, Wisconsin Dells\par \par \uc2 Healthy choices are worth being mandated\par \par \uc2 Steve Chapman's libertarian diatribe against Michael Bloomberg's pro-health measures in New York City is so full of hyperbole that it hardly advances rationale debate.\par \par \uc2 Indeed, use of the term "tyranny of the virtuous" or comparing Bloomberg's pro-health campaign to sexual Puritanism or Salem witch hunts seems rather sophomoric. Chapman seems to long for the days when restaurants and bars were filled with smoke, leaving patrons with the "choice" of not going to those establishments if they don't like the pollution.\par \par \uc2 Yes, people are free to "make their own decisions," but does Chapman really think we would have made any inroads in the control of tobacco illnesses without the anti-tobacco movement and lawsuits that hit the purveyors of death in their wallets?\par \par \uc2 I care less about banning large, sugary drinks, but I would like retailers to offer smaller options at lower cost. The normalization of large size drinks and candy bars has as its primary purpose the advancement of financial profit. Has Chapman been to a movie theater lately and seen the size and cost of the sodas they sell?\par \par \uc2 Consumers like me want smaller options, not libertarian rhetoric.\par \par \uc2 ? Ron Berger, McFarland\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020130320e93j0000l\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 FRONT\par {\*\bkmkstart toc21}{\*\bkmkend toc21}\b \uc2 REPORT: KILLER TAUNTED GRIEVING MOTHER ; THE JUDGE ORDERS BAIL OF $1 MILLION TO PREVENT HIM FROM BEING DEPORTED.\b0\par\par\uc2 ED TRELEVEN   \par \uc2 By ED TRELEVEN etreleven@madison.com 608-252-6134\par \uc2 678 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 July 2012\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2012 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 After running over and killing their 2-year-old son with his SUV, Jesus Castillo-Dimas laughed at his former girlfriend and taunted her as she kneeled over the dead boy's body.\par \par \uc2 "There's nothing you can do now, neither one of us are going to have him now," Castillo-Dimas said to her, according to a criminal complaint filed Friday. "I told you you would pay for it."\par \par \uc2 The complaint charged Castillo-Dimas with first-degree intentional homicide for killing Yandel Castillo-Castillo and three counts of attempted first-degree intentional homicide for trying to kill his ex-girlfriend, Maria del Rosario Castillo-Castillo and her new boyfriend, Miguel A. Menendez-Ruvalcaba.\par \par \uc2 Dressed in a suicide prevention smock, Castillo-Dimas, 30, was in Dane County Circuit Court on Friday where he was ordered jailed on $1 million bail. Assistant District Attorney Mary Ellen Karst said she asked for high bail to keep him from posting bail, then being deported by the federal Immigration and Customs Enforcement agency, which has Castillo-Dimas on a hold as an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 . Karst said she wanted to be sure Castillo-Dimas remains in Dane County so he can be prosecuted.\par \par \uc2 The criminal complaint tells a gruesome story.\par \par \uc2 Menendez-Ruvalcaba told Fitchburg police not only did Castillo- Dimas run over his own son with his SUV and hit the boy's mother, he backed up and ran over Yandel a second time.\par \par \uc2 Police officer Doug Heimerl, who was among the first on the scene, described seeing the boy's crushed head and his body still under the rear driver's side tire of Castillo-Dimas' Ford Explorer.\par \par \uc2 Castillo-Castillo knelt over the boy, crying, blood on her face and clothing. Menendez-Ruvalcaba was restraining Castillo-Dimas, Heimerl saw, and saying over and over, "He's the one who was driving, he's the one who did this."\par \par \uc2 Officer Denise Miller, also at the scene, heard Castillo-Dimas say in English, "I love her," and "She spent last night with him and I love her."\par \par \uc2 According to the complaint:\par \par \uc2 Menendez-Ruvalcaba told Fitchburg police he was returning from lunch with Castillo-Castillo and her son when Castillo-Dimas followed them into the driveway at 2111 Red Arrow Trail. He confronted Castillo-Castillo about dating Menendez-Ruvalcaba, then said, "You are all going to pay for it."\par \par \uc2 Turning to Menendez-Ruvalcaba, Castillo-Dimas said, "You will see what's going to happen to you, you will see."\par \par \uc2 As Castillo-Castillo and Yandel walked up the driveway, hand in hand, the boy started to say, "Pa, pa, pa, pa," and Menendez- Ruvalcaba turned to see Castillo-Dimas drive toward the pair and hit them. He said he watched in shock as Castillo-Dimas put the SUV in reverse and run over his son again, leaving him with severe head injuries.\par \par \uc2 Castillo-Dimas then emerged from the SUV with a knife in his hand and stabbed at Castillo-Castillo, telling her, "I'm going to kill you."\par \par \uc2 Menendez-Ruvalcaba fought with Castillo-Dimas, trying to grab the knife, but in the process was cut badly on his right hand and stabbed in the abdomen. He held Castillo-Dimas down for police and watched as Castillo-Castillo kneeled over the boy saying, "You killed our son, you killed our son."\par \par \uc2 That was when Castillo-Dimas laughed and taunted her.\par \par \uc2 Castillo-Castillo, in court Friday wearing a neck brace and being pushed in a wheelchair by members of the District Attorney's staff, was hospitalized with a cut that just missed her carotid artery, Dr. Angela Gibson of UW Hospital told police. She also had a deep cut on her head, Gibson told police.\par \par \uc2 Caption: Ed Treleven - State Journal Interpreter Liesl Monroy, left, speaks Friday with Jesus  Castillo- Dimas, charged with first-degree intentional homicide, in  Dane County Circuit Court. At right is lawyer Gina Bosben.   \par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020120715e87e00003\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 77 SQUARE\par {\*\bkmkstart toc22}{\*\bkmkend toc22}\b \uc2 'LE HAVRE' CHARMS WITH QUIRKY CHARACTERS\b0\par\par\uc2 ROB THOMAS   77 Square   \par \uc2 ROB THOMAS 77 Square\par \uc2 562 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 March 2012\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par 17\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2012 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 It's rare and welcome to watch a movie that, reflexively, assumes people will do the right thing at the slightest provocation. That's the case with the charming comedy "Le Havre," set in France but made by Finnish writer-director Aki Kaurismaki ("The Man Without a Past").\par \par \uc2 We first meet Marcel Marx (Andre Wilms), living in the port city of Le Havre in Normandy, passing his days as a shoeshine man in the local train station. He looks like a distinguished old Frenchman, but he seems like a big kid at heart, reveling in stealing loaves of bread from a local shopkeeper on the way home from work. When he gets home, dinner isn't ready, and his wife (Kati Outinen) sends him out to the bar for an aperitif the way mothers send their sons out to play.\par \par \uc2 On one of those jaunts around town, he comes across a young African boy named Idrissa (Blondin Miguel) hiding in the water near the pier. The boy was smuggled out of Africa in a shipping container, hoping to reconnect with his father in London. Marcel, without giving it a second thought, decides to hide the boy from the immigration authorities who want to deport him. When he asks for help from his neighbors, even that shopkeeper he swipes bread from, they instantly spring into action.\par \par \uc2 As Marcel tries to figure out a way to get Idrissa out of Le Havre and off to London, "Le Havre" becomes sort of like a comedic version of "The Visitor," the Richard Jenkins drama about a widowed professor who befriends a Senegalese \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  and his wife. The film is dryly funny, as when Marcel attempts to visit one of Idrissa's relatives in a deportation facility and insists "I'm the family albino."\par \par \uc2 Kaurismaki heightens the comedy with unexpected framings, sometimes having the characters stare silently and directly into the camera or just to the side, or filming them in close-up and then backing away, the opposite of a zoom shot.\par \par \uc2 But the film's light tone is played against a very serious backdrop of immigration, especially in France, where the influx of Muslim immigrants has become a political hot-button topic. Kaurismaki gently makes fun of xenophobia, and the futility of immigration laws, but underneath the chuckles there's a sense of sorrow at the damage those laws can do.\par \par \uc2 The movie is full of odd, off-kilter moments, like an off-camera gun battle between criminals that opens the movie, and then is never referred to again. Or when the film takes a break from the story for a full performance from a gray-haired Le Havre rockabilly legend named "Little Bob."\par \par \uc2 Kaurismaki seems to be winking at us as he guides his characters towards happy endings, a couple of which openly strain credibility. "Miracles do happen," one character says, to which another responds bitterly, "Not in my neighborhood." But Le Havre turns out to have a few miracles left there after all.\par \par \uc2 LE HAVRE\par \par \uc2 ***\par \par \uc2 Andre Wilms, Blondin Miguel\par \par \uc2 Not rated\par \par \uc2 1 hour 33 minutes\par \par \uc2 Opens Friday at Sundance\par \par \uc2 "The Visitor," "Monsieur Ibrahim," the lighter side of the immigration debate\par \par \uc2 Caption: JANUS FILMS  Andre Wilms and Jean-Pierre Dassoulin star in the  quirky comedy "Le Havre."   \par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020120309e8380001k\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 FRONT\par {\*\bkmkstart toc23}{\*\bkmkend toc23}\b \uc2 CLASSES MEANT TO INFORM, ENLIGHTEN MADISONIANS ; CITY'S \uc2 ILLEGAL IMMIGRANT\uc2  POPULATION IS GROWING.; IMMIGRATION\b0\par\par\uc2 GEORGE HESSELBERG   \par \uc2 By GEORGE HESSELBERG ghesselberg@madison.com 608-252-6140\par \uc2 761 \uc2 words\par \uc2 31 August 2011\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2011 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 All it takes is a peek into the kitchen of your favorite restaurant, behind the garden shed of a condominium or into the hearing rooms of the state Capitol and you will get a notion of the growing importance of immigration issues in Wisconsin.\par \par \uc2 A series of weekly classes at James Reeb Unitarian Universalist Congregation that begins Sept. 18 is designed to introduce Madison residents to the issues - social, legislative, legal and economic - faced by the city's silent population of illegal immigrants.\par \par \uc2 "Very few Madisonians actually personally know undocumented immigrants, or any immigrants," said Leila Pine, a retired Madison lawyer who has split her time between Madison and Arizona the past decade, working with that growing population and a faith-based humanitarian group called No More Deaths.\par \par \uc2 "You are educating yourself," she said. "Fear comes from lack of knowledge, a sense of loss of control. When you educate yourself, the fear tends to disappear."\par \par \uc2 Dane County's documented Hispanic population today is about 25,000, according to census data published by the Pew Hispanic Center.\par \par \uc2 "The Latinos are the fastest-growing minority in the country and nobody knows for sure how many undocumented there are. But in Dane County, for every one documented, there is at least one undocumented," Pine said.\par \par \uc2 With four bills coming through the Legislature identified by advocates as affecting immigrants, and with continuing nationwide attention that has grown out of Arizona's laws, Pine said the time is ripe to bring context to the local discussion.\par \par \uc2 The classes' topics are broad, from the causes and history of immigration, economics and security, beneficiaries of the current system, and solutions.\par \par \uc2 What's different, said Pine, is that questions will be answered by experts.\par \par \uc2 "The purpose (of the classes) is not to try and tell people how to think. It is to provide accurate information that lets them draw their own conclusions. No proselytizing," she emphasized.\par \par \uc2 Though the church, 2146 E. Johnson St., is sponsoring the series, this is not a course on religion, she said.\par \par \uc2 "We're looking at the system through a moral, not a religious, lens," she said.\par \par \uc2 Among those scheduled to speak are Christine Neumann-Ortiz, executive director of Voces de la Frontera in Milwaukee; Salvador Carranza, president of Latinos United for Change and Advancement; Fabiola Hamdan, a social worker at Joining Forces for Others, and Luis Yudice, a former Madison police captain who's now coordinator of safety and security for the Madison School District and head of the Dane County Task Force on Immigration.\par \par \uc2 IF YOU GO | IMMIGRATION CLASSES\par \par \uc2 WHAT: "Immigration as a Moral Issue," a series of classes to help people understand the complex issues and history of the immigration debate.\par \par \uc2 WHEN: Six consecutive Sundays starting Sept. 18, from 2 to 4 p.m., at James Reeb Unitarian Universalist Congregation, 2146 E. Johnson St.\par \par \uc2 TO REGISTER: Email Leila Pine, sabinosanctuary@gmail.com, or call the James Reeb Unitarian Universalist Congregation, 608-242-8887, and leave a message requesting a registration slip. The registration deadline is Saturday, and the cost is $15.\par \par \uc2 PENDING LEGISLATION\par \par \uc2 The statewide immigrant rights organization Voces de la Frontera has identified these four bills currently in the Legislature as affecting immigrants negatively. The analyses are from the Legislative Reference Bureau.\par \par \uc2 Senate Bill 107: Prohibits local governments from enacting ordinances that limit a residential landlord's ability to obtain and use personal information from tenants and prospective tenants, including income and source of income, occupation, court records, rental history, and credit information.\par \par \uc2 Senate Bill 137: Makes companies that hire workers who are not legally in the United States ineligible for certain tax exemptions, governmental contracts, grants and loans.\par \par \uc2 Assembly Bill 173:\par \par \uc2 Based on laws passed in Arizona and Alabama, requires local law enforcement to check the immigration status of a person who is arrested or charged with a crime or civil violation if the officer has reasonable suspicion the person is in the country illegally.\par \par \uc2 Under the bill, a law enforcement officer may not consider a person's race, color, or national origin except as permitted under the U.S. and the Wisconsin constitutions.\par \par \uc2 Assembly Bill 222:\par \par \uc2 Requires documents proving citizenship or satisfactory immigration status for public assistance programs.\par \par \uc2 Caption: STEVE APPS  State Journal   A reflection of Madison's growing Hispanic population can be seen  in billboards in Spanish. Several along Park Street and Fish  Hatchery Road, for example, promote telephone services.   \par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020110901e78v00004\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 CHRIS RICKERT\par \uc2 LOCAL\par {\*\bkmkstart toc24}{\*\bkmkend toc24}\b \uc2 PRIDEMORE'S IMMIGRATION BILL SEEMS MISGUIDED\b0\par\par\uc2 CHRIS RICKERT   \par \uc2 CHRIS RICKERT\par \uc2 540 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 June 2011\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2011 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 It almost would be worth seeing state Rep. Don Pridemore's immigration bill become law just to show how misguided its premise is and how reluctant most of the criminal justice system would be to implement it.\par \par \uc2 The bill requires police to detain anyone who is arrested on a civil or criminal violation who can't provide identification proving legal residence in the United States. If after 48 hours the suspect still can't cough up a driver's license, permanent resident alien card or one of several other documents specified in the legislation, police would be required to notify federal immigration officials.\par \par \uc2 And they would do ... what?\par \par \uc2 It "depends," according Leticia Zamarripa, a spokeswoman with U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement. If we're talking about a person stopped for one of the minor violations that make up the vast majority of the criminal justice system's workload, Zamarripa reminded me ICE's "focus is on criminal aliens."\par \par \uc2 ICE agents "can't turn a blind eye" to evidence of possible undocumented status, she said, but action in any such case "just depends what our resources are," and "ICE has very limited resources."\par \par \uc2 In other words, if you think the Feds are going to rush in to deport an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  caught going 55 in a 45 mph zone, I've got a bridge over the Rio Grande I'd like to sell you.\par \par \uc2 This correlates with what I heard about local authorities from Michael Scott, a former Madison cop and head of the UW-Madison- based Center for Problem-Oriented Policing.\par \par \uc2 "Nobody in the local criminal justice system would put very high on their priority list the deportation of otherwise law-abiding immigrants," Scott said, as the infrastructure of American local law enforcement - police, jails, district attorneys, etc. - tend to make more serious crimes the main focus of their limited time and money.\par \par \uc2 To this criticism, Pridemore pointed to a fatal crash in April in Milwaukee allegedly caused by a drunk \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  and said most criminals start small and work their way up. If the authorities had the power to deal with budding criminals of the \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  variety early on, he suggested, couldn't tragedies like this be avoided?\par \par \uc2 Of course, you could say the same of budding criminals in the country legally. Shall we deport them or lock them up for long periods just to prevent them from committing worse crimes on our soil later?\par \par \uc2 I don't mean to minimize the seriousness of entering the U.S. illegally or to suggest we should simply throw open our borders to anyone.\par \par \uc2 But tailoring the punishment to the crime and making fiscally rational choices about when to crack down on lawbreakers are just as important to the operation of a just, efficient and effective criminal justice system as a single-minded focus on catching every lawbreaker, every time.\par \par \uc2 Seeking to deport an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  for speeding is not only unrealistic, it's poor crime fighting.\par \par \uc2 Contact Chris Rickert at 608-252-6198 or crickert@madison.com, as well as on \uc2 Facebook\uc2  and Twitter (@ChrisRickertWSJ). His column appears Tuesday, Thursday, Saturday and Sunday.\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020110603e76200009\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 LOCAL\par {\*\bkmkstart toc25}{\*\bkmkend toc25}\b \uc2 Officials investigating whooping crane deaths\b0\par\par\uc2 State Journal staff, wire services\par \uc2 733 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 January 2011\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A4\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2011 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 ALBANY, Ga. - Wildlife authorities are investigating the deaths of three whooping cranes in south Georgia.\par \par \uc2 The three cranes were released in October in Wisconsin as part of a program to reintroduce the birds to the eastern United States.\par \par \uc2 The birds were found by hunters in Calhoun County, just west of Albany, on Dec. 30.\par \par \uc2 U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service spokesman Tom MacKenzie said the deaths are considered suspicious since the birds were found together. He said a predator would generally kill a single bird at a time. A landowner told authorities that the birds were in the area several weeks before they were found dead.\par \par \uc2 Necropsies are expected to be complete in about two weeks.\par \par \uc2 Fitchburg police look into stabbing\par \par \uc2 FITCHBURG - Police reported they are investigating a stabbing that happened during a domestic dispute Tuesday night.\par \par \uc2 Officers responded to the 4500 block of Thurston Lane for a report of a stabbing, according to a news release from Fitchburg police, and found a male with a stab wound.\par \par \uc2 He was taken to a local hospital with non-life threatening injuries.\par \par \uc2 No arrests were made, and the incident remains under investigation.\par \par \uc2 Beloit hunter accidentally shot when exchanging gun\par \par \uc2 BELOIT - A 30-year-old Beloit man killed on Christmas Eve while hunting with his son was shot accidentally when the two were exchanging the victim's rifle, according to findings released Tuesday by the Rock County Sheriff's Office.\par \par \uc2 Patrick Preston died Dec. 24 after suffering a gunshot wound to the abdomen. Preston was hunting in a partially wooded area in the town of Newark in Rock County with his 12-year-old son when the accident occurred.\par \par \uc2 "The preliminary autopsy results confirmed the detective bureau's findings that this incident was accidental in nature," said Sheriff Robert Spoden in a news release. "The fatal shot accidentally occurred as the father and son were exchanging the father's rifle."\par \par \uc2 Fewer than 600 died in traffic accidents in 2010\par \par \uc2 For the third straight year, fewer than 600 people died on Wisconsin highways in 2010 - numbers that haven't been seen since World War II years, when there were far fewer people and vehicles.\par \par \uc2 The state Department of Transportation issued its preliminary traffic fatality report on Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 In 2010, 564 people died in crashes in Wisconsin, more than the 542 in 2009 but less than the 687 in 2008.\par \par \uc2 "We are encouraged traffic fatalities are staying at levels not experienced since the early 1940s, when the number of vehicle miles traveled was minuscule compared to today," Transportation Secretary Mark Gottlieb said in a news release.\par \par \uc2 The December 2010 traffic death total was 38, making it the safest December on state roads since World War II.\par \par \uc2 River cities host bald eagle spotting events\par \par \uc2 A number of cities on the Wisconsin and Mississippi Rivers will offer bird lovers the chance to observe bald eagles over the next few weeks.\par \par \uc2 Sauk City and Prairie du Sac on the Wisconsin River will hold their 24th annual Bald Eagle Watching Days on Jan. 14-15. Cassville and Prairie du Chien, which lie on the Mississippi, will hold Bald Eagle Appreciation Day on Feb. 26.\par \par \uc2 Wisconsin wildlife officials estimate the state is home to about 1,150 pairs of eagles.\par \par \uc2 Hundreds of them congregate on the Wisconsin and Mississippi each winter, looking for fish in open water below dams.\par \par \uc2 Milwaukee man accused of killing woman, DUI\par \par \uc2 MILWAUKEE - A 41-year-old Milwaukee man is accused of driving drunk the wrong way on Interstate 94 on Saturday, slamming head-on into another car and killing a woman.\par \par \uc2 Leopoldo Salas-Gaytan, 41, was charged Wednesday with homicide by intoxicated use of a vehicle, homicide by intoxicated use of a vehicle with a prohibited alcohol concentration and operating without a license, causing death.\par \par \uc2 Police said Salas-Gaytan was driving drunk the wrong way on Interstate 94 when he slammed into another car driven by Corrie Damske, of Wauwatosa, killing her.\par \par \uc2 According to the criminal complaint, Salas-Gaytan said he had been going to rehab for alcohol addiction but drank a 12-pack of beer and possibly more.\par \par \uc2 He's also accused of drinking while driving and throwing cans out the window.\par \par \uc2 Salas-Gaytan remained hospitalized Wednesday with a leg injury.\par \par \uc2 Salas-Gaytan admitted to being an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 , the Milwaukee County sheriff's department said.\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020110107e7160000f\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 LOCAL\par {\*\bkmkstart toc26}{\*\bkmkend toc26}\b \uc2 TEEN SENTENCED IN SHOOTING ; 17-YEAR-OLD GETS 2 YEARS IN PRISON FOR INVOLVEMENT IN APRIL KILLING\b0\par\par\uc2 ED TRELEVEN   \par \uc2 By ED TRELEVEN etreleven@madison.com 608-252-6134\par \uc2 485 \uc2 words\par \uc2 13 November 2010\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 A second teenager involved in a fatal confrontation with a rival gang member was sentenced Friday to two years in prison after pleading guilty to a lesser charge.\par \par \uc2 Victor E. Prado-Velasquez, 17, told the family of Antonio Perez that he was sorry for his involvement in the April 28 incident that ended with Perez being shot by another man.\par \par \uc2 "When I get out, I want to change my life, go to church and be a different person," said Prado-Velasquez, a former Verona High School student.\par \par \uc2 A plea agreement reduced the charge against Prado-Velasquez from first-degree intentional homicide to felony murder, which carried a maximum sentence of 15 years of combined prison and extended supervision. Dane County Circuit Judge Maryann Sumi accepted the agreement and sentenced him to two years in prison with five years of extended supervision to follow.\par \par \uc2 Prado-Velasquez's prison time will be shortened by just over six months because of the time he has spent in custody since his arrest in May.\par \par \uc2 Prado-Velasquez was in a car with four other people when they spotted Perez, 19, taking a break from work outside \uc2 Webcrafters\uc2 , 2211 Fordem Ave.\par \par \uc2 According to a criminal complaint, the group confronted Perez about being a member of a rival gang when Ivan Mateo-Lozenzo, 21, shot Perez.\par \par \uc2 Mateo-Lozenzo and Billy Wenner-Say, 24, remain at large. Wenner- Say's girlfriend, Karen Giron-Cruz, 20, is in custody awaiting a trial.\par \par \uc2 Franklin Yanez, 16, also was convicted of felony murder and received eight years of probation. Yanez is at a juvenile correctional facility serving time for other crimes. As an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 , he'll likely be deported when he is released. Prado- Velasquez is a U.S. citizen.\par \par \uc2 Assistant District Attorney Corey Stephan said Prado-Velasquez's involvement in Perez's death was minimal, adding that it was unlikely he expected anyone to be shot during the confrontation with Perez.\par \par \uc2 Sumi added, however, that the shooting wouldn't have happened at all "if the shooter didn't have that ring of people around him," emboldening him.\par \par \uc2 Stephan said Prado-Velasquez has given credible statements to investigators and will testify against his co-defendants.\par \par \uc2 Still, Perez's family expressed bitterness toward Prado- Velasquez.\par \par \uc2 "I will always hate him for what he did," said Estrella Perez, a sister of Antonio Perez. "My family is suffering. Every day we think about (Antonio), especially now with the holidays coming."\par \par \uc2 "I hate him. I hate him for what he did to my family," said another sister, Elizabeth Perez. She said her brother alone cared for his 2-year-old daughter.\par \par \uc2 "You took away everything from her," she said to Prado- Velasquez. "Everything she lived for, you took away."\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020101114e6bd00004\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 LOCAL\par {\*\bkmkstart toc27}{\*\bkmkend toc27}\b \uc2 Alleged drug dealer now faces weapons charge\b0\par\par\uc2 State Journal staff\par \uc2 817 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 October 2010\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A4\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 MADISON - An alleged drug dealer reportedly known on the streets as the "Mayor of Middleton" was charged Wednesday in federal court with being an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  in possession of a firearm.\par \par \uc2 Cecil Villagarcia, 41, is accused of possessing Beretta .40 caliber and 9mm pistols on Oct. 15, according to an indictment filed in U.S. District Court in Madison.\par \par \uc2 Villagarcia was charged Oct. 20 in Dane County Circuit Court with maintaining a drug place, possession of cocaine with intent to deliver and violating a harassment restraining order. He is being held in Dane County Jail.\par \par \uc2 Middleton police executed a search warrant at Villagarcia's Pondview Road duplex after a confidential informant told them that Villagarcia has been has been dealing cocaine in the Middleton and Madison area for several years, according to court documents.\par \par \uc2 Republican governors pitch Walker at rally\par \par \uc2 OAK CREEK - Governors from three southern states told Wisconsin voters Wednesday that the Republican strategies of cutting taxes and shrinking government worked in their states, and gubernatorial candidate Scott Walker could make them work here too.\par \par \uc2 Louisiana Gov. Bobby Jindal, Virginia Gov. Bob McDonnell and Mississippi Gov. Haley Barbour appeared with Walker at a rally in the Milwaukee suburb of Oak Creek as part of a three-city tour that started in Newton, Iowa, and was set to wrap up in Homer Glen, Ill.\par \par \uc2 Several polls show Walker, the Republican Milwaukee County executive, leading his Democratic opponent, Milwaukee Mayor Tom Barrett. Barrett had planned to spend Wednesday campaigning at schools in Eau Claire, Rhinelander and La Crosse, but he canceled due to bad weather.\par \par \uc2 Walker said the governors have been his inspiration when people ask him how he'll create jobs and make government smaller.\par \par \uc2 When asked whether Wisconsinites would care what governors from three distant states had to say, Jindal told The Associated Press the basic principles are the same everywhere: Americans need leaders who can balance budgets, create jobs and cut taxes - and Walker is the man to do those things for Wisconsin.\par \par \uc2 Graeme Zielinski, a spokesman for the Democratic Party of Wisconsin, said the state would take a step backward if it took its leadership cues from states like Barbour's.\par \par \uc2 DNR board scales back emergency cave rules\par \par \uc2 MADISON - The state Department of Natural Resources' board on Wednesday scaled back emergency provisions to stave off a deadly bat disease, refusing to allow the agency to close commercial caves or force cave-goers to decontaminate themselves for the next six weeks.\par \par \uc2 The DNR had proposed a set of emergency provisions last week that would have granted the agency the power to inspect caves and mines for the fungus that causes white-nose syndrome. The regulations also required cave and mine visitors to decontaminate themselves, banned out-of-state cave and mine equipment in Wisconsin and allowed the DNR to unilaterally close caves and mines to bats or humans.\par \par \uc2 The Natural Resources Board, though, tweaked the provisions under pressure from cave owners and spelunkers, who complained the DNR was moving too fast and didn't inform them of the rules' details.\par \par \uc2 The DNR has been scrambling to prepare for the onset of white- nose syndrome. The white-nose fungus grows on hibernating bats, causing them to wake up and starve to death.\par \par \uc2 Madison woman faces felony DUI charge\par \par \uc2 MADISON - A 50-year-old Madison woman was arrested for her fourth drunken driving offense early Tuesday morning, after her claim that she swerved to avoid an oncoming truck didn't hold up, Madison police said.\par \par \uc2 The truck was legally parked, police said. Sandra Dary was tentatively charged with felony drunken driving, imprudent speed and possession of drug paraphernalia following her arrest at the East Side intersection of Fairmont and Burke avenues.\par \par \uc2 According to the incident report, Dary's car ended up in a ditch after her vehicle struck the parked truck.\par \par \uc2 Prison sentences in tax and mortgage fraud case\par \par \uc2 MADISON - Two defendants in a tax fraud and mortgage fraud scheme have been sentenced to time in federal prison.\par \par \uc2 Former real estate agent Carlos Solis, 33, of Morrisonville, was sentenced to 18 months in prison and former tax preparer Marty Mendez, 27, of Sun Prairie, was sentenced to a year and a day in prison, both by U.S. District Judge William Conley in federal court in Madison on Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 Solis pleaded guilty in May to a charge of bank fraud, while Mendez pleaded guilty in May to a charge of assisting in the filing of a false income tax return.\par \par \uc2 According to the U.S. Department of Justice, the mortgage fraud scheme involved filing false tax returns through a Park Bank mortgage loan program, resulting in losses of more than $400,000 to the bank.\par \par \uc2 The tax fraud scheme defrauded the IRS out of about $900,000, through fraudulent claims for dependents and child tax credits.\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020101029e6as00003\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 John Nichols\par \uc2 Opinion\par {\*\bkmkstart toc28}{\*\bkmkend toc28}\b \uc2 Our give-and-take with Walker, other contenders\b0\par\par\uc2 John Nichols   \par \uc2 John Nichols\par \uc2 896 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 October 2010\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 All\par WEB\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 The Capital Times editorial board met this week with Scott Walker, the Republican nominee for governor who is very much under attack by the Democratic Party, unions and liberal interest groups. It is no secret that The Capital Times has usually backed Democrats in recent years - just as we usually backed Progressives in the 1930s and 1940s and Republicans in the 1910s and 1920s.\par \par \uc2 The Capital Times has always been a progressive newspaper. But progressivism has never been the province of one party. Since the paper's founding, in the heady days when Wisconsin Sen. Robert M. La Follette was challenging the war profiteers of World War I and other corporate interests, we have always chosen principle over party. And that has meant that, in every election season, we have found Democrats and Republicans to back. We have also backed independents and third-party candidates, recognizing that the two big parties do not begin to define the range of reasonable debate.\par \par \uc2 Walker, a political veteran whose fascination with Wisconsin elections and policymaking goes back to his youth, has earned our praise and criticism over the years. When he served in the Legislature, he was one of favorite Republicans. And he knows we respect that he is running to be governor of the whole state of Wisconsin, not just the conservative wing of the Republican Party. That does not mean that we agree with Walker on most issues. In fact, quite the opposite is the case. But Walker is up for the debate and interested in looking for areas of common ground; that's to his credit. It is, as well, what distinguishes him from the extreme positioning of Republican Senate candidate Ron Johnson, who has tended to avoid serious discussions about issues and ideas.\par \par \uc2 In general, this year's sessions with the candidates of varying parties have been good-spirited and thoughtful. It serves as a reminder that, even in this hyperpartisan moment, there is still room for dialogue, debate and perhaps cooperation.\par \par \uc2 That does not mean that candidates can't be contentious. On Monday and Tuesday, Democrat Brett Hulsey and Green Ben Manski, the leading candidates in the Assembly District 77 race, came by. The candidates took some shots at one another, although I was impressed by the extent to which both of them emphasized their strengths. That appealed to me. As I have noted before in this space, I have worked on a host of democratic reform initiatives with the Liberty Tree Foundation, which Manski heads and on whose I have served. At the same time, I have known and written favorably about Hulsey for the better part of 15 years; during this campaign, he has been using a line I wrote about his work on the County Board on his literature and in radio commercials.\par \par \uc2 It may say something about the still relatively "small-town" nature of Madison that last month, both Hulsey and Manski attended a party at my home with Jim Hightower. (I was only sorry that my friend Dave Redick, the GOP candidate in the race, was not there. Dave's plan for a State Bank of Wisconsin has at least a tinge of Hightower-style populism to it.) Both Manski and Hulsey made good impressions on folks at the party; so much so that one fellow told me he wished they were running in different races so that he could vote for both of them. That may be a bit of a cop-out; Hulsey and Manski have enough honest differences to justify the race between the two. But the intelligence and energy these two candidates brought to our sessions this week was striking; they're both more focused, serious and informed than most legislators.\par \par \uc2 Of all the meetings we have had recently with candidates, the most striking for me was with Dane County Sheriff Dave Mahoney. The Capital Times editorial board endorsed Mahoney four years ago, but since then we have differed with him on some immigration questions. The Madison City Council recently voted unanimously to adopt a resolution disapproving of Mahoney's policy of contacting Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) authorities when someone appearing to be an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  is arrested, and we expressed sympathy with the council's view. When we met with Mahoney this week and immigration policy came up, however, he was not defensive. Rather, he offered a thoughtful and quite nuanced take on the issues involved. In particular, he outlined the many areas in which the Sheriff's Office has chosen not to cooperate with ICE.\par \par \uc2 Reasonable people will disagree with Mahoney on particular immigration questions, and I certainly believe that he needs to keep talking with (and learning from) his critics on this issue. But it is fair to say that our entire editorial board came away from the discussion with the sheriff struck by his sensitivity to the complex mix of human, political and law-enforcement issues that define the immigration debate.\par \par \uc2 John Nichols is the associate editor of The Capital Times. jnichols@madison.com\par \par \uc2 Copyright 2010 madison.com. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed.\par \par \uc2 .Posted in John_nichols on Thursday, October 14, 2010 4:55 am Updated: 11:34 am\par \par \uc2 Caption: Scott Walker MORRY GASH - Associated Press .   \par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020101218e6ae0001g\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Footnote\par \uc2 LOCAL\par {\*\bkmkstart toc29}{\*\bkmkend toc29}\b \uc2 '\uc2 Illegal immigrant\uc2 ' or 'undocumented worker': Is there a difference?\b0\par\par\uc2 328 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 August 2010\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Q. A tough new law in Arizona has put immigration in the spotlight. In discussing the issue, some people refer to 'illegal immigrants,' while others say 'undocumented workers.' Is there a difference?\par \par \uc2 A. As with anything related to immigration right now, the debate around terminology is heated.\par \par \uc2 Latino groups draw a clear distinction between the terms, arguing that '\uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 ' distorts the debate because it suggests the person is a criminal or dangerous.\par \par \uc2 The American Civil Liberties Union issued a brief on the issue in February and said the act of being present in the U.S. in violation of immigration laws is not, standing alone, a crime. 'Unauthorized presence in the U.S. is criminally punishable only if it occurs after an individual was previously formally removed from the U.S. and then returned without permission,' it said.\par \par \uc2 Many undocumented immigrants enter the U.S. legally but overstay their visas, which is a civil violation, not a crime, the ACLU said. That's the basis for the argument used by local groups such as Latinos United for Change and Advancement, which strongly opposes use of '\uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 ' and prefers 'undocumented worker.' The Associated Press stylebook, which guides usage at most U.S. newspapers, including this one, says '\uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 ' is preferred over 'undocumented worker.' News organizations have defended the usage over the years, saying people who break civil laws still are acting illegally and that 'undocumented worker' makes sense only in a story addressing employment.\par \par \uc2 David Minthorn, deputy standards editor for the AP in New York, said '\uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 ' is accurate and neutral for news stories. An immigrant is someone who comes into a country to settle, and illegal means a violation of the law, he said.\par \par \uc2 'Alternatives like 'undocumented worker,' 'illegal alien' or 'illegals' lack precision or may have negative connotations,' he said.\par \par \uc2 The State Journal follows AP style and uses '\uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 .' - Doug Erickson\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020100806e6850000o\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 SUNDAY OPINION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc30}{\*\bkmkend toc30}\b \uc2 Support groups don't see the whole picture ; Focus: Illegal Immegration\b0\par\par\uc2 1,189 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 August 2010\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par B2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 It's difficult to resolve a problem like illegal immigration when some of the key players, such as leaders of two support organizations, can't see the full picture themselves, according to their letters printed last Sunday. Neither writer offered a viable solution to the problem.\par \par \uc2 Salvador Carranza of LUCha contributes to the inflammatory hyperbole by insinuating that anti-illegal sentiment is driven by "lies and misinformation" by anti-illegal immigration groups. It's not, if you listen to the relevant group leaders.\par \par \uc2 And Patrick Hickey of the Workers' Rights Center wrote "...employers have an unreasonable amount of control over workers, making the situation ripe for exploitation". Clearly an uncontrolled employer/worker relationship like we have now is more likely to result in exploitation than one with government oversight.\par \par \uc2 Made-up "facts" do nothing but drive us further apart, making a solution more difficult. Pro-immigration leaders need to pay attention to the relevant facts about the issue such as the failure of amnesty, control of the border and the increasing crime rate among the Latino population.\par \par \uc2 - Rick Sanson, Lancaster\par \par \uc2 Root of problem is Mexico's instability\par \par \uc2 What a sad commentary it is on the growing discrimination towards Mexican immigrants. I admire their work ethic and salute those who get in line to obtain legal visas.\par \par \uc2 Unfortunately, the root of the problem is not the immigrants, but the state of affairs in Mexico. The immigrants flee to the United States for a better life away from drug lords, corruption and poverty. They miss their culture, climate and families. Some would just as soon stay in Mexico, but the chance for survival is dwindling.\par \par \uc2 We should concentrate on the bigger picture by helping Mexico to build its infrastructure for a more stable government.\par \par \uc2 I look forward to the day when, instead of building walls, we focus our energy on building greater relationships of cooperation in commerce and open travel throughout the Americas. Maybe I'm a dreamer, but it seems like we'd have a lot more to gain and could all feel better about ourselves in the long run.\par \par \uc2 - Kathleen Williams, Monona\par \par \uc2 Build prison in Mexicofor illegal immigrants\par \par \uc2 Illegal immigrants are a major part of our economic problem. Without solving this issue, I don't believe the economy can be fixed. And neither party has had what it takes to solve it.\par \par \uc2 Illegal immigrants overload our penal system, school systems, health care and social services system. Illegal immigrants rarely contribute to the tax base which funds these programs. Some use fake documents, including drivers licenses and Social Security cards.\par \par \uc2 The government must fix the \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  problem and ensure that there is an effective visiting worker program. The borders must be sealed and controlled, and those found to be here illegally must be sent back to their homelands. If this is not done, the U.S. economy will be pulled down to the level of Mexico.\par \par \uc2 It would be a good investment for a U.S. or Mexican business person to build a maximum security detention facility to house all illegal immigrants detained on U.S. soil. This facility should be built south of the U.S. border in the desert, and be run and funded by the Mexican government or private Mexican business people. House the captured illegal immigrants there rather than in U.S. prisons.\par \par \uc2 - John H. Pickle Jr., Lodi\par \par \uc2 Jobs are key - other issues are distracting\par \par \uc2 We have seized too many chances lately, and we have not gotten any of them right. Immigration will be no different.\par \par \uc2 We need jobs and more jobs, and we need them now. As for immigration, it could be done with a two-step plan.\par \par \uc2 First, secure the border and implement a better guest worker program immediately. Then provide a clear path to citizenship without any illegal immigrants bypassing legal immigrants in the process.\par \par \uc2 - M. W. "Jake" Jacobs, Pelican Lake\par \par \uc2 System works againsts killed legal immigrants\par \par \uc2 I am a member of Immigration Voice, a national organization of over 41,000 skilled legal immigrants (\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.ImmigrationVoice.org"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.ImmigrationVoice.org}}}\uc2  ). We are committed to sensible improvements to the employment-based immigration and green card process.\par \par \uc2 The immigration system is broken, causing hardship for families of highly-skilled immigrants. The wait times for employment-based green cards for highly-skilled workers could span six to 25 years, causing brain drain, which is hurting innovation, preventing creation of new jobs and hindering economic recovery.\par \par \uc2 I applaud Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., for his leadership in immigration reform. Recently Schumer shared his proposal for comprehensive immigration reform. This is a great first step in the right direction.\par \par \uc2 There are highly-skilled immigrants and members of Immigration Voice, including doctors, engineers, research scientists and professors, who are stuck in long green-card backlogs of over 25 years.\par \par \uc2 - Vidyadhar Gandikota, Madison\par \par \uc2 Political correctness thwarts enforcement\par \par \uc2 The country does not need to reform its immigration laws. What we need is proper enforcement of current laws.\par \par \uc2 We need to secure the borders, and require all law enforcement agencies to check on immigration status. We need to stop providing safe havens for illegal immigrants by not allowing law enforcement officers to do their jobs. We need to stop lawsuits against states that are trying to properly enforce the law.\par \par \uc2 The list could go on, but the fact is that common sense went by the wayside due to political correctness.\par \par \uc2 - Gary W. Sutherland, Brodhead\par \par \uc2 Charge employers who hire the undocumented\par \par \uc2 Congress and President Barack Obama need to enforce the Western Hemisphere Travel Initiative that requires a passport or other secure identification documents for travel to and from Canada, Mexico and the Caribbean.\par \par \uc2 The United States has many visa programs for guest workers. We do not need more. We need a law that goes after employers who knowingly hire illegal immigrants for profit and sends them to prison and fines them. Congress and the president should support the federal E-Verify program.\par \par \uc2 The troops should be brought back from Iraq, South Korea, Germany and other places and be used to secure the southern border.\par \par \uc2 - Kenneth Krivanek, Baraboo\par \par \uc2 Arizona acts when Obama and Dems don't\par \par \uc2 When was the last time we saw the president of the United States sue a state that is trying to protect itself from illegal rapists, kidnappers, human-traffickers, drug smugglers, murderers and possibly terrorists?\par \par \uc2 The answer is never! President Barack Obama is telling Arizona residents he's not going to protect you, and he won't let you protect yourselves either.\par \par \uc2 Is this the only way the Democratic Party can recruit new voters? Are there that many employers dedicated to getting cheap laborers in Arizona?\par \par \uc2 Arizona's law is exactly like the federal law, except in one respect: Arizona law forbids profiling (yes, specifically forbids profiling). Federal laws require people with green cards to carry their documents with them at all times. While travelling abroad, we Americans are required to carry our passports at all times.\par \par \uc2 If you are here legally, that should be mandatory. Deport those who don't have documents.\par \par \uc2 - Joyce McRoberts, New Glarus\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020100804e6810002x\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 FRONT\par {\*\bkmkstart toc31}{\*\bkmkend toc31}\b \uc2 MADISON SCHOOLS SET POLICY ON AGE PROOF ; THE CHANGE IS IN RESPONSE TO A FORMER STUDENT WHO LIED ABOUT HIS AGE AND IS NOW ACCUSED OF HOMICIDE.\b0\par\par\uc2 GENA KITTNER   \par \uc2 By GENA KITTNER gkittner@madison.com 608-252-6139\par \uc2 664 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 July 2010\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 The Madison School District will ask for proof of age when registering students who live with people other than their parents or guardians or those who are 18 years or older and are enrolling themselves for school.\par \par \uc2 The district disclosed the new procedure - which goes into effect next month for the 2010-11 school year - in a statement to the State Journal dated July 23 and received Monday.\par \par \uc2 The announcement comes three months after the revelation that a 21-year-old gang member charged in a fatal April shooting had enrolled in Madison's West High School and later transferred to Middleton High School under a fake name and age.\par \par \uc2 Ivan Mateo-Lozenzo, 21, was enrolled at Middleton High School as 18-year-old junior Arain Gutierrez at the time of the shooting. Middleton officials have said Mateo-Lozenzo, whom police have identified as an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  from Veracruz, Mexico, had transferred from Madison's West High School. "This change is made as a result of a review following that situation," Madison Superintendent Dan Nerad said in an interview Monday. "We're trying to get as much verification that we can. Understandably, there is probably no system that can be totally error-proof."Asking for proof of age will serve as a good "second-check" on information that is "provided with the student's standard registration forms and any information received from a former school," the district said in its statement to the newspaper. If documentation is unavailable, the district now will seek "a sworn statement from the person claiming knowledge of the student's age, which, if falsified, could subject the person to legal consequences."Don Johnson, superintendent of the Middleton-Cross Plains School District, which also has reviewed its enrollment policy, said the district will be more aggressive in asking for proof of age from students who don't provide it during registration.\par \par \uc2 "In every case, we'll make at least three attempts to get that birth certificate or proof of name or date of birth," Johnson said.\par \par \uc2 Still hunting for suspects\par \par \uc2 Mateo-Lozenzo; Billy Wenner-Say, 23, of Madison; Karen Giron- Cruz, 19, of Madison; Victor Prado-Velasquez, 16, of Fitchburg; and Franklin E. Yanez, 15, of Madison, have been charged with being party to first-degree intentional homicide in the slaying of Antonio Perez.\par \par \uc2 Perez, 19, was shot dead April 28 outside a Fordem Avenue business in what police are calling a gang dispute.\par \par \uc2 Giron-Cruz, Yanez and Velasquez have been ordered to stand trial. A trial for Giron-Cruz is slated for August. Yanez and Velasquez will have their final pretrial hearing next month, but no trial date has been set.\par \par \uc2 Madison police spokesman Joel DeSpain said Monday police still are looking for Mateo-Lozenzo and Wenner-Say.\par \par \uc2 Under current policy, the Madison School District only asks parents or guardians of students 17 or younger who are living with them to present a utility bill, a mortgage document or a lease with an address to enroll a child in school. School officials are directed to verify both the age and name of those students using a birth certificate or "other documentation provided by parent." But the federal McKinney-Vento Homeless Assistance Act of 1987 requires districts to enroll students even if they can't show identification.\par \par \uc2 While the Madison School District is requesting certain students to show proof of age, the law does not require such documentation to register, officials said.\par \par \uc2 Middleton-Cross Plains also requires a parent or guardian to show residency through a utility bill, lease or mortgage document. The district requires proof of age and identification through a birth certificate or passport when a student enrolls in kindergarten, but does not require it for later grades.\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020100728e67r0000q\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 SUNDAY OPINION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc32}{\*\bkmkend toc32}\b \uc2 Should Congress and President Barack Obama make immigration reform a major priority?\b0\par\par\uc2 2,295 \uc2 words\par \uc2 25 July 2010\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par B2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Old solutions failed, trynew ones, like E-Verify\par \par \uc2 Sunday's editorial was another rehash of the tired "solutions" to this nation's illegal immigration problem - beef up border security, hold employers accountable, put illegal immigrants on a path to citizenship and so on.\par \par \uc2 What it didn't offer is an explanation for how an eighth amnesty since 1986 would benefit any of the 25 million citizens and legal residents who, according to the Labor Department, can't find full- time jobs. Nor does it ask why the federal government approves of allowing 7 million illegal immigrants, according to the Pew Hispanic Center, to keep their jobs in non-agricultural industries.\par \par \uc2 When your editorial board calls for the Wisconsin delegation to support amnesty, isn't that what most of its members, especially U.S. Sens. Russ Feingold and Herb Kohl, have been doing all along? According to NumbersUSA, Feingold and \uc2 Kohl's\uc2  grade on coddling illegal immigrants to the detriment of American workers is a miserable F-.\par \par \uc2 Feingold in particular has attacked the federal E-Verify program that is the best tool we have to keep illegal immigrants out of jobs. I sent him information about E-Verify, but he continues to deny even those statistics provided by the Department of Homeland Security, which oversees E-Verify.\par \par \uc2 - Dave Gorak, LaValle,\par \par \uc2 executive director, Midwest\par \par \uc2 Coalition to Reduce Immigration Facts, not hyperbole,\par \par \uc2 need to propel reform\par \par \uc2 Two main things need to happen to adequately reform our dysfunctional immigration system.\par \par \uc2 First, we must recognize that undocumented immigrants are not criminals. They are human beings who deserve dignity and compassion. Over 6,000 immigrants have lost their lives in the Arizona desert searching for a better life for themselves and their families, more than 460 this year alone. Our current system doesn't allow them to come here with the proper documents.\par \par \uc2 Second, we must educate the public with the facts. Anti- immigrant groups have been using lies and misinformation to distort the public's perception of immigrants. For example, it's false that coming to the United States to look for work is a crime. In fact, being in this country without a visa is a civil violation, not a crime.\par \par \uc2 It's a myth that immigrants don't pay taxes and are a burden to our communities. In fact, most immigrants pay their fare share of taxes through payroll deductions, sales taxes and property taxes. Without them, key back-breaking industries such as agriculture and the dairy industry would collapse. And few American citizens are willing to take their places.\par \par \uc2 Unless we consider the facts and not inflammatory hyperbole, comprehensive immigration reform won't happen and our nation will suffer for it.\par \par \uc2 - Salvador Carranza, Madison,\par \par \uc2 Latinos United for Changeand Advancement (LUChA)\par \par \uc2 Politicians wary of this hot-button issue\par \par \uc2 The steps outlined in Sunday's editorial seem reasonable. The problem stems from the fact that the issue is susceptible to demagoguery. A news article in the same edition told of self- appointed "enforcement" by neo-Nazis and other vigilantes in Arizona.\par \par \uc2 As long as such strong xenophobia on the part of anti- immigration zealots remains, no president of either party will score any political points for advocating practical solutions to the problem, especially when candidates for office are all too willing to cater to the most narrow-minded among the electorate.\par \par \uc2 - Roger Dobrick, Madison\par \par \uc2 Talk of amnesty causes hike in border crossings\par \par \uc2 I agree with your four principles for reform. However, certain caveats must be expressed.\par \par \uc2 I'm a Wisconsin resident, but I live 36 miles from the Arizona border eight months of the year. I have photographed and documented the activities of illegal immigrants for over five years and give slide lectures to dozens of groups in several states, including Wisconsin.\par \par \uc2 A secure border is absolutely necessary before amnesty is even discussed. Several years ago there was a flurry of discussion in Washington about amnesty that had a devastating effect on Arizona and the desert. An area several miles long became covered with backpacks and debris dropped by illegal border crossers who heard about possible amnesty and wanted to be part of it, so they came across by the thousands. That area, littered with thousands of backpacks, is now referred to as "the amnesty trail."The border can absolutely be secured with a hard-to-climb bollard fence, which would allow agents to view the other side with cameras with a range of up to 10 miles. This would give border patrol officers ample time to send agents to a particular location ahead of the crossers.\par \par \uc2 Americans, including those of Hispanic heritage, are disgusted by possible amnesty offered to those who broke the law by jumping in front of fellow citizens trying to enter our country legally.\par \par \uc2 - Gary Meinert, Boulder Junction, Wis. and Green Valley, Ariz.\par \par \uc2 Guest worker programs were tried, and failed\par \par \uc2 I commend the State Journal for taking a thoughtful position on immigration reform, especially during the current storm of hyperbole and xenophobia.\par \par \uc2 But I disagree with expanding guest worker programs. These programs have a checkered history, from the controversial Bracero program of the 1960s to more recent problems with H-2B visa programs. These programs are often plagued by issues of exploitation and declining standards for U.S. workers. If job loss means deportation, employers have an unreasonable amount of control over workers, making the situation ripe for exploitation.\par \par \uc2 Five hundred people brought from India as temporary workers to repair oil rigs after Hurricane Katrina by Signal International did not feel like "guests." They felt like slaves. When they protested about treatment and conditions, ICE colluded with the employer to try to muzzle workers. Other countries, such as Germany and France, that have tried guest worker programs have run into serious problems.\par \par \uc2 These programs are just not the American way. People who come to this country to work should have all the rights and protections afforded all workers and should be encouraged to integrate into society as rapidly as possible. This is what has made this country such a dynamic, vibrant place.\par \par \uc2 - Patrick Hickey, Madison,\par \par \uc2 director, Workers' Rights Center\par \par \uc2 Consider ways to keep part of wages in U.S.\par \par \uc2 Get our troops from Germany and Japan back to the United States and place one soldier with each border patrol agent. If a person or company needs workers, use a lottery system at the border.\par \par \uc2 Regarding illegal immigrants, give them, at a small cost, a green card if they are employed, and make them get a drivers license, insurance and learn English.\par \par \uc2 Pay half their wages in script that has to be used in the United States. That way only half of their wages will be sent back to Mexico, the rest spent here. Currently most or all is sent back to Mexico, then they get food stamps, Medicaid and so on.\par \par \uc2 Deport any who don't have jobs, or make them join the military. After two years in the military with an honorable discharge, they could become U.S. citizens.\par \par \uc2 These are some things that need to be done to keep money from leaving the United States.\par \par \uc2 - Emil Rufener, Monticello\par \par \uc2 States must step up when feds fail to enforce\par \par \uc2 It amazes me how many politicians flunked math. With states cutting back police and fire departments and other utilities and social programs because of lack of funds, politicians will not admit that immigrants are one of the biggest drains on state resources.\par \par \uc2 In Arizona there are hundreds of thousands of illegal immigrants who need shelter, food, medical care and more. But they do not pay taxes for these services and feel it's their right to receive said services. Include the fact that crime rates in areas where illegal immigrants cross the border are high, which puts a strain on border patrol and local police departments.\par \par \uc2 Who is going to pay for all this? The federal government may want to sweep the immigration problem under the carpet and forget about it, but states cannot. They have to deal with the financial impact that illegal immigrants cause.\par \par \uc2 - Michyle S. Glen, Columbus\par \par \uc2 Immigration reform a matter of fairness\par \par \uc2 Immigration reform should be a major priority for both Congress and the president. Such reform should bring predictability and fairness for many groups affected by the current piecemeal and ill- considered system.\par \par \uc2 Much public attention is on the estimated 11 million immigrants who - most with no way to enter the U.S. legally regardless of how long they wait - have entered illegally in search of better lives for themselves and their families.\par \par \uc2 But they are by no means the only group that would benefit from a change in American immigration law. Employers could have a way to confirm whether a job applicant is legally entitled to work here through a much more accurate and less cumbersome system. Immigrant employees and potential employees could receive the worker protections they are entitled.\par \par \uc2 Young people brought to the United States illegally as children could have a way of earning American citizenship. People entitled to legal entry to the United States but now facing a daunting waiting period could have that waiting period reduced.\par \par \uc2 Many other improvements are being considered and could be implemented. Immigration reform is critical to confidence in the fairness and resolve of the American government.\par \par \uc2 - Welcome Fawcett, Madison\par \par \uc2 It's only effort to get at Hispanic voter bloc\par \par \uc2 Who's doing more racial profiling than Arizona these days? The Democratic Party.\par \par \uc2 President Barack Obama and his Democratic cronies will try to shove immigration "reform" down America's collective throat before the November elections, if possible, but at least before 2012. Their reasons are cynical if not dishonest.\par \par \uc2 Racial profiling is at the heart of their mission. Develop a path to legalizing illegal immigrants - the majority of whom are Hispanic - under the assumption that they will vote for Democrats to say thanks and because of the misguided belief that Democrats will take better care of them. This mirrors how Democrats have historically taken African-American votes for granted. How's that working out?\par \par \uc2 These are strategies on which the Obama regime bases its anti- Arizona and pro-\uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  positions. It's not about federal jurisdiction or keeping families together. It's political and contrary to how this president promised he would govern. Again, Obama lies.\par \par \uc2 If the opportunity remains, Democratic legislators must be removed in November. If not, we can forget about 2012 and brace for the destruction of our democracy. Those of all genders, races and creeds with their hands in the treasury will unwittingly destroy it.\par \par \uc2 - Mark S. Peterson, Verona\par \par \uc2 Realistic reform requires concessions\par \par \uc2 The barrier to new immigration legislation is the last point recommended in Sunday's editorial: "Create a program to permit most of the estimated 11 million illegal immigrants now living in the United States to earn legal residency.""Comprehensive immigration reform" has become code for letting almost all illegal immigrants become voting citizens. Most conservatives, and probably most of the American people, reject that. Most liberals, and most Hispanics, demand it. Resolving this issue will require concessions on both sides.\par \par \uc2 First, it makes no difference which laws are on the books if the government can't or won't enforce them.\par \par \uc2 Second, there is much variety among the illegal immigrants. Some would be welcome as citizens in any country. But those who just recently came looking for work should be deported without hesitation. The status of millions of others falls in between.\par \par \uc2 Conservatives must admit that it's logistically impossible as well as cruel to uproot millions of people who have established lives here. Consider it our national penance for not enforcing laws in the past. Liberals must concede that not every person who touches American soil should be guaranteed residency, much less a path to citizenship.\par \par \uc2 Both sides need to quit using the word "all" when referring to illegal immigrants. Then reasonable people can work out criteria to decide who should stay and who should not.\par \par \uc2 - Wayne Shockley, Brooklyn\par \par \uc2 Close border because of drug gang threats\par \par \uc2 We need to completely close our border with Mexico before we do anything else.\par \par \uc2 The drug gangs in Mexico are murdering people in large numbers just south of our border. We have to stop them from getting a foothold in this country.\par \par \uc2 Just what is immigration reform? I think we are doing the right thing now, only it's too little, too late.\par \par \uc2 Several years ago we tried the amnesty scheme, which was only to buy votes. After that the situation just got worse because the illegal immigrants realized we weren't going to enforce our laws anyhow.\par \par \uc2 If people knew what illegal immigration is costing Arizona in free health care and education, you would want to follow their lead.\par \par \uc2 - Wesley Geringer, Black Earth\par \par \uc2 Amnesty will increase flow of Mexicans to U.S.\par \par \uc2 Last October, \uc2 Zogby International\uc2  released a poll they had run in Mexico to learn what peoples' reactions would be to immigration amnesty (sometimes referred to as a "path to citizenship").\par \par \uc2 Of Mexicans with a member of their immediate family in the United States, 65 percent said a legalization program would make people more likely to go illegally. Of those polled, 36 percent would move to the United States if they could, a figure comparable to the 33 percent found by a Pew Research poll conducted about the same time.\par \par \uc2 Sixty-nine percent thought the primary loyalty of Mexican- Americans should be to Mexico. The same percentage thought the Mexican government should represent the interests of Mexican Americans in the United States.\par \par \uc2 This poll didn't seem to receive any coverage or discussion in the mainstream press here.\par \par \uc2 - Chuck Litweiler, Madison\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020100727e67p0001p\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Front\par {\*\bkmkstart toc33}{\*\bkmkend toc33}\b \uc2 SCHOOLS HAMSTRUNG BY ID LAW ; DISTRICTS ARE REVIEWING POLICIES IN WAKE OF KILLING SUSPECT'S ENROLLMENT USING A FAKE NAME AND AGE.\b0\par\par\uc2 GENA KITTNER   \par \uc2 By GENA KITTNER gkittner@madison.com 608-252-6139\par \uc2 796 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 June 2010\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Even if local school districts wanted to require all students to show a birth certificate or other identification before enrolling, they'd still have to let in students who don't produce one under a federal law requiring the immediate enrollment of homeless students.\par \par \uc2 The Madison and Middleton-Cross Plains school districts are reviewing their enrollment policies after police say they discovered a 21-year-old gang member charged in a fatal April shooting had enrolled in Middleton High School under a fake name and age.\par \par \uc2 After six weeks, neither district has announced enrollment policy changes.\par \par \uc2 Middleton-Cross Plains superintendent Don Johnson said in an e- mail to parents concerned about the matter that the district is "reviewing all options within state and federal law to determine additional screening and verification of identity for all students enrolling."\par \par \uc2 But the federal McKinney-Vento Homeless Assistance Act of 1987 requires districts to enroll students even if they can't show identification, officials said.\par \par \uc2 "What we have found so far is that we are significantly hindered by McKinney-Vento legislation which covers homeless children and the law regarding undocumented students," Johnson said in an e- mail to a parent. "The summary that we have compiled ... has not revealed a fix that is adequate at this point."Lisa Soronen, a lawyer for the National School Boards Association, said it's understandable that asking for identification when enrolling appears to be a simple solution to parents worried about safety. However, such a requirement may be tantamount to asking about a student's immigration status, which is problematic under Supreme Court precedent. "Some of the obvious easy solutions have other problems," Soronen said.\par \par \uc2 Parents want stronger oversight\par \par \uc2 The revelation that shooting suspect Ivan Mateo-Lozenzo, 21, was enrolled at Middleton High School as 18-year-old junior Arain Gutierrez prompted about a dozen angry and concerned e-mails from parents urging the district to enact more stringent oversight of who enrolls in the district.\par \par \uc2 "Seems to me that an age check of all students is in order. ... I can foresee two possible reasons this person was enrolled ... to sell drugs or to recruit or control gang members. Proof of age should be required of all students," e-mailed one parent.\par \par \uc2 The newspaper obtained the e-mails under the state's open records law.\par \par \uc2 Middleton officials said Mateo-Lozenzo, an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  from Veracruz, Mexico, had transferred from West High School last fall. Mateo-Lozenzo; Billy Wenner-Say, 23, of Madison; Karen Giron-Cruz, 19, of Madison; Victor Prado-Velasquez, 16, of Fitchburg; and Franklin E. Yanez, 15, of Madison have been charged with being party to first-degree intentional homicide in the slaying of Antonio Perez.\par \par \uc2 Perez, 19, was shot dead April 28 outside a Fordem Avenue business in what police are calling a gang dispute.\par \par \uc2 Giron-Cruz, Yanez and Velasquez have been ordered to stand trial. Police still are looking for Mateo-Lozenzo and Wenner-Say.\par \par \uc2 Students don't have to show ID\par \par \uc2 The Madison School District requires the parents or guardians of a student to present a utility bill, a mortgage document or a lease with an address to enroll a child in school. Under district policy, school officials are directed to "verify age and name" of a student using a birth certificate or "other documentation provided by parent." The policy states that if a student's previous school was in a foreign country, school officials should ask to see a visa. If the student doesn't have a visa, the student still is enrolled under federal law.\par \par \uc2 Middleton-Cross Plains also requires a parent or guardian to show residency through a utility bill, lease or mortgage document. The district requires proof of age and identification through a birth certificate or passport when a student enrolls in kindergarten, but does not require it for later grades.\par \par \uc2 A district can implement any enrollment documentation it wants as long as it doesn't violate federal law, said Mary Maronek, coordinator for the state Department of Public Instruction's Education for Homeless Children and Youth program. But if a student is enrolling and he or she doesn't have identification, "they couldn't refuse enrollment," she said.\par \par \uc2 Because of McKinney-Vento, the district can't enforce a blanket policy requiring all students to provide a birth certificate or photo identification when enrolling, said district spokeswoman Michelle Larson.\par \par \uc2 The Middleton School Board is expected to take up the issue sometime this summer, she said. Madison district spokesman Ken Syke last week said the district still is reviewing its policy.\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020100615e66e00028\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 THE CAP TIMES\par {\*\bkmkstart toc34}{\*\bkmkend toc34}\b \uc2 Letters to the Editor\b0\par\par\uc2 930 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 June 2010\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par 37\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Cap Times should highlight population\par \par \uc2 Dear Editor: The Cap Times published eight opinion columns in print on June 2, but ran only six lines stating that Barbara Quirk's column on overpopulation and "ecological overshoot" - the most important issue facing us today - was only available on the Cap Times website.\par \par \uc2 At present, the world's population grows by 157 people every minute, adding 80 million people every year. That is like adding 10 cities the size of New York to the earth every year. Let that figure sink in for a minute.\par \par \uc2 Each person needs food and housing, each demands resources and each creates waste. Talk about a crisis!\par \par \uc2 Symptoms of this are wide-ranging - the one-child-per-family laws in China, the closing of the borders in Arizona, hunger, disease, extinction of plants and animals worldwide due to loss of habitat, and yes, even the Gulf oil spill, as companies drill down ever deeper to find oil.\par \par \uc2 Please run Quirk's column in its entirety in an upcoming issue. As she states, "There are no easy answers to this vital issue, but education and empowerment of women seem to be essential components." The Cap Times can and should be a leader in educating readers on this issue. If not you, who? If not now, when?\par \par \uc2 Hugh Iltis and Sharyn Wisniewski, Madison\par \par \uc2 County should scrutinize animal experiments\par \par \uc2 Dear Editor: Dane County supervisors should approve the resolution to scrutinize the University of Wisconsin's use of primates in experiments. UW has a horrendous history of violating animal welfare regulations and flouting public access to information laws.\par \par \uc2 Recently, PETA sued UW for withholding public documents related to invasive and deadly taxpayer-funded eye-movement experiments on monkeys and cats. In the experiments, holes are drilled into animals' skulls, electrodes are inserted into their brains, and stainless steel coils are implanted in their eyes.\par \par \uc2 In other experiments, sheep were locked in high-pressure chambers and some died from decompression sickness. Such painful deaths constitute a violation of Wisconsin law. Although an investigation by the Dane County district attorney confirmed this, UW was not prosecuted. PETA and Madison-based Alliance for Animals are now pushing for prosecution.\par \par \uc2 An independent study examining the ethics of primate experimentation will help shed light on - and hopefully bring some accountability to - practices at UW.\par \par \uc2 Alka Chandna, People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals Norfolk, Va.\par \par \uc2 Holiday should honor illegal immigrants\par \par \uc2 Dear Editor: What this country needs is another national holiday. I propose a new holiday for the third Monday in August. It would be \uc2 Illegal Immigrant\uc2  Appreciation Day, the day Americans could celebrate all the hardworking people who plant our crops, pick our fruits and vegetables, wash our cars, mow our lawns, cook in some of our favorite restaurants, and do all the other jobs our kids don't want to do.\par \par \uc2 Americans on that day could invite an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  family over for a barbecue, and order an extra case of beer. We could also show our appreciation for all the taxes they contribute to our Social Security system, which they will never see unless they become citizens.\par \par \uc2 John Morgan, Madison Asking for proof of citizenship protects us all Dear Editor: When did asking someone to prove they are a citizen of this country become racist? We should all be proud of the step Arizona has taken to protect not only its citizens but the rest of the law-abiding citizens of this nation. President Obama as usual is on the wrong side of the debate and would rather talk racism than protection of the country. When will the liberals in Washington stop using racism as the end of every debate they know they can't win and start using common sense?\par \par \uc2 James Hanson, Madison\par \par \uc2 Don't let \uc2 McDonald's\uc2  build near library\par \par \uc2 Dear Editor: It's come to my attention that \uc2 McDonald's\uc2  has outlined plans to move from its location on East Washington to the Madison East Shopping Center parking lot in front of the Hawthorne Branch Library. Since then, my attention has been consumed.\par \par \uc2 Isn't the first location profitable? Is it too far from the payday loan locations? Does \uc2 McDonald's\uc2  need to glow its golden landmark a little closer to the Capitol?\par \par \uc2 I am opposed to this plan. The Hawthorne Library is that mall's diamond in the rough. It is the one thing in it that really belongs to the city and it would be outrageous to obscure its view with the arches that are seen by so many as a symbol of the decline of a free- thinking society. Allowing this to happen would be a gigantic step back.\par \par \uc2 I plan on attending the public hearing June 16. I hope you do too.\par \par \uc2 Robin Lee, Madison\par \par \uc2 Madison doesn't need third white elephant\par \par \uc2 Dear Editor: We already have two white elephants grazing in Madison: the convention center and the performing arts center. Now we are well along contemplating a third: the new rail project between Madison and Milwaukee.\par \par \uc2 Shouldn't we be talking about details for an effective 4-year- old kindergarten, expansion of MATC, maybe a local job corps instead of the number of stations for a railroad with only hypothetical public use and acceptance? Isn't it more cost effective to invest in people's economic well-being rather than building a railroad for the convenience of lawyers, baseball fans and a few tourists?\par \par \uc2 Do we really want a third white elephant to financially "clean up" after?\par \par \uc2 James Jung Madison\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020100610e6690002t\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 SUNDAY OPINION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc35}{\*\bkmkend toc35}\b \uc2 What changes if any does Social Security need to stay sustainable ; for future generations of retirees?\b0\par\par\uc2 2,287 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 May 2010\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par B2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Stop the politicians from raiding our funds While extending the starting age for Social Security recipients seems to be a logical change, it is a reaction to the "symptom" and does not address the problem.\par \par \uc2 There is no doubt our current system should be revised to better reflect the changes in demographics and actuaries since the inception of Social Security in President Franklin Roosevelt's day. However, the most benefit may be achieved by removing the legislators who allowed the people's Social Security funds to be an unlocked and unsecured reservoir for meeting the costs of "overspending" that they created in the first place.\par \par \uc2 Anyone who allowed the $2.5 trillion Social Security fund to be depleted on non-related, frivolous programs is unfit to serve and should be voted out of office.\par \par \uc2 First, we need the funds to be replaced. Second, we need a ban on using our contributions for anything other than paying back the contributors who have made the deposits. If our representatives in Washington are not savvy enough to introduce legislation to do this, let's send them home.\par \par \uc2 Last, it's obvious that leaving our funds in the hands of our representatives in Washington to "manage" gives them another way to prove their inability to do so.\par \par \uc2 - Jim Brud, Middleton\par \par \uc2 Program has become a federal 'Ponzi scheme'\par \par \uc2 Social Security, like the term "entitlement programs," has broad implications. Yet how many have considered what is provided, who pays for the benefits and - like a family budget - whether the program is within your financial capacity?\par \par \uc2 Social Security was originated in the mid-1930s as a supplement for retirement. In the beginning there were about 40 people paying in for each one receiving benefits. Now, just over two workers pay in for each current beneficiary. Since it passed, Congress has added disability and survivor benefits. None of the collected taxes for these benefits has been invested and original surpluses were spent by politicians for non-related programs.\par \par \uc2 Essentially, the U.S. government has conducted a "Ponzi scheme" just like Bernie Madoff. He went to jail, and our politicians are still passing laws and spending our money and trillions borrowed from foreign governments.\par \par \uc2 Yes, people are living longer and that should modify how the program pays out benefits. However, legislative financial abuse and fraud by politicians is also unacceptable. Benefits paid by debt merely passes on the burden to our kids.\par \par \uc2 - Clarence A. Rumpel, Stoughton\par \par \uc2 Get rid of cap and change eligibility age\par \par \uc2 Yes, we need changes in Social Security, and the first change should be to have everyone who earns money help pay. This means getting rid of the cap. Don't raise it, as has been done many times before, but get rid of it completely and have folks pay on every penny they earn.\par \par \uc2 Regarding age, that's a no-brainer. Folks are living longer today! Did you know that when Otto von Bismarck first introduced social security in Germany in the 1880s, the retirement age was actually 70?\par \par \uc2 - Pete Etter, New Glarus\par \par \uc2 If markets can be made safe, invest some funds Most people were opposed to sidelining a percentage of Social Security contributions to the security exchange market, and the last corrections to the unregulated market showed why.\par \par \uc2 But if the Security Exchange Commission would have powers to identify, observe and stop high risk and speculative transactions, it could be a secure investment market. The solution is: * Control or ban all short-selling activities including day trading.\par \par \uc2 * Buyers must hold any securities for a minimum of two years. If they are sold before that, collect 20 percent of the trade value in taxes for Social Security. All publicly traded companies should pay a minimum in dividends or interest, perhaps 4.5 percent.\par \par \uc2 * Cap all executive salaries, bonuses, options and other fringe benefits. Again, collect a high tax for the combined financial value that exceeds the established cap. Double that tax if the publicly-owned company is operating with losses.\par \par \uc2 * If a publicly-owned company files for bankruptcy, strip their officers and directors of their belongings in excess of certain amounts.\par \par \uc2 If this was done, more would participate in the securities market. Fortunes would be smaller but more widespread. Social Security would only be needed for the frail, sick and unfortunate who never had a chance to participate in the market.\par \par \uc2 - Wolfgang Risop, Madison\par \par \uc2 Change collection rates and clean up fraud\par \par \uc2 Why is it that this ongoing issue rears its ugly head when a major election is approaching?\par \par \uc2 The Social Security fund was raided for other purposes so it should be replenished. Also, why stop collecting it at certain income levels?\par \par \uc2 Tax the entire earnings of movie stars and multi-millionaire sports figures. How about a higher rate for the big companies and corporations? They can afford it and have more employees.\par \par \uc2 Rein in and audit Social Security Disability Income recipients. I know many whose only disability is alcoholism or drug addiction, or who fake illness or are just plain lazy. Some earn more on SSDI than I get on regular Social Security, and I had to work 40 years for it. And do millionaires really need it?\par \par \uc2 Please, whatever else is done, don't cut or lower the payments. I worked for them.\par \par \uc2 - Helen Spring, Madison\par \par \uc2 Retirement at 65 is often not a choice\par \par \uc2 How many people does the Wisconsin State Journal employ over age 65? It's not that people want to retire at age 65, it's that employers are not enthusiastic about hiring older workers.\par \par \uc2 Medicine is allowing people to live longer, but could someone with bilateral hip replacements who uses a cane work eight to 10 hours a day in shipping and receiving?\par \par \uc2 U.S. Sen. Herb Kohl, enjoying his cushy government job, will be able to continue working for as long as he chooses. Those of us who bust our butts to make \uc2 Kohl's\uc2  life so pleasurable look at Social Security as a life line for when the body decides it has had enough, or an employer decides he would prefer a newer model.\par \par \uc2 I cannot believe the government would endorse anything as foolhardy as investing part of our Social Security in the stock market.\par \par \uc2 Remember "safe" mutual funds? They are why I am still working in my mid-60s. If government would use Social Security only for its intended purpose - a subsidy for old people - there would be no problem with it going broke.\par \par \uc2 - Greg Zeszotarski, Lone Rock\par \par \uc2 Change rules to reflect healthier population\par \par \uc2 Why was Social Security created? Initially it was to provide a safety net for those individuals who had insufficient means to provide for their own retirement, were disabled or in poverty.\par \par \uc2 Specifically focusing on the retirement aspect of Social Security, and taking into account the healthier older population we have today and expect to have in the future, I recommend three ways to allow Social Security to continue to meet its original intent:\par \par \uc2 * Raise the age at which individuals are eligible to receive benefits.\par \par \uc2 * Take into account income and/or wealth in determining eligibility.\par \par \uc2 * Use some combination of the above approaches.\par \par \uc2 Perhaps consider allowing those with lower incomes or individuals with lower net worth to begin collecting Social Security benefits at an earlier age, while making those with higher incomes and/or greater net assets wait to collect, or possibly never be able to do so.\par \par \uc2 This may sound unfair to the wealthy or even upper middle class.\par \par \uc2 However, if I'm fortunate enough to have sufficient assets to fund my own retirement, I'll be first in line to let others who need it have more benefit from the program.\par \par \uc2 - Tom Schwei, Fitchburg\par \par \uc2 Hiking retirement age hurts younger workers\par \par \uc2 Raising the retirement age to 70 will only worsen the unemployment rate for younger workers, as fewer jobs will be vacated and available for fresh blood.\par \par \uc2 Before dramatically raising the retirement age, we should restructure the Social Security tax so it is less regressive. Currently, it's a regressive program because payroll taxes are applied only to wage earners, not to those whose income comes from investments.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, the maximum income for the Social Security tax was $106,800 in 2009. That means a person making twice or even three times that income essentially pays less tax as a percentage of personal income.\par \par \uc2 Removing the upper limits on the tax will allow for future solvency of the system, while allowing the tax rate to be lowered for lower- and middle-income working families.\par \par \uc2 As for privatization, I am against putting Social Security in the hands of the same people whose recklessness created the current financial crisis and ruined the retirement and pension funds of so many Americans.\par \par \uc2 The folly of such a move would seem to be a no-brainer in view of our recent experience.\par \par \uc2 - Roger Dobrick, Madison\par \par \uc2 Let guest workers pay, but not collect benefits\par \par \uc2 How about this novel idea to fix our growing Social Security and \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  problems?\par \par \uc2 We could issue temporary work permits to foreigners. In exchange for the privilege of obtaining a temporary work permit, permit holders would be required to contribute to the Social Security system with the understanding that they will not be able to collect benefits in the future.\par \par \uc2 Sounds like a win-win solution for everyone.\par \par \uc2 - John Olson, Madison\par \par \uc2 Tax all income without cap or exclusions\par \par \uc2 An obvious answer to the coming Social Security deficit is payroll taxes for everyone on all their income.\par \par \uc2 Right now, those earning up to $106,800 per year (which is the great majority of Americans), pay to the limit, as do their employers. People earning over $106,800 stop there. The theory, I suppose, is that the wealthy will not live long enough to recoup all their Social Security investment.\par \par \uc2 But many people who have paid Social Security taxes all their lives die before or shortly after retirement. Illegal immigrants pay into Social Security (assuming their employers are obeying that law), but they will never collect benefits.\par \par \uc2 Can anyone provide a good, moral reason why money earned through investments should not be subject to Social Security taxes, while money earned from genuine work is? I don't think any justification for that shows up in the New Testament.\par \par \uc2 If asking high earners for payroll taxes on their entire income, just like everybody else, causes them economic hardship, they are simply bad managers of their personal finances. Poor souls, they will need to make cuts in their household budgets that most ordinary Americans have already made.\par \par \uc2 - Bill Spevacek, Mineral Point\par \par \uc2 Hard to justify the Social Security cap\par \par \uc2 There is only one real solution to keeping Social Security solvent: Remove the cap on the FICA tax.\par \par \uc2 Why is the cap $106,800? Why is there a cap at all? Why can't the well-to-do help the poor working souls have at least some sort of comfortable retirement?\par \par \uc2 I can't help but believe that some of the other "fixes" are just Band-Aids.\par \par \uc2 - Clifford Voegeli, Madison\par \par \uc2 Scrap Social Securityand start over\par \par \uc2 To better appreciate Social Security's dismal future, it would be helpful to more fully understand its past.\par \par \uc2 It was established in 1935, though the first Social Security tax wasn't levied until 1937. That tax was 1 percent of an employee's pay, matched by a 1 percent employer contribution.\par \par \uc2 It remained level until 1950, but by 1990 the tax had been raised to 6.2 percent paid by each employee and employer, for a total of 12.4 percent.\par \par \uc2 That's an astounding increase in only 40 years (see {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.ssa.gov/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.ssa.gov/}}}\uc2  OACT/ProgData/taxRates.html\par \par \uc2 ).\par \par \uc2 Now U.S. Sen. Herb Kohl tells us that a "modest 1.1 percent increase" can solve all that ails Social Security. Rather than believing the politicians, let's trust the numbers. Based on past history, the Social Security tax projects to total 22.8 percent by the year 2070.\par \par \uc2 Is that the mess we want to leave for future generations? It's time to recognize Social Security for what it is - a noble, but failed, experiment. It's time to start over.\par \par \uc2 - Greg Thoemke, New Glarus\par \par \uc2 Wealthy have little need for Social Security\par \par \uc2 The easiest way to help the Social Security dilemma is to eliminate the cap, which is currently $106,800. There are many people out there, including overpaid pro athletes, actors, politicians, CEOs and so on, whose income far exceeds this amount.\par \par \uc2 The counter argument to eliminating the cap is that these people are limited to the maximum Social Security payout, so their input should be limited.\par \par \uc2 However, with their inflated incomes, they should be able to provide for their retirement above and beyond their "limited" Social Security payout.\par \par \uc2 - Al Bunescu, Madison\par \par \uc2 Retirement age hike makes sense to youth\par \par \uc2 As a young person soon to enter the workforce, I am worried about the Social Security crisis. However, I believe in raising the age at which people receive retirement benefits.\par \par \uc2 As medicine and modern health care techniques improve, it is only natural that people live longer and longer. To increase the amount of funds available for retirement benefits, there would have to be either an increase in tax on each paycheck, or an increase in the time people have to wait for benefits.\par \par \uc2 The increase in taxes would cause problems for the current workforce, so I agree with the second option. I don't think a choice for young workers on how much they pay toward Social Security would be effective because many would not chose to pay at all.\par \par \uc2 - Garrett Farin, student, Madison East\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020100604e65u0001s\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 FRONT\par {\*\bkmkstart toc36}{\*\bkmkend toc36}\b \uc2 Madison police to expand gang unit ; BUT THERE STILL IS NO COUNTYWIDE GANG PREVENTION COORDINATOR, WHICH MADISON POLICE CHIEF NOBLE WRAY SAYS IS NEEDED.\b0\par\par\uc2 SANDY CULLEN   \par \uc2 By SANDY CULLEN scullen@madison.com 608-252-6137\par \uc2 1,320 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 May 2010\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Nearly three years after a Dane County task force called for a coordinated effort to combat growing gang activity and six weeks after a gang-related homicide, the Madison Police Department will launch an expanded gang unit that has been in the works since last year.\par \par \uc2 But still lacking is a countywide gang prevention coordinator that Chief Noble Wray said is critical to addressing gang activity, including a rise in Latino gangs, which police say were involved in the April 28 shooting death of a 19-year-old Madison man.\par \par \uc2 "Our emphasis should be on how do we stop the homicide, not what do we do after the homicide," said Wray, who vowed to renew the call for a countywide gang prevention coordinator when the department introduces its new Crime Prevention Gang Unit on June 10 to representatives of community agencies and others working on issues involving gangs and youth violence.\par \par \uc2 But both county and city officials say it's not their sole responsibility to create such a position, and it isn't known how it would be funded.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, in Madison, the police department will triple the size of its gang unit, from two members to six, starting June 14. The expansion will put one gang-prevention officer in each of its five districts. Sgt. Amy Schwartz, currently with the department's Criminal Intelligence Section, will supervise the unit.\par \par \uc2 The gang officers will work closely with other officers in their districts and with police serving as educational resource officers in the city's high schools, as well as with community members, in an effort to keep youths out of gangs, Wray said.\par \par \uc2 Joel Plant, an aide to Mayor Dave Cieslewicz, said the new Crime Prevention Gang Unit already is drawing attention from other U.S. law enforcement agencies for its combined focus and its placement of gang officers in districts throughout the city.\par \par \uc2 Lt. Brian Ackeret of the North District, where the April homicide took place, said the new gang unit "will be a welcome additional resource that's definitely needed, and the timing is perfect."\par \par \uc2 In the wake of the death of Antonio Perez, the victim in the April shooting whom police identified as a member of the C14 gang, police said they feared retaliation. So far, that hasn't happened.\par \par \uc2 Police have said most of the group involved in the shooting belongs to the South Side Carnales, though court records also suggest some or all were members of MS-13.\par \par \uc2 On Friday, police on horses patrolled Warner Park, where last week a 22-year-old man was stabbed after a fight on the basketball court and two days later shots were fired. Police were investigating whether those incidents, as well as two after-school disturbances last week involving students at Metro Transit's North Transfer Point, were gang-related. Ackeret said those incidents were not related to the April homicide.\par \par \uc2 But Wray and others say a countywide coordinator is also essential to keeping efforts by police, schools, social services agencies and community organizations to combat gang issues on track.\par \par \uc2 40 gangs in Madison\par \par \uc2 Police estimate there are now more than 1,100 confirmed gang members in Madison and about 40 gangs, about 12 of which are the main Latino gangs.\par \par \uc2 The Dane County Enhanced Youth Gang Prevention Task Force recommended in August 2007 that a countywide gang coordinator's position be considered. That group's co-chairman, former Madison police Capt. Luis Yudice, who's also security coordinator for the Madison School District, first called for a "comprehensive strategy so we can all work in unison" to address gang violence in September 2005.\par \par \uc2 Since then, Yudice said, staff in Madison schools are recognizing more issues involving gangs among students, which he attributes in part to greater awareness and training.\par \par \uc2 "We have gang-involved kids in probably most of our high schools and middle schools and some of our elementary schools," he said. Staff do a good job of keeping gang activity out of the schools, he said, and work closely with students, families, police and social workers in an effort to keep students out of gangs.\par \par \uc2 Locally, the gang issue is not unique to Madison schools. "We're seeing more gang activity in the suburban school districts," Yudice said, as well as the emergence of hate groups targeting blacks and Latinos in Madison, Deerfield, Cottage Grove and DeForest.\par \par \uc2 Ivan Mateo-Lozenzo, a 21-year-old \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  from Veracruz, Mexico, who police say killed Perez, was enrolled as a junior at Middleton High School, where officials knew him as Arain Gutierrez, 18, and believed he had previously attended Madison's West High School.\par \par \uc2 Madison School District officials, citing federal privacy laws and district policy, have refused to say whether Mateo-Lozenzo, who is still at large, had been enrolled there. But they said they shared information with police after the homicide.\par \par \uc2 Four others charged had attended schools in Madison or Verona, according to court records.\par \par \uc2 Coordinator needed\par \par \uc2 Yudice said he had hoped a county gang coordinator would be created "to keep this issue on the front burner" and avoid duplication of services among the many entities working to address the gang issue.\par \par \uc2 Had such a position been in place, Yudice said, he believes some of the increase in the county's gang activity might have been prevented.\par \par \uc2 County Human Services Director Lynn Green said in an e-mail that the task force was a joint effort by the city and county, and its recommendation doesn't indicate that the county "should be the entity to consider creating this position."The county already spends over $16.7 million on gang prevention, intervention and enforcement efforts, and has committed the time of Delinquency Services Manager and task force co-chairman Stephen Blue "to the daily duties of the coordinator role," Green said.\par \par \uc2 Green said in an e-mail that after the April shooting, Dane County Executive Falk named Frank Rodriguez as a "program leader" with the neighborhood program to work with Latino youth.\par \par \uc2 Plant said the city agrees that a countywide coordinator is vital to the efforts to combat gang activity. "I think that the mayor would welcome a conversation with (Falk) about this position and how it might be funded," Plant said. "At this point, that conversation hasn't happened."- State Journal reporter Gena Kittner contributed to this story.\par \par \uc2 WARNING SIGNS IN YOUTHS\par \par \uc2 Signs of gang influence or involvement:\par \par \uc2 ? Sudden change in friends.\par \par \uc2 ? Change in style of clothing or an interest in a particular color, number or logo.\par \par \uc2 ? Less interest in time with family and a desire for more privacy.\par \par \uc2 ? Disrespect for authority, family and/or school.\par \par \uc2 ? Decline in grades and poor school attendance.\par \par \uc2 ? Unexplained money or possessions.\par \par \uc2 ? Appearance of graffiti on personal items.\par \par \uc2 ? Use of nicknames and/or tattoos.\par \par \uc2 ? Unusual pen marks, bruises or burns on arms, hands or body.\par \par \uc2 ? Using unknown vocabulary, gang slang, speaking in fractured sentences, excessive swearing.\par \par \uc2 ? Using hand signals.\par \par \uc2 ? Staying out later than usual/all night.\par \par \uc2 ? Increased conflict with other young people.\par \par \uc2 ? Fear of traveling to certain neighborhoods.\par \par \uc2 ? Listening to music that glorifies violence, drugs and gangs. ? Associating with gang members.\par \par \uc2 SOURCE: Dane County Youth Prevention Task Force\par \par \uc2 Caption: KYLE MCDANIEL  State Journal  Graffiti referencing the C14 gang is displayed on an apartment  complex on Lovell Lane in Madison earlier this month. Police said  Antonio Perez, the victim in an April gang-related shooting, was a  member of the Clanton 14, or C14, gang. ANDY MANIS - For the State Journal  Madison Police Officers Matthew Kenny, at left atop Zander, and Katherine Cherne, atop Artex, patrol Warner Park on Friday evening. Police have been investigating whether a stabbing in the park last week was gang-related.   \par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020100527e65n0002b\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 LOCAL\par {\*\bkmkstart toc37}{\*\bkmkend toc37}\b \uc2 SHOULD LAWMAKERS OVERRIDE VETO ON TAX-CREDIT PROVISION? ; AT ISSUE | A WEEKLY FEATURE ON PROPOSED CHANGES TO STATE AND LOCAL LAW\b0\par\par\uc2 Mary Spicuzza   \par \uc2 Mary Spicuzza\par \uc2 412 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 May 2010\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par D1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 In a nutshell\par \par \uc2 \f2    A bill providing tax credits to companies that   upgrade or\par expand their food-processing operations has been signed   into law\par by Gov. Jim Doyle. But he used his partial veto powers to   get rid\par of a provision that would have blocked companies from   getting tax\par \f28 \par \par \uc2 credits if they hire illegal immigrants.\par \par \uc2 The Legislature has a veto review period scheduled for May 25 and 26, so lawmakers can attempt a veto override for that provision of the bill in question, AB 757. But Rebekah Sweeney, a spokeswoman for Assembly Speaker Mike Sheridan, D-Janesville, said they're not planning to try for an override.\par \par \uc2 The case for it\par \par \uc2 \f2    The Senate Committee on Economic Development added   the \f28 \uc2 \f2 illegal\par immigrant\f28 \uc2 \f2  amendment to the bill at the request of   leadership. And\par Carrie Lynch, a spokeswoman for Senate Majority   Leader Russ\par Decker, said its goal was to avoid giving an unfair   advantage to\par \f28 \par \par \uc2 \f2 companies that break the law.\f28 \par \par \uc2 \f2 "A lot of people in our caucus didn't want to reward companies that hire illegal workers over legal Wisconsin workers," Lynch said.\f28 \par \par \uc2 \f2 But she added that because it's an Assembly bill, any override attempt would have to originate in that house.\f28 \par \par \uc2 \f2 The case against it\f28 \par \par \uc2 \f2    Doyle warned that the portion of the bill he   vetoed would have\par unfairly targeted food processors and   distributors - and would\par drag Wisconsin companies into the federal   immigration debate.\par "Seeking to address national immigration policy   issues by limiting\par the access of Wisconsin's food-processing   industry to job-\par creating tax credits is unfair and could weaken   Wisconsin's\par agriculture economy," Doyle wrote in Wednesday's veto   message. \par \par \par    The governor also wrote that he objects to the limitations the  \par \f28 \par \par \uc2 \f2 vetoed part of the bill would place on companies in the state.\f28 \par \par \uc2 \f2 To get involved\f28 \par \par \uc2 \f2 Decker can be reached at 608-266-2502 or Sen.Decker@legis.wisconsin.gov.\f28 \par \par \uc2 \f2 Sheridan can be reached at 608-266-7503 or Rep.Sheridan@legis.wisconsin.gov.\f28 \par \par \uc2 \f2 To contact lawmakers to oppose or support the veto, use the legislative hotline, which is staffed from 8:15 a.m. to 4:45 p.m. weekdays, at 800-362-9472. To send e-mail, log onto the Legislature's Web page at \f28 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.legis.state.wi.us"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.legis.state.wi.us}}}\uc2 \f2 , select Senate or Assembly, and follow the link to the e-mail directory.\f28 \par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020100518e65g0000i\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 News\par {\*\bkmkstart toc38}{\*\bkmkend toc38}\b \uc2 Seeking your help: Did your child go to high school with this man?\b0\par\par\uc2 State Journal staff\par \uc2 211 \uc2 words\par \uc2 13 May 2010\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par WEB\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Did your child attend Madison's West High School or Middleton High School with Ivan Mateo-Lozenzo, also known by his alias Arain Gutierrez?\par \par \uc2 The man, 21, who was known to Middleton officials as a 18-year- old junior, is charged with first-degree intentional homicide for his alleged role in what police are calling a gang-related killing.\par \par \uc2 If he or if any of the other people accused in this shooting were classmates with your son or daughter, and you'd like to talk about it, please contact us at wsjcity@madison.com.\par \par \uc2 Also charged with homicide are: Franklin E. Yanez-Hernandez, 15; Billy Wenner-Say, 23; Karen Giron-Cruz, 19; and Victor E. Prado- Velasquez, 16.\par \par \uc2 Posted in Crime_and_courts on Thursday, May 13, 2010 8:05 am Updated: 8:12 pm Posted: Thursday, May 13, 2010 8:05 am\par \par \uc2 Caption: Ivan Mateo-Lozenzo, the man Madison police say shot and killed a  gang rival last week, is known to local authorities as a  21-year-old \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  from Veracruz. But school officials  thought he was an 18-year-old high school junior named Arain  Gutierrez.   Madison Police Department   \par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020100517e65d0001s\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 OPINION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc39}{\*\bkmkend toc39}\b \uc2 School should stop stonewalling ; The public deserves to know if a man accused of shooting a gang rival went to Madison schools.\b0\par\par\uc2 451 \uc2 words\par \uc2 13 May 2010\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A10\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 The public has a right to know if Ivan Mateo-Lozenzo, 21, attended West High School or any other Madison schools and for how long.\par \par \uc2 School district officials are stubbornly refusing to say.\par \par \uc2 Nor will they disclose if the district followed its own policies for screening new students when (or if) Mateo-Lozenzo enrolled at West using a fake name and age.\par \par \uc2 Police say Mateo-Lozenzo pulled the trigger in the shooting death of gang rival Antonio Perez, 19, on Madison's East Side late last month.\par \par \uc2 Mateo-Lozenzo was an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  from Mexico. But that's not the central issue here because the U.S. Supreme Court has ruled that school districts can't withhold public education because of immigration status.\par \par \uc2 The real issue here is school safety.\par \par \uc2 Middleton school officials have acknowledged that Mateo-Lozenzo, 21, attended Middleton High School under the name of Arain Gutierrez, 19 - a name and age that police say are fake. Middleton records also suggest Mateo-Lozenzo previously attended West High School in Madison.\par \par \uc2 A guy who gains regular access to our schools, who isn't a teenager anymore, who uses a false name and age, who is now accused of shooting and killing a rival gang member - that's someone who presents school security concerns of high public interest.\par \par \uc2 Madison schools shouldn't give out information willy-nilly about students, whose privacy should be respected.\par \par \uc2 But in extreme cases - and they don't get much more extreme than this one - district policies should be flexible enough to incorporate some common sense.\par \par \uc2 Parents, students and taxpayers have a right to know what's going on. The public needs more information and reassurance from Madison school officials about the case of Mateo-Lozenzo.\par \par \uc2 Refusing to give details about how this man came to attend local schools doesn't give the public much confidence in district policies or in the protection of other students.\par \par \uc2 Madison's refusal to even acknowledge whether a man charged with murder was in fact a student is especially egregious.\par \par \uc2 School officials should stop hiding the facts and discuss the district's actions in an open way. They also should let the public in on any discussions about district enrollment policy moving forward.\par \par \uc2 Caption: CRAIG SCHREINER - State Journal  Police search a car they say was used in the gang-related shooting  death of Antonio Perez, 19, on April 28 on Madison's East Side.  Police are still looking for Ivan Mateo-Lozenzo, who they say  pulled the trigger and who attended local schools using the name  Arain Gutierrez.   \par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020100517e65d0000u\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Footnote\par \uc2 LOCAL\par {\*\bkmkstart toc40}{\*\bkmkend toc40}\b \uc2 Sheriff's Office refers illegal immigrants to federal authorities\b0\par\par\uc2 Chris Rickert   \par \uc2 Chris Rickert\par \uc2 356 \uc2 words\par \uc2 13 May 2010\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Q This month, the State Journal reported that a committee created to look for ways to improve relations between police and immigrants is divided over whether the Dane County Sheriff's Office should continue to report illegal immigrants to federal authorities. How are those reports made and do any other local agencies make them?\par \par \uc2 A The only time the Sheriff's Office asks about a person's immigration status is when he is being booked into the Dane County Jail, according to Capt. Jeff Teuscher.\par \par \uc2 A question on the jail's booking sheet asks for the arrested person's birth country. The answer to that question and the personal items collected during booking - such as identification - will give deputies some idea about whether the person is in the country legally.\par \par \uc2 "We don't actually make a determination on whether they are here legally or not," Teuscher said. Rather, if the person was not born in the United States and doesn't have documents proving his legal immigration status, Immigration and Customs Enforcement is notified and it decides.\par \par \uc2 Teuscher said the birth country question is on the booking form because the United States has agreements with some countries that require law enforcement to contact the countries' consulates if one of their citizens is arrested.\par \par \uc2 It's Madison Police policy not to arrest or detain anyone solely for violating immigration laws unless ICE asks them to and a supervisor OKs the arrest. Officers also cannot ask for immigration documents unless they are assisting ICE. Monona Police Chief Walter Ostrenga, president of the Dane County Chiefs of Police Association, said he doesn't know if other local police report suspected illegal immigrants to ICE, but Monona doesn't.\par \par \uc2 In a January 2008 guide by the state attorney general's office on how police should deal with foreign nationals, the office notes police do not have authority to enforce civil immigration violations such as being in the country illegally.\par \par \uc2 But it recommends that if an officer does arrest an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 , she should notify ICE.\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020100517e65d0000q\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 FRONT\par {\*\bkmkstart toc41}{\*\bkmkend toc41}\b \uc2 MADISON'S BIG CENSUS QUESTION: WILL HISPANICS BE COUNTED? ; WHILE CIVIC LEADERS TRY TO QUELL DEPORTATION FEARS, THE NEW ARIZONA LAW HAS SOME ON EDGE.\b0\par\par\uc2 STEVEN VERBURG|   \par \uc2 By STEVEN VERBURG sverburg@madison.com| 608-252-6118\par \uc2 1,209 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 May 2010\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 With more than 300 census workers in Dane County knocking on doors of those who didn't mail in census forms, community leaders in Madison voiced renewed concerns that Hispanic immigrants might avoid being counted.\par \par \uc2 "I hope to be wrong on that, but I think we are going to have an issue," said Veronica Lazo, service coordinator at Centro Hispano of Dane County and a member of a committee that worked to maximize local participation.\par \par \uc2 Hispanic leaders have worked hard to quell unfounded fears that filling out the forms exposed illegal immigrants to higher risk of deportation. But recent enactment in Arizona of a controversial law requiring police to investigate anyone they suspect of entering the United States illegally has stoked worries, Lazo and others said.\par \par \uc2 "That's not going to make you want to fill out a form for the government," Brian Grady, a Madison city planner in charge of assisting the U.S. Census Bureau locally, said of the Arizona law. "If someone hasn't sent in the mail-in response by now, I wonder if they're going to want to talk to someone who comes to their door."\par \par \uc2 Wisconsin led the nation with 81 percent of households mailing in forms by the April 28 cutoff. Dane County's overall rate was slightly higher than the state rate, but tracts with high levels of rental housing, low incomes and large numbers of Spanish speakers were as low as 64 percent. Census "enumerators" already have canvassed campus areas to catch students before classes end. Now the effort is concentrated in other low-response areas, mostly along the Beltline in Madison, the town of Madison and Fitchburg. Since May 1, nearly 1,000 have been working in the 10-county Madison region. The number nationally is 600,000. The goal is to complete the work in July.\par \par \uc2 Pushing for complete count\par \par \uc2 The 2000 census overcounted affluent whites and undercounted minorities, according to a census report. This year the bureau is pushing for a complete count, as mandated by the Constitution, because census numbers affect the distribution of political power and the geographic disbursement of $400 billion in federal aid for medical care, roads and other services.\par \par \uc2 Ashley Halase, 21, is a Baraboo native who lives in the Fitchburg end of one of those Dane County tracts with a low response rate. She says she and her husband, an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  from Mexico, won't fill out their form because they don't want the government to have his name.\par \par \uc2 "I've heard people say that they were using it to find out how many people are in the United States illegally," Halase said. "You never know, especially with these things happening in Arizona."\par \par \uc2 Their marriage last year gave him an avenue to U.S. citizenship, but applying now would mean possible fines and a requirement to spend a year in Mexico because he's been here without documents so long, she said.\par \par \uc2 An \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  who isn't worried about filling out his form is Edgar Sanchez, who moved here from Mexico City in 1996 and hasn't become a citizen. He said he doesn't want to be deported because life is better here for his family. But he's already sent in his census form.\par \par \uc2 "Everybody's concerned about it," said Sanchez. "If the police send me back, I can't help that. I just worried for too much time. Not anymore."\par \par \uc2 Reflecting neighborhoods\par \par \uc2 U.S. Census Bureau policy is to hire local residents for door-to- door work in their own neighborhoods, but Lazo and the Rev. David Smith, chairman of the committee of local officials who promoted census participation, said they haven't been able to get answers about how well the enumerators reflect the county's black and Latino makeup.\par \par \uc2 "The value of getting African-Americans and Latinos is because it reflects the neighborhoods and people feel more comfortable with people who look like they do," said Smith, interim director of South Madison Health and Family Center-Harambee and pastor of Faith Community Christian Church.\par \par \uc2 Lazo echoed Smith's concerns, and added that having fluent Spanish speakers was crucial to winning trust of recent immigrants.\par \par \uc2 Centro Hispano staff members spent many hours persuading suspicious Latinos to mail in census forms, and more time trying to recruit Spanish speakers to go door to door, she said.\par \par \uc2 The bureau will only hire U.S. citizens, although exceptions can be made for Spanish speakers who have permanent resident status or work visas. Some who are here legally backed off when they were asked to give their fingerprints for the FBI, Lazo said.\par \par \uc2 "It was really hard to overcome that," Lazo said. "It was part of the whole distrust the community has with the legal system."\par \par \uc2 Muriel Jackson, a spokeswoman in the census regional office in Chicago, said the bureau's goal is to hire census takers who reflect the community, but the bureau won't release information about how well it did in hiring Spanish speakers, minorities or residents of neighborhoods with low response rates and a high risk of undercounts.\par \par \uc2 Pat Ryan, manager of the Madison office, said on Thursday that he would release a report on the number of Spanish speaking census workers, but he didn't return phone calls Friday.\par \par \uc2 The FBI does criminal background checks on all field workers.\par \par \uc2 "We don't want criminals going to people's doors," Ryan said.\par \par \uc2 HOW IT WORKS\par \par \uc2 Census takers visit all addresses that haven't mailed in a form. If nobody comes to the door, the census taker will visit a home up to three times and try by phone three times. Census takers will ask only the questions that appear on the census form.\par \par \uc2 CAN YOU SAY NO?\par \par \uc2 Participation is required by law, (Section 221, of Title 13 of the U.S. Code), but census officials say they prefer to persuade people by pointing out that the count guides distribution of $400 billion in federal aid.\par \par \uc2 Source: U.S. Census Bureau\par \par \uc2 LOOK FOR ID\par \par \uc2 Residents approached by census workers should look for identification, said Brian Grady, a city planner who has been assisting in the count. 'All census takers carry an official ID and shoulder bag which have the U.S. Department of Commerce seal,' Grady said. 'They will provide an information sheet explaining that responses are confidential and will only ask questions that are on the form. People should keep in mind that these folks are from the community and are working on behalf of all of us.'\par \par \uc2 The Associated Press contributed to this story.\par \par \uc2 Caption: CRAIG SCHREINER - State Journal Edgar Sanchez, 40, said he moved from Mexico City to Madison with family in 1996. He works in a food processing facility and said he would hate to be sent back, because crime makes Mexico City a very dangerous place to live. State Journal graphic Census mail-in rates SOURCE: U.S. Census Bureau, City College of New York Center for Urban Research State Journal   \par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020100511e65a00010\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 SUNDAY OPINION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc42}{\*\bkmkend toc42}\b \uc2 WHY SPECIAL TREATMENT FOR HISPANIC PEOPLE?\b0\par\par\uc2 1,613 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 May 2010\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par B2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 I support legal immigration, no matter what country people come from, but I'm amazed at the leniency shown to Hispanic people who enter the United States illegally, especially at the U.S.-Mexico border.\par \par \uc2 Anyone who enters illegally breaks our laws, so why are they being tolerated and catered to here? They have no rights of any kind in this country. They're not entitled to jobs, welfare payments, free housing, medical care or education. Economically they are draining this country because they send millions of dollars back to relatives in Mexico and other countries.\par \par \uc2 Breaks are not given to German, Italian, Russian or Asian immigrants. They have to apply for citizenship and learn to speak English, while we accommodate the Hispanics by posting signs in Spanish. This is ridiculous.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, we need National Guard troops on the border to help the overburdened Border Patrol, which desperately needs help. Many illegal immigrants coming in are drug runners, pushers or users, some of whom carry assault weapons. If this isn't a war-like situation, I don't know what is.\par \par \uc2 I applaud the governor of Arizona for taking action to try to remedy the problem that the U.S. government should have taken care of a long time ago.\par \par \uc2 - Donna Bergman, Reedsburg\par \par \uc2 Arizona law fails to give equal protection\par \par \uc2 Arizona's immigration law should be found unconstitutional due to, among other things, the argument that equal protection will not be appropriately enforced as provided by the U.S. Constitution.\par \par \uc2 The Constitution states in Article I, Section 8, that "Congress shall have power ... to establish a uniform rule of naturalization." The law signed by Arizona Gov. Jan Brewer requiring immigrants to have immigration documents with them to verify their status could easily be abused by authorities who could stop Hispanics at will, leading to harassment and racial profiling. It further gives police authority to request information from any individual suspected of not being a legal resident.\par \par \uc2 The law should be challenged and overturned on these merits alone. If it's not, it will fuel the profiling fire in other states with the same mentality. The impact will trickle down to everyone of non-Anglo heritage and therefore speed up the downfall of positive race relations in this country.\par \par \uc2 A positive alternative solution must be found. We simply cannot afford to sacrifice the accomplishments of the last 40 years in both civil and human rights. Equal protection under the Constitution is for everyone, not just the select few.\par \par \uc2 - Rick Buffington, Beloit\par \par \uc2 Amnesty will divide our nation even more\par \par \uc2 Since its inception, our nation has welcomed immigrants from all over the world to become legal and productive citizens. We truly are a nation of immigrants which is a good thing for all of us. But the intent of our nation's founders was never to open the flood gates for every person who wanted to come and stay here without legal documentation.\par \par \uc2 The reason Arizona enacted the current state immigration law was because the federal government has failed to secure and protect our borders. Arizona government officials and many citizens are fed up with the murders, rapes and violence involving illegal immigrants for years.\par \par \uc2 Currently the U.S. Senate is considering granting amnesty to millions of illegal immigrants residing in the United States. If this amnesty bill becomes law, it will tear our country apart and cause great divisions and strife.\par \par \uc2 Currently about 70 percent of Arizonans support their state's dramatic and courageous action to fill the void of federal border enforcement. We need to enforce current federal immigration laws instead of allowing a special interest group to dictate to the majority. Citizenship here is a right you earn and every naturalized citizen must go through the proper legal channels to accomplish it.\par \par \uc2 - Wayne Alden, McFarland\par \par \uc2 Calderon blames U.S., neglects countrymen\par \par \uc2 I am baffled by the criticism piled upon those who demand constraints for illegal immigrants. Not counting Constitutional guarantees, we now become "Nazis" for verbalizing the obvious. What part of "illegal" don't our detractors understand?\par \par \uc2 But let's assign blame where it begins, in the leadership of Mexican government. How can Mexican President Felipe Caldern criticize the state of Arizona when he creates a cesspool by driving away his own unprotected citizens? Why does he sit idly while his own people cannot afford necessities to such an extent that expatriation is their only option?\par \par \uc2 I'm sure the United States would be happy to purchase more \uc2 Pemex\uc2  products if the end game was for humanitarian reasons - it would not be the first time our country bought oil under those conditions.\par \par \uc2 Caldern's slovenly public policy is now based upon making over ten million of his own brethren into refugees, knowing that many perish in the desert. Death before dollars. How about a few protest marches on this behavior?\par \par \uc2 - Chico Buller, Sun Prairie\par \par \uc2 Mexican lineage means facing discrimination\par \par \uc2 My mother was right - Mexicans are treated worse than other minorities in this country. She was from a family of illegal immigrants who fled Mexico to escape violence.\par \par \uc2 She told me to get educated, taught me that I was to grow up and take care of a home, and told me to never reveal that I was Mexican. I was not allowed to part my hair in the middle because it accentuated my Mexican features.\par \par \uc2 In response to a Wednesday letter writer, my \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  family came to the United States and saved lives. Mama helped to develop the quick strep test as well as the meningitis vaccine. My siblings include two doctors, a physicist, a New York Times best- selling author and an interior designer. I'm a musician. We are not murderers, rapists or "coyotes."\par \par \uc2 At age 19, I was stopped at the Canadian/U.S. border and almost not allowed back into the U.S. I was threatened with deportation, and I had done nothing wrong except giggle when asked for proof of citizenship. This was 1979 when crossing back and forth to Canada was easy.\par \par \uc2 A couple of years later, my aunt was nearly deported back to Mexico. I have faced racism my entire life. Now I am applying for a passport card just in case.\par \par \uc2 - Nancy Orr, Madison\par \par \uc2 Sheriff should report illegal immigrants\par \par \uc2 Dane County Sheriff Dave Mahoney is right regarding informing federal authorities of illegal immigrants in his custody. Mexican law allows their law enforcement agencies to jail illegal immigrants when caught (although this fact should have no bearing on how we enforce our laws). Why should any State in the United States not do the same?\par \par \uc2 The sheriff's decision to report the names of illegal immigrants should not be changed unless for the better, which would be to put them on a bus with a one way ticket to the nearest city in Mexico.\par \par \uc2 An \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  is an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2 , and is not someone to be sequestered and protected against deportation. They might be welcomed with open arms if they were here legally, but the fact is, they broke our laws and because of that they are criminals.\par \par \uc2 - Don Murphy, Madison\par \par \uc2 Liberals want illegal immigrants' votes\par \par \uc2 I praise Arizona Gov. Jan Brewer for her action in signing a law which deals with illegal immigrants. What part of "illegal" is so hard to understand? They are law breakers and considered to be criminals who do not have rights. We are a nation founded on laws.\par \par \uc2 Does anyone consider the risks that they bring, some being drug runners with weapons? No one knows the dangers like the police and guards. Do the liberals want to allow them to come in order to get more votes and power?\par \par \uc2 Most Americans are for securing our borders. Doesn't anyone listen to the people? Let's also require everyone to have a photo ID. That's the only safe, sure way to keep felons from voting.\par \par \uc2 As far as violent protests, I guess that says that our tea party movement is peaceful in trying to get the administration's attention. We are for faith, hope and charity as in the U.S. Constitution. Does the anti-American crowd ever think of what this great country was founded on? Peace-loving people.\par \par \uc2 There are over 40,000 illegal immigrants in Wisconsin, draining our social services, schools and emergency rooms, among other services. They know how to get these services, too. I am somewhat furious about this.\par \par \uc2 - Arlene M. Huffman, Monroe\par \par \uc2 Impeach Obama for failing to enforce laws\par \par \uc2 It is a fact that the guilty party in this matter is the federal government and the current president who finds it difficult to fulfill his oath of office to defend this country from both foreign and domestic enemies.\par \par \uc2 My grandparents came through Ellis Island legally, not illegally. They were granted legal citizenship by meeting all the requirements.\par \par \uc2 People coming over the border illegally are foreign law breakers. They do not deserve any protection under any of laws granted those who came into this country through legal channels. If the president doesn't enforce the law, then he has broken his oath and should be impeached for not fulfilling his requirement for the office.\par \par \uc2 Every person - no matter what race, creed, color or national origin - who is in this country outside of the legal requirements should be deported, not supported. That is the law, and government on all levels should be held accountable to enforce those laws. Any and all methods should be used to enforce these laws. If we pick and choose which ones to support, this nation will descend into chaos.\par \par \uc2 - John Adams, Brodhead\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020100511e6590001w\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 FRONT\par {\*\bkmkstart toc43}{\*\bkmkend toc43}\b \uc2 SUSPECT HAD HIGH SCHOOL ALIAS ; AT MIDDLETON HIGH SCHOOL, THE 21-YEAR-OLD MAN ACCUSED IN A GANG- RELATED SHOOTING CLAIMED TO BE AN 18-YEAR-OLD JUNIOR.\b0\par\par\uc2 GENA KITTNER; GAYLE WORLAND Wisconsin   \par \uc2 By GENA KITTNER and GAYLE WORLAND Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 825 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 May 2010\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Ivan Mateo-Lozenzo, the man Madison police say shot and killed a gang rival last week, is known to local authorities as a 21-year- old \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  from Veracruz, Mexico, who worked as an area roofer in 2008.\par \par \uc2 Middleton High School officials thought he was an 18-year-old junior named Arain Gutierrez who had previously attended West High School in Madison.\par \par \uc2 So how did the man police say is affiliated with a ruthless Los Angeles gang pass himself off as a student in area high schools?\par \par \uc2 Middleton-Cross Plains School District records show Gutierrez - a Mateo-Lozenzo alias, according to police - entered the district Sept. 1 as a junior after attending West the previous year. The records list a birth date of Jan. 1, 1992, although Dane County Sheriff's Office records show Mateo-Lozenzo was born Jan. 14, 1989.\par \par \uc2 The Middleton records list a Madison address and say he was attending the Middleton school under a waiver and was enrolled for next year.\par \par \uc2 Madison officials won't confirm Mateo-Lozenzo ever attended West or any other school in the district, citing district policy not to disclose information about current or former students unless "it relates to educational activities, school-related functions or has a legitimate educational purpose."\par \par \uc2 Five accused in shooting\par \par \uc2 Mateo-Lozenzo; Billy Wenner-Say, 23, of Madison; Karen Giron- Cruz, 19, of Madison; Victor Prado-Velasquez, 16, of Fitchburg; and Franklin E. Yanez-Hernandez, 15, of Madison have been charged with being party to first-degree intentional homicide in the murder of Antonio Perez.\par \par \uc2 Perez, 19, was shot dead April 28 outside a Fordem Avenue business in what police are calling a gang dispute.\par \par \uc2 All but Prado-Velasquez are in the country illegally, according to Madison police.\par \par \uc2 Sheriff's records show that Wenner-Say, the other suspect not captured by police, listed his school as Memorial High School in Madison, and a police search of his residence turned up a Memorial identification card. But the records don't indicate when he went to school there.\par \par \uc2 Giron-Cruz was formerly a student at West, a teacher there verified. Prado-Velasquez attended Verona High School. It's unclear whether Yanez-Hernandez was enrolled in school.\par \par \uc2 Under the state constitution, all residents from age 4 to 20 are entitled to a free public education, said Patrick Gasper, state Department of Public Instruction spokesman. A 1982 U.S. Supreme Court ruling prohibits districts from withholding public education because of immigration status.\par \par \uc2 In Wisconsin, students must attend school in the district where they live unless they get an open-enrollment waiver to attend elsewhere, Gasper said. Districts can set their own policies on how to prove residency, he said.\par \par \uc2 Documentation needed\par \par \uc2 The Madison School District requires the parents or guardians of a student to present a utility bill, a mortgage document or a lease with an address to enroll a child in school. Under district policy, school officials are directed to "verify age and name" of a student using a birth certificate or "other documentation provided by parent."\par \par \uc2 The policy states that if a student's previous school was in a foreign country, school officials should ask to see a visa. If the student doesn't have a visa, the student is still enrolled.\par \par \uc2 Middleton-Cross Plains also requires a parent or guardian to show residency through a utility bill, lease or mortgage document, said district spokeswoman Michelle Larson. The district requires proof of age and identification through a birth certificate or passport when a student enrolls in kindergarten, but does not require it for later grades, she said.\par \par \uc2 Citing student privacy reasons, the district would not release what proof of residency or age Mateo-Lozenzo, his family or guardian provided. Larson said he was already listed in a state database of students, and officials "wouldn't have any reason to question the legitimacy of the information" provided for his enrollment into Middleton High School.\par \par \uc2 A man who answered the door at the residence listed in the Middleton district records said Mateo-Lozenzo had lived there at one point. The man declined to give his name or speak further.\par \par \uc2 Police went to the Middleton-Cross Plains School District on April 29 - the day after the shooting - with information that Gutierrez could be a Middleton High School student, which the district confirmed through its records and a student photo, Larson said.\par \par \uc2 State Journal reporters Mary Spicuzza and Dee J. Hall contributed to this report. Reporter Gena Kittner can be reached at gkittner@madison.com or 608-252-6139. Reporter Gayle Worland can be reached at gworland@madison.com or 608-252-6188.\par \par \uc2 Caption: Ivan Mateo-Lozenzo: Attended Middleton and Madison West.   \par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020100509e6580000k\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 OPINION\par {\*\bkmkstart toc44}{\*\bkmkend toc44}\b \uc2 BLAME THOSE WHO HIRE ILLEGAL WORKERS\b0\par\par\uc2 785 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 April 2010\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par A8\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Among the many issues we face in the United States, immigration is one of the most contentious and vitriolic. Nowhere is this more evident than in the case of the Arizona immigration law. In the debate over this law, illegal immigrants have been cast as evil law- breakers and Hispanic Americans have become suspicious because of the color of their skin.\par \par \uc2 The real issue is if there were not an active job market for illegal immigrants, they would not come here to find work. Why are we attacking illegal immigrants when we have employers, both large and small, saying "Come on over, we have work for you!"\par \par \uc2 If we really wanted to stop illegal immigration, we would make the punishments for employing an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  so draconian that no one would ever hire one again. Why not jail the contractor who picks up a day laborer, or slap a politician with a million dollar fine for having an undocumented nanny?\par \par \uc2 Let's recognize who the real villains are in this debate and hold them responsible.\par \par \uc2 - Patrick Olson, Sun Prairie\par \par \uc2 Agencies supporting disabled threatened\par \par \uc2 It was great to see Sunday's "Know Your Madisonian" on Phil Porter, a real Madison treasure. I'd like to add a dose of reality to Phil's story and the stories of hundreds in the same boat.\par \par \uc2 I am the long-term president of Integrated Community Work, a supported employment agency that has worked with Porter for years. ICW and agencies like it provide job-related service to developmentally disabled adults, helping to ensure their lives are richer than they would have been years ago when, for instance, Porter was warehoused in large institutions.\par \par \uc2 In the past few years, supported employment agencies (and residential agencies, too) have suffered from horrific, county- imposed, budget cuts, resulting in growing unmet need in our area.\par \par \uc2 If the story about Phil Porter moved you (and how couldn't it?), drop a line to your county supervisor and to the Dane County executive as a way of giving Phil a pat on the back and making sure he can keep doing what he loves: making others happy.\par \par \uc2 - Joe Davis, Madison\par \par \uc2 Wood should donate salary to MADD\par \par \uc2 Rep. Jeff Wood has been convicted three times for driving under the influence. I spent years as a volunteer EMT and firefighter in rural Wisconsin, and I also worked in organ and tissue donation. I've seen firsthand the destruction people like Wood leave in their paths when they choose to drive under the influence.\par \par \uc2 Wood was elected to help govern Wisconsin and to keep us safe by enacting laws that protect us, such as Wisconsin Code 346.63, which prohibits people from driving under the influence of alcohol and other drugs. Wood ignored that law and endangered every Wisconsinite on the road.\par \par \uc2 That's why I'm unwilling to pay his salary with my tax dollars while he serves his sentence. By my calculations, he'll earn around $6,000 while serving his 45-day sentence. Why should I pay him my hard-earned dollars while he's serving time for endangering my safety by driving under the influence?\par \par \uc2 I demand that he donate the $6,000 he'll earn while being punished for his third drunken driving offense to Mothers Against Drunk Driving or a similar program.\par \par \uc2 - Chris Truitt, DeForest\par \par \uc2 Support needed for fine arts in schools\par \par \uc2 I have long admired the fine work done by Madison Symphony Orchestra's Tyrone and Janet Greive in this area for so many years. I thank them for their efforts.\par \par \uc2 As Greive noted in his Friday guest column, the ability level of college orchestras, including those at UW-Madison, has become very high. The directors are also wonderful - I've been watching the exemplary work of orchestra director James Smith and choir professor Beverly Taylor with the university orchestras for years, and recommend that readers attend upcoming university opera and choir concerts.\par \par \uc2 Growth in the quality and number of public school orchestra programs and youth orchestras began after World War II, along with a move toward a more diverse curricular program, based on growing knowledge of human learning.\par \par \uc2 However, with the current economic problems we face, school arts programs are in jeopardy. The big thing about the cuts this time is that they are not scare tactics or teachers' union "bargaining" moves. These cuts are real, and may be permanent.\par \par \uc2 America has bailed out greedy banks with executives making multi- millions per year, but it can't seem to support fine arts in the schools, much less education in general, the way it should. How shameful and ignorant this is.\par \par \uc2 - Edward Reich, Janesville\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020100429e64s00011\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 FAITH & VALUES\par \uc2 THE CAP TIMES\par {\*\bkmkstart toc45}{\*\bkmkend toc45}\b \uc2 EXPLOITATION OF AREA'S IMMIGRANTS IS SHAMEFUL\b0\par\par\uc2 Phil Haslanger   \par \uc2 Phil Haslanger\par \uc2 594 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 February 2010\par \uc2 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal\par \uc2 XWST\par \uc2 ALL\par 34\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 \u169\'00\'A9 2010 The Capital Times & Wisconsin State Journal. Provided by ProQuest Information and Learning. All Rights Reserved.   \par \par \uc2 Exploitation of area's immigrants is shameful It's not a good season to be an \uc2 illegal immigrant\uc2  in America.\par \par \uc2 Not that it's ever a particularly good season for illegal immigrants. America is not alone in the world in its hostility toward immigrants and in our history we have done better than many nations in creating pathways for immigrants to become part of our society. But now, with unemployment continuing at high rates, it is easy to engender even harsher feelings toward immigrants than at other times - especially if they are here without legal standing.\par \par \uc2 But this is more than a legal issue. It is a moral issue about how human beings treat each other.\par \par \uc2 Despite President Obama's passing reference in his State of the Union speech to immigration reform, the political realities make such reform highly unlikely this year, leaving those who have been here for a long time without documentation as vulnerable as ever.\par \par \uc2 I'm not just talking about vulnerability to deportation. I'm talking about their vulnerability to economic exploitation - yes, right here in the Madison area. I'm talking about their vulnerability to a national system of immigration jails that is often Kafkaesque - a system that the nation tolerates because we find it so easy to dismiss people who risk much to support their families as simply being foreign lawbreakers.\par \par \uc2 There are numerous religious groups in this country that continue both to care for immigrants on a personal basis and to advocate for reforms that will make this whole system more humane. Within the Jewish and Christian traditions, there are strong statements in their Scriptures about welcoming the alien, about treating the foreigner with respect and care - with understanding that all are equal in God's vision.\par \par \uc2 Rabbi Renee Bauer, who is director of the Interfaith Coalition for Worker Justice of South Central Wisconsin, talked recently about the workers, most of them Latino, who come into her office each and every day. "Most often they come in because they have not been paid for hours they have worked," she said. "They are forced to clock out and then continue working overtime without pay. Or they are fired and not paid for their last two weeks of work. Or they are contract workers and are just simply not paid."\par \par \uc2 Last month, the New York Times reported on the silence that surrounds the deaths of men and women in immigration jails. "For years, they went uncounted and unnamed in the public record," wrote reporter Nina Bernstein. In 2008, the Times got a list of the names of those who had died, but still could get very little information about who these people were or how they died.\par \par \uc2 Yes, I know when people come into this country illegally, they are taking on a certain amount of personal risk. They understand that they may well be sent back to their home country. But that does not justify the slurs they face from so many people in public debate, the exploitation by employers who use their labor and then cheat them out of wages because they have little recourse, or a penal system that treats them as cattle.\par \par \uc2 Across the centuries, nations all over the world have struggled with immigration. In the U.S., where the vast majority of us are descendants of immigrants, we surely can do better.\par \par \uc2 Phil Haslanger is pastor of Memorial United Church of Christ in Fitchburg. phaslanger@gmail.com.\par \par \uc2 Document XWST000020100204e6230000d\par }\par \b \uc2 Search Summary\b0\par \par  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx2000\clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx9360\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Text\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \li50\uc2 illegal immigrant \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx2000\clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx9360\row } \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx2000\clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx9360\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Date\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \li50\uc2 01/01/2010 to 12